{"timestamp": "2026-04-19T13:24:57.801373", "agent_name": "AstroDeepResearchAgent", "method_name": "load_cached_research", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "Cached research loaded from: deep_research_claude/Aspartic-Acid-Run1.txt", "user_message": "Config: deep_research_claude", "raw_response": "# Prebiotic synthesis of aspartic acid: routes, evidence, and open challenges\n\n**Aspartic acid ranks among the most metabolically central yet prebiotically elusive amino acids.** At least 10 distinct prebiotic routes have been proposed or demonstrated, ranging from HCN oligomer hydrolysis \u2014 where aspartate emerges as a major product \u2014 to metal-catalyzed transamination of oxaloacetate, which mimics the biological pathway but battles the rapid decarboxylation of its precursor. The core tension in prebiotic aspartate chemistry is that the most biologically relevant pathways (via oxaloacetate) face severe kinetic competition from degradation, while the most productive abiotic routes (HCN oligomerization, spark discharge) operate through entirely different mechanisms. This report synthesizes the full landscape of published research on prebiotic aspartate formation, organized to guide synthesis network design and pathway evaluation in an agentic AI system for prebiotic chemistry.\n\n---\n\n## Known prebiotic routes span at least 10 distinct pathways\n\n### Strecker synthesis\n\nThe classical Strecker route proceeds through aldehyde + NH\u2083 \u2192 imine (Schiff base), then imine + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-aminonitrile, and finally hydrolysis of the aminonitrile to the amino acid. For aspartate, this requires a **C3 aldehyde bearing a carboxyl group** (such as 3-oxopropanoic acid or a related functionalized aldehyde), making the Strecker route to aspartate less straightforward than for glycine or alanine. Miller (1957, *Biochim. Biophys. Acta* 23, 480) established that spark discharge amino acid synthesis proceeds via this Strecker mechanism in the aqueous phase. Conditions are aqueous solution, **pH 7\u20139, room temperature to moderate heat**, with reaction times of hours to days. The prebiotic availability of the specific C4 aldehyde precursor for aspartate remains poorly constrained, representing a significant gap in this pathway.\n\n### Miller-Urey spark discharge\n\nMiller's original 1953 experiment (*Science* 117, 528) used CH\u2084 (200 torr), NH\u2083 (200 torr), H\u2082 (100 torr), and H\u2082O with Tesla coil spark discharge for one week. Aspartic acid was tentatively identified as spot #1 on the 2D paper chromatogram, though Miller's more rigorous 1955 analysis (*JACS* 77, 2351) reclassified this spot as likely **iminodiacetic acid**. The yield of aspartate, when confirmed, was approximately **0.024% relative to carbon input** \u2014 far below glycine at ~2.1%.\n\nModern reanalysis of Miller's archived samples transformed our understanding. Johnson et al. (2008, *Science* 322, 404) reanalyzed volcanic apparatus vials using HPLC-ToF-MS, detecting **22 amino acids and 5 amines** including confirmed D,L-aspartate. Parker et al. (2011, *PNAS* 108, 5526) reanalyzed Miller's unpublished 1958 H\u2082S experiment (CH\u2084/NH\u2083/H\u2082S/CO\u2082 atmosphere), finding **23 amino acids and 4 amines** including 7 organosulfur compounds. Aspartate was present at relatively low abundances, and the H\u2082S experiment produced yields an **order of magnitude higher** than the classic apparatus for many amino acids. Cleaves et al. (2008, *Orig. Life Evol. Biosph.* 38, 105) showed that adding oxidation inhibitors (pyrite, ascorbic acid, FeSO\u2084) to neutral atmosphere (CO\u2082/N\u2082) spark discharge experiments boosted amino acid yields by factors of **2\u2013100\u00d7**.\n\n### HCN oligomerization \u2014 the most productive route for aspartate\n\nHCN oligomerization followed by hydrolysis is the single most productive prebiotic route specifically for aspartate. Ferris, Donner & Lobo (1974, *J. Mol. Evol.* 3, 225) demonstrated that the **major amino acids** released on hydrolysis of HCN oligomers were **glycine, aspartate, and diaminosuccinic acid** \u2014 making aspartate a dominant product rather than a trace component. Ferris et al. (1978, *J. Mol. Evol.* 11, 293) confirmed this using 0.1 M HCN solutions at pH 9.2, where oligomers form over days to weeks and yield amino acids upon acid hydrolysis (6N HCl, 110\u00b0C, 24h). Matthews & Moser (1966, *PNAS* 56, 1087) independently detected glycine, alanine, and aspartic acid from HCN polymerization in aqueous ammonia. Frozen HCN solutions (\u221220 to \u221278\u00b0C) concentrated at the eutectic point (~10 M HCN at \u221223.4\u00b0C) also produce aspartate upon oligomer hydrolysis (Miyakawa, Cleaves & Miller, 2002, *Orig. Life Evol. Biosph.* 32, 195). The mechanism likely involves **5-carboxymethylidenehydantoin**, a cyclic intermediate specifically related to aspartate identified in HCN oligomer mixtures.\n\n### Cyanoacetylene route\n\nSanchez, Ferris & Orgel (1966, *Science* 154, 784) showed that cyanoacetylene (HC\u2261C-C\u2261N) \u2014 a major nitrogen-containing product of electric discharge in CH\u2084/N\u2082 mixtures (up to 8.4% of HCN yield) \u2014 reacts with HCN and NH\u2083 in aqueous solution at **pH ~9, room temperature** to produce **aspartic acid, asparagine, and cytosine**. This C\u2083 + C\u2081 coupling pathway is distinct from Strecker chemistry. However, cyanoacetylene production is suppressed when NH\u2083 or H\u2082S are present in the discharge, and Shapiro (1999, *PNAS*) questioned its abundance under more realistic CO\u2082/N\u2082 atmospheres.\n\n### Bucherer-Bergs pathway via \u03b1-keto acids \u2014 a key recent discovery\n\nPulletikurti, Yadav, Springsteen & Krishnamurthy (2022, *Nature Chemistry* 14, 1142) demonstrated that \u03b1-keto acids react with cyanide and ammonia sources via the **Bucherer-Bergs pathway** (not classical Strecker) to form amino acids. Specifically, **oxaloacetate + NaCN + NH\u2084HCO\u2083** produces aspartate via an **N-carbamoyl aspartate** intermediate. This route simultaneously generates **dihydroorotate**, directly paralleling biochemical pyrimidine nucleobase synthesis and elegantly linking amino acid and nucleotide pathways. Conditions are aqueous solution at room temperature to mild heating, neutral to slightly basic pH. This discovery bridges the gap between prebiotic Strecker chemistry (aldehyde-based) and biological metabolism (\u03b1-keto-acid-based).\n\n### Transamination of oxaloacetate\n\nHarrison, Webb, Rammu & Lane (2023, *Life* 13, 1177) published the most focused study on prebiotic aspartate synthesis via transamination. Cu\u00b2\u207a-catalyzed transamination of oxaloacetate by pyridoxamine achieved **~5% yield of aspartate within 1 hour** (160\u2013258 \u00b5M), operating across pH 6\u201310, 25\u201370\u00b0C, and ambient to high pressure. Metal ions tested included Cu\u00b2\u207a (best), Fe\u00b3\u207a, Mn\u00b2\u207a, and Co\u00b2\u207a, at **5\u201310 mM reactants, 50 mM NH\u2084HCO\u2083 buffer, 1 mM catalyst**. Mayer, Kaur, Rauscher & Moran (2021, *JACS* 143, 19099) and Dherbassy, Mayer, Muchowska & Moran (2023, *JACS* 145, 13357) provided kinetic and mechanistic details for non-enzymatic metal-pyridoxal transamination. The critical finding: Cu\u00b2\u207a-catalyzed transamination can initially **outcompete** OAA decarboxylation, but sustained aspartate production requires continuous OAA regeneration.\n\n### Reductive amination of oxaloacetate\n\nThis biologically parallel route (OAA + NH\u2084\u207a + [H] \u2192 aspartate) has been tested with multiple reducing systems. Hafenbradl, Keller, W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user & Stetter (1995, *Tetrahedron Lett.* 36, 5179) used FeS + H\u2082S at 100\u00b0C under anaerobic conditions but obtained low yields. Critically, Barge, Flores et al. (2019, *PNAS* 116, 4828) tested reductive amination with mixed-valence Fe(II)/Fe(III) oxyhydroxides and found that **aspartic acid was NOT obtained from oxaloacetate** \u2014 the starting material converted entirely to pyruvate (via decarboxylation) and subsequently yielded alanine and lactate. Mayer & Moran (2022, *Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.* 61, e202212237) showed OAA has intermediate reactivity for reductive amination with NaBH\u2083CN, with a rate 1.7\u00d7 faster than glutamate formation from \u03b1-ketoglutarate \u2014 but OAA decarboxylation remains the dominant competing pathway.\n\n### Michael addition of ammonia to fumarate\n\nThe biological reaction (aspartase, EC 4.3.1.1) reversibly adds NH\u2083 to fumarate yielding L-aspartate (K_m \u2248 15\u201320 mM for NH\u2084\u207a). Non-enzymatically, this reaction is thermodynamically feasible under **alkaline conditions with high NH\u2083 concentrations** at elevated temperatures, but yields are very low without enzymatic catalysis. Fumarate itself can be produced prebiotically through several routes: photocatalytic reduction of oxaloacetate to malate on ZnS surfaces followed by dehydration (Guzman & Martin, 2008, *Int. J. Astrobiol.* 7, 271); non-enzymatic rTCA cycle analogs (Muchowska, Varma & Moran, 2020, *Chem. Rev.* 120, 7708); and detection in the Murchison meteorite.\n\n### Additional routes\n\nSeveral other pathways contribute to the prebiotic aspartate inventory. **Photochemical synthesis** by Sagan & Khare (1971, *Science* 173, 417) produced aspartate from UV irradiation of CH\u2084/C\u2082H\u2086/NH\u2083/H\u2082O/H\u2082S mixtures. Mu\u00f1oz Caro et al. (2002, *Nature* 416, 403) produced 16 amino acids including aspartate from UV irradiation of interstellar ice analogs. Fox & Windsor (1970, *Science* 170, 984) obtained aspartate from heated formaldehyde and ammonia mixtures. **Hydrothermal vent synthesis** has been demonstrated by Marshall (1994, *GCA* 58, 2099) and Hennet, Holm & Engel (1992), and Amend & Shock (1998, *Science* 281, 1659) calculated that amino acid synthesis including aspartate is thermodynamically favorable in **100\u00b0C moderately reduced hydrothermal solutions**. Varma, Muchowska & Moran detected aspartate from Fe\u2070-mediated CO\u2082 reduction at 30\u2013100\u00b0C, 35 bar with hydroxylamine as nitrogen source.\n\n---\n\n## Critical intermediates and the oxaloacetate instability problem\n\n### Oxaloacetate is the central but unstable nexus\n\nOxaloacetate (OAA) sits at the heart of multiple aspartate synthesis routes (transamination, reductive amination, Bucherer-Bergs) but is **notoriously unstable**. It decarboxylates to pyruvate + CO\u2082 with a half-life of approximately **1\u20132 hours at 25\u00b0C, neutral pH** (rate constant k = 8.9 \u00d7 10\u207b\u2077 s\u207b\u00b9; Guzman & Martin, 2008). This decarboxylation follows Arrhenius behavior: log(k) = 11.74 \u2212 4956/T. Divalent metal cations **accelerate** decarboxylation following the Irving-Williams series (Mg\u00b2\u207a < Mn\u00b2\u207a < Fe\u00b2\u207a < Co\u00b2\u207a < Ni\u00b2\u207a < Cu\u00b2\u207a < Zn\u00b2\u207a), creating a paradox where the same metals that catalyze transamination also promote degradation.\n\nPrebiotic OAA can form through several routes: pyruvate + glyoxylate reactions generating 4-hydroxy-2-ketoglutarate intermediates that undergo oxidative decarboxylation (Eschenmoser & Krishnamurthy, *Nat. Commun.* 2017); iron-mediated CO\u2082 fixation pathways (Muchowska et al., 2019, *Nature* 569, 104); and as a transient intermediate in non-enzymatic rTCA cycle analogs. CO\u2082-saturated Hadean ocean conditions might partially suppress decarboxylation by Le Chatelier's principle, though this remains experimentally unvalidated.\n\n### HCN oligomers, fumarate, and branching pathways\n\n**HCN oligomers** form the alternative major pathway to aspartate. The oligomerization cascade proceeds: HCN dimer (iminoacetonitrile) \u2192 trimer (aminomalononitrile, AMN) \u2192 tetramer (diaminomaleonitrile, DAMN) \u2192 higher polymers. The tetramer DAMN is a key branch-point molecule leading to both purines and amino acids. Oligomerization requires **[HCN] > 10\u207b\u00b2 M at pH ~9.2**, achievable through eutectic freezing concentration at \u221223.4\u00b0C.\n\n**Fumarate** connects to aspartate via Michael addition and serves as a node in the rTCA cycle network. It can form from malate dehydration, ZnS-photocatalyzed reduction products (Zhou & Guzman, 2016), and succinate oxidation. **Cyanoacetylene** provides a C\u2083 building block that couples with HCN and NH\u2083 to produce both aspartate and cytosine, representing a branch point linking amino acid and nucleobase synthesis. **Glyoxylate** serves as the central C\u2082 feedstock in protometabolic TCA analogs, connecting to OAA via aldol chemistry with pyruvate.\n\nAspartate itself is a critical **nodal metabolite** in modern biochemistry \u2014 the precursor for asparagine, lysine, methionine, threonine, isoleucine, all pyrimidine nucleotides, and contributions to purine synthesis. Harrison et al. (2023) describe it as essential to any \"minimal autotrophic protometabolism.\"\n\n---\n\n## Environmental conditions favor alkaline vents and surface pools\n\n### Alkaline hydrothermal vents offer the best thermodynamic window\n\n**Lost City-type alkaline vents** operate at **40\u201390\u00b0C, pH 9\u201311**, with copious H\u2082 from serpentinization, along with CH\u2084, formate, NH\u2083, and H\u2082S. The Russell/Martin hypothesis (Russell 1993; Martin & Russell 2007, *Phil. Trans. R. Soc. B*) proposes that FeS/NiS precipitate compartments at alkaline mounds created **pH gradients of ~3 units** \u2014 mimicking the proton-motive force in modern cells \u2014 where cool, slightly acidic CO\u2082-rich Hadean ocean (pH 5\u20136) met hot, reduced alkaline fluid. Kitadai (2015, *Orig. Life Evol. Biosph.* 45, 377) calculated that mixing CO\u2082-rich seawater with H\u2082-rich alkaline fluid creates energetically favorable conditions for amino acid synthesis at an optimum of **~50\u00b0C**. Preiner et al. (2020, *Nature Ecol. Evol.* 4, 534) demonstrated H\u2082-dependent primordial carbon metabolism using greigite and magnetite catalysts.\n\n**Black smoker vents** (up to 350\u2013400\u00b0C, pH 2\u20133) provide rich transition metal catalysis (pyrite, chalcopyrite, sphalerite) and the pyrite-pulled energy source (FeS + H\u2082S \u2192 FeS\u2082 + H\u2082; \u0394G = \u22129.2 kcal/mol). However, amino acids are **irreversibly destroyed above ~240\u00b0C** (Miller & Bada, 1988, *Nature* 334, 609; Bada et al., 1995). Aspartate is among the more oxidized amino acids (high Z_C value), making its synthesis **endergonic even at 100\u00b0C** in many hydrothermal fluid compositions according to Amend & Shock's calculations \u2014 though Kitadai showed that alkaline vent mixing zones create sufficiently steep chemical gradients to overcome this.\n\n### Surface pools and atmospheric considerations\n\nWet-dry cycling in volcanic hot spring pools (Damer & Deamer, 2020, *Astrobiology* 20, 429) provides **concentration through evaporation** (up to ~1000\u00d7 enrichment), UV energy input (much higher flux on early Earth without ozone, \u03bb > 200 nm), and thermal energy for condensation reactions during drying (20\u2013120\u00b0C). Deliquescent minerals mediate effective wet-dry cycles, achieving **21.2% oligomerization yields** versus 3.5% for non-deliquescent controls after 10 cycles (Campbell & Bracher, 2019, *Nat. Commun.* 10, 4508).\n\nThe early Earth atmosphere composition remains debated. Current consensus favors a **weakly reducing to neutral atmosphere** (CO\u2082 + N\u2082 dominant, with smaller amounts of H\u2082O, H\u2082, and traces of CH\u2084/NH\u2083) rather than the strongly reducing mixture used in Miller's original experiment. Transient H\u2082-rich atmospheres after large asteroid impacts could periodically create conditions conducive to Miller-Urey synthesis. Localized reducing environments near volcanic plumes can drive amino acid synthesis even under a weakly reducing global atmosphere.\n\n---\n\n## Mineral catalysts play distinct roles at each reaction step\n\n### Iron-sulfur minerals bridge geochemistry and biochemistry\n\n**Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)** has an inverse thiospinel structure with cubic Fe\u2084S\u2084 units that are structurally identical to [4Fe-4S] clusters in ferredoxins and CODH/ACS enzymes. It is thermodynamically stable (confirmed by Navrotsky group, *PNAS* 2020), catalyzes CO\u2082 reduction to small organics, and can promote the CO\u2082 fixation steps that generate oxaloacetate precursors. Santos-Carballal et al. (2018, *Phil. Trans. R. Soc. A*) modeled CO\u2082 reactivity on greigite surfaces by DFT.\n\n**Pyrite (FeS\u2082)** provides the thermodynamic driving force for W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user's surface metabolism (FeS + H\u2082S \u2192 FeS\u2082 + H\u2082; \u0394G = \u22129.2 kcal/mol). Hafenbradl et al. (1995) demonstrated amino acid synthesis by reductive amination of \u03b1-oxo acids coupled to pyrite formation. A remarkable recent finding: natural pyrite **photocatalytically drives reductive amination** of keto acids with **14.5\u201342.4% enantiomeric excess for D-amino acids** via wavy surface atom arrangements (*Nat. Commun.* 2024).\n\n**Mackinawite (FeS)** \u2014 a layered iron sulfide and precursor to greigite \u2014 reduces CO\u2082 to CO at >300\u00b0C and catalyzes H\u2082-driven CO\u2082 reduction to methanol at **80\u2013120\u00b0C** when doped with Mn (5\u00d7 enhancement) or illuminated with UV-visible light (*Nat. Commun.* 2024). Its semiconductor properties enable photo-assisted catalysis relevant to the earliest steps of carbon fixation.\n\n### Clay minerals concentrate and catalyze\n\n**Montmorillonite** catalyzes oligomerization of activated nucleotides to 40\u201355-mers (Ferris & Ertem, 1992, *Science* 257, 1387), amino acid polymerization under wet-dry cycling (Lahav et al., 1978, *Science* 201, 67), and specifically the formation of glycyl-aspartic acid dipeptides from glycine and aspartate at **85 \u00b1 5\u00b0C** (Kalra/Pant et al., *Int. J. Astrobiol.*). Notably, linear and cyclic aspartate-only peptides were NOT formed, indicating distinct reactivity for aspartate on clay surfaces. Montmorillonite interlayers create **nano-confined environments** distinct from bulk solution, providing locally anhydrous conditions that protect from hydrolysis.\n\n### Photocatalysts and transition metal ions\n\n**ZnS** (sphalerite, band gap ~3.6 eV) photocatalyzes **reversible amination of \u03b1-keto acids** under UV (~360 nm) irradiation, including oxaloacetate \u2192 aspartate (Wang et al., 2011\u20132013; Guzman & Martin, 2008). Chiral mesostructured ZnS can drive CO\u2082 + NH\u2083 \u2192 amino acids with **>96% enantiomeric excess** via spin-polarized electron transfer. **TiO\u2082** (rutile/anatase, band gap 3.0\u20133.2 eV) enhances amino acid polymerization (23% increase with anatase) and converts formamide to nucleoside bases under UV.\n\n**Cu\u00b2\u207a** is the most efficient non-enzymatic transamination catalyst (Harrison et al., 2023). **Fe\u2070** reduces CO\u2082 to pyruvate and acetate at 30\u2013100\u00b0C, 35 bar, generating aspartate when hydroxylamine is present as nitrogen source (Varma et al., 2018, *Nat. Ecol. Evol.*). **Ni\u2070** catalyzes a prebiotic Krebs cycle analog generating amino acids from H\u2082 + NH\u2083 (Kaur et al., 2024, *Chem* 10, 1528). FeS/NiS co-catalyzes thioester synthesis (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1997).\n\n---\n\n## Meteoritic and extraterrestrial evidence confirms abiotic aspartate formation\n\nAspartate is consistently detected in carbonaceous chondrites. In the **Murchison meteorite**, modern analyses by Glavin et al. report **L-aspartate at 1.7 \u00b1 0.1 nmol/g** and **D-aspartate at 0.95 \u00b1 0.04 nmol/g**. The **Tagish Lake meteorite** shows remarkably large L-enantiomeric excesses of **~60% for aspartate**, confirmed as extraterrestrial by \u03b4\u00b9\u00b3C enrichments (+24\u2030 D, +29\u2030 L). The Aguas Zarcas meteorite shows **~28% L-ee** for aspartate. Chimiak et al. (2022, *Geochim. Cosmochim. Acta* 321, 78) used position-specific carbon isotope analysis of Murchison aspartate and found signatures consistent with Strecker synthesis origins. Over **90 amino acids** have been identified in Murchison, with glycine most abundant and aspartate present at lower but significant concentrations. Mu\u00f1oz Caro et al. (2002, *Nature* 416, 403) produced 16 amino acids including aspartate from UV irradiation of interstellar ice analogs (H\u2082O/CO\u2082/CO/CH\u2083OH/NH\u2083), demonstrating that extraterrestrial aspartate formation is experimentally reproducible.\n\n---\n\n## Six major unresolved challenges constrain prebiotic aspartate synthesis\n\n### The oxaloacetate decarboxylation race\n\nThe single greatest bottleneck is that **OAA decarboxylates to pyruvate faster than it can be aminated to aspartate** under most tested conditions. Barge et al. (2019) showed this definitively: iron oxyhydroxide experiments yielded alanine (from pyruvate, the OAA decomposition product) rather than aspartate. The ~5% transamination yield achieved by Harrison et al. (2023) requires the reaction to outpace decarboxylation in the first hour, but sustained production demands continuous OAA regeneration \u2014 something not yet demonstrated in a cyclic, self-sustaining manner. The glyoxylate-mediated OAA generation pathway (Eschenmoser & Krishnamurthy, *Nat. Commun.* 2017) works but requires relatively high concentrations and H\u2082O\u2082 as oxidant.\n\n### Chirality remains without a definitive solution\n\nAll major prebiotic routes produce **racemic aspartate**. Known symmetry-breaking mechanisms include circularly polarized UV light (~1\u20132% ee in aminonitrile precursors), chiral mineral surfaces, and kinetic resolution via dipeptide-mediated transamination (Dherbassy/Moran group, *PNAS* 2024). The most aspartate-specific mechanism is **differential adsorption on calcite**: Hazen et al. (2001, *PNAS* 98, 5487) showed D-aspartate forms 3 strong bonds on calcite (214) surfaces (~8 kcal/mol lower energy than L-aspartate with 2 bonds), enabling chiral separation on mirror-related scalenohedral faces. Aspartate's ability to form **conglomerate enantiopure crystals** (unlike alanine's racemic crystals) provides a plausible amplification mechanism. Racemization half-lives are approximately **3,500\u201315,000 years at 25\u00b0C** (Bada & Schroeder), with aspartate racemizing faster than most amino acids via a succinimide intermediate.\n\n### The concentration problem\n\nEstimated steady-state amino acid concentrations in the prebiotic ocean are ~10\u207b\u2079 M \u2014 orders of magnitude below the mM concentrations used in most published experiments. Strecker synthesis requires [HCN] > 10\u207b\u00b2 M; peptide bond formation needs mM amino acid concentrations. Solutions include evaporative concentration in pools (up to 1000\u00d7), eutectic freezing (HCN concentrates to ~10 M at \u221223.4\u00b0C), mineral adsorption, aerosol enrichment, and submarine vent gradients. Whether protometabolic cycles can operate at ocean-relevant dilutions remains largely untested.\n\n### Thermal stability limits viable environments\n\nAspartate decomposes via deamination (\u2192 fumarate + NH\u2083) and decarboxylation (\u2192 \u03b2-alanine + CO\u2082). At **240\u2013250\u00b0C**, decomposition is rapid and irreversible (Miller & Bada, 1988). Activation energies range from **88.5\u2013137.4 kJ/mol** for amino acid decomposition at 160\u2013240\u00b0C (Hou et al., 2024, *Sci. Rep.*). At 100\u00b0C, half-lives are on the order of thousands of years, making alkaline vents (40\u201390\u00b0C) far more favorable than black smokers (>300\u00b0C). Solid-state decomposition occurs at ~270\u00b0C (\u0394H_f = \u2212973 kJ/mol). Protection by mineral adsorption, vesicle encapsulation, and peptide incorporation can extend stability.\n\n### Competing reactions and pathway selectivity\n\nHCN polymerization converts the vast majority of starting material to intractable \"tar\" rather than useful amino acids. Maillard-type reactions between amino acids and sugars produce complex brown polymers. Aspartate undergoes cyclization to succinimide intermediates, leading to \u03b2-aspartate isomers and accelerated racemization. In aqueous solution, hydrolysis of peptide bonds overwhelmingly outcompetes condensation at hydrothermal temperatures.\n\n### Key experimentally undemonstrated steps\n\nThe following remain as the weakest links in proposed pathways:\n\n- Sustained OAA production from CO\u2082 fixation under prebiotically plausible conditions without enzymes or ATP\n- A complete, self-sustaining non-enzymatic rTCA cycle with turnover (9 of 11 intermediates demonstrated individually by Muchowska et al. 2019, but not as a running cycle)\n- Prebiotic synthesis of pyridoxamine, required for the most efficient transamination route\n- Operation of any protometabolic aspartate synthesis at ocean-relevant dilute concentrations\n- Experimental validation that Hadean CO\u2082 saturation suppresses OAA decarboxylation\n\n---\n\n## Conclusion: converging pathways, persistent gaps\n\nThe prebiotic synthesis landscape for aspartic acid is richer than often appreciated, with HCN oligomer hydrolysis and the Bucherer-Bergs pathway from \u03b1-keto acids standing out as the most productive and most elegant routes, respectively. **HCN oligomerization uniquely yields aspartate as a major product** alongside glycine \u2014 not a trace component \u2014 making it the most efficient single route. The **Bucherer-Bergs pathway** (Pulletikurti et al., 2022) simultaneously generates aspartate and dihydroorotate, linking amino acid and pyrimidine nucleotide synthesis in a single reaction network. For network design in an agentic AI system, these two pathways should be prioritized as primary aspartate sources.\n\nThe protometabolic routes via oxaloacetate (transamination, reductive amination) face the fundamental kinetic barrier of OAA decarboxylation but achieve biological relevance through Cu\u00b2\u207a/pyridoxamine catalysis at ~5% yields in one hour. The most plausible integrated scenario combines **alkaline vent CO\u2082 fixation** (Fe/Ni catalysts, 40\u201390\u00b0C) to generate keto acid intermediates, **rapid transamination or Bucherer-Bergs conversion** before OAA degrades, and **transport to lower-temperature environments** (surface pools, clay surfaces) for concentration via wet-dry cycling and chiral selection on calcite. The three unresolved challenges that most constrain pathway viability are OAA stabilization, operation at realistic dilutions, and the origin of homochirality \u2014 each representing a frontier where new experimental work could transform our understanding of how this metabolically essential amino acid first emerged on the prebiotic Earth.", "parsed_response": {"source": "deep_research_claude/Aspartic-Acid-Run1.txt", "config": "deep_research_claude", "length": 25101}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 0.0, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-19T13:24:57.802570", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Aspartic-Acid\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof Aspartic-Acid. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n# Prebiotic synthesis of aspartic acid: routes, evidence, and open challenges\n\n**Aspartic acid ranks among the most metabolically central yet prebiotically elusive amino acids.** At least 10 distinct prebiotic routes have been proposed or demonstrated, ranging from HCN oligomer hydrolysis \u2014 where aspartate emerges as a major product \u2014 to metal-catalyzed transamination of oxaloacetate, which mimics the biological pathway but battles the rapid decarboxylation of its precursor. The core tension in prebiotic aspartate chemistry is that the most biologically relevant pathways (via oxaloacetate) face severe kinetic competition from degradation, while the most productive abiotic routes (HCN oligomerization, spark discharge) operate through entirely different mechanisms. This report synthesizes the full landscape of published research on prebiotic aspartate formation, organized to guide synthesis network design and pathway evaluation in an agentic AI system for prebiotic chemistry.\n\n---\n\n## Known prebiotic routes span at least 10 distinct pathways\n\n### Strecker synthesis\n\nThe classical Strecker route proceeds through aldehyde + NH\u2083 \u2192 imine (Schiff base), then imine + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-aminonitrile, and finally hydrolysis of the aminonitrile to the amino acid. For aspartate, this requires a **C3 aldehyde bearing a carboxyl group** (such as 3-oxopropanoic acid or a related functionalized aldehyde), making the Strecker route to aspartate less straightforward than for glycine or alanine. Miller (1957, *Biochim. Biophys. Acta* 23, 480) established that spark discharge amino acid synthesis proceeds via this Strecker mechanism in the aqueous phase. Conditions are aqueous solution, **pH 7\u20139, room temperature to moderate heat**, with reaction times of hours to days. The prebiotic availability of the specific C4 aldehyde precursor for aspartate remains poorly constrained, representing a significant gap in this pathway.\n\n### Miller-Urey spark discharge\n\nMiller's original 1953 experiment (*Science* 117, 528) used CH\u2084 (200 torr), NH\u2083 (200 torr), H\u2082 (100 torr), and H\u2082O with Tesla coil spark discharge for one week. Aspartic acid was tentatively identified as spot #1 on the 2D paper chromatogram, though Miller's more rigorous 1955 analysis (*JACS* 77, 2351) reclassified this spot as likely **iminodiacetic acid**. The yield of aspartate, when confirmed, was approximately **0.024% relative to carbon input** \u2014 far below glycine at ~2.1%.\n\nModern reanalysis of Miller's archived samples transformed our understanding. Johnson et al. (2008, *Science* 322, 404) reanalyzed volcanic apparatus vials using HPLC-ToF-MS, detecting **22 amino acids and 5 amines** including confirmed D,L-aspartate. Parker et al. (2011, *PNAS* 108, 5526) reanalyzed Miller's unpublished 1958 H\u2082S experiment (CH\u2084/NH\u2083/H\u2082S/CO\u2082 atmosphere), finding **23 amino acids and 4 amines** including 7 organosulfur compounds. Aspartate was present at relatively low abundances, and the H\u2082S experiment produced yields an **order of magnitude higher** than the classic apparatus for many amino acids. Cleaves et al. (2008, *Orig. Life Evol. Biosph.* 38, 105) showed that adding oxidation inhibitors (pyrite, ascorbic acid, FeSO\u2084) to neutral atmosphere (CO\u2082/N\u2082) spark discharge experiments boosted amino acid yields by factors of **2\u2013100\u00d7**.\n\n### HCN oligomerization \u2014 the most productive route for aspartate\n\nHCN oligomerization followed by hydrolysis is the single most productive prebiotic route specifically for aspartate. Ferris, Donner & Lobo (1974, *J. Mol. Evol.* 3, 225) demonstrated that the **major amino acids** released on hydrolysis of HCN oligomers were **glycine, aspartate, and diaminosuccinic acid** \u2014 making aspartate a dominant product rather than a trace component. Ferris et al. (1978, *J. Mol. Evol.* 11, 293) confirmed this using 0.1 M HCN solutions at pH 9.2, where oligomers form over days to weeks and yield amino acids upon acid hydrolysis (6N HCl, 110\u00b0C, 24h). Matthews & Moser (1966, *PNAS* 56, 1087) independently detected glycine, alanine, and aspartic acid from HCN polymerization in aqueous ammonia. Frozen HCN solutions (\u221220 to \u221278\u00b0C) concentrated at the eutectic point (~10 M HCN at \u221223.4\u00b0C) also produce aspartate upon oligomer hydrolysis (Miyakawa, Cleaves & Miller, 2002, *Orig. Life Evol. Biosph.* 32, 195). The mechanism likely involves **5-carboxymethylidenehydantoin**, a cyclic intermediate specifically related to aspartate identified in HCN oligomer mixtures.\n\n### Cyanoacetylene route\n\nSanchez, Ferris & Orgel (1966, *Science* 154, 784) showed that cyanoacetylene (HC\u2261C-C\u2261N) \u2014 a major nitrogen-containing product of electric discharge in CH\u2084/N\u2082 mixtures (up to 8.4% of HCN yield) \u2014 reacts with HCN and NH\u2083 in aqueous solution at **pH ~9, room temperature** to produce **aspartic acid, asparagine, and cytosine**. This C\u2083 + C\u2081 coupling pathway is distinct from Strecker chemistry. However, cyanoacetylene production is suppressed when NH\u2083 or H\u2082S are present in the discharge, and Shapiro (1999, *PNAS*) questioned its abundance under more realistic CO\u2082/N\u2082 atmospheres.\n\n### Bucherer-Bergs pathway via \u03b1-keto acids \u2014 a key recent discovery\n\nPulletikurti, Yadav, Springsteen & Krishnamurthy (2022, *Nature Chemistry* 14, 1142) demonstrated that \u03b1-keto acids react with cyanide and ammonia sources via the **Bucherer-Bergs pathway** (not classical Strecker) to form amino acids. Specifically, **oxaloacetate + NaCN + NH\u2084HCO\u2083** produces aspartate via an **N-carbamoyl aspartate** intermediate. This route simultaneously generates **dihydroorotate**, directly paralleling biochemical pyrimidine nucleobase synthesis and elegantly linking amino acid and nucleotide pathways. Conditions are aqueous solution at room temperature to mild heating, neutral to slightly basic pH. This discovery bridges the gap between prebiotic Strecker chemistry (aldehyde-based) and biological metabolism (\u03b1-keto-acid-based).\n\n### Transamination of oxaloacetate\n\nHarrison, Webb, Rammu & Lane (2023, *Life* 13, 1177) published the most focused study on prebiotic aspartate synthesis via transamination. Cu\u00b2\u207a-catalyzed transamination of oxaloacetate by pyridoxamine achieved **~5% yield of aspartate within 1 hour** (160\u2013258 \u00b5M), operating across pH 6\u201310, 25\u201370\u00b0C, and ambient to high pressure. Metal ions tested included Cu\u00b2\u207a (best), Fe\u00b3\u207a, Mn\u00b2\u207a, and Co\u00b2\u207a, at **5\u201310 mM reactants, 50 mM NH\u2084HCO\u2083 buffer, 1 mM catalyst**. Mayer, Kaur, Rauscher & Moran (2021, *JACS* 143, 19099) and Dherbassy, Mayer, Muchowska & Moran (2023, *JACS* 145, 13357) provided kinetic and mechanistic details for non-enzymatic metal-pyridoxal transamination. The critical finding: Cu\u00b2\u207a-catalyzed transamination can initially **outcompete** OAA decarboxylation, but sustained aspartate production requires continuous OAA regeneration.\n\n### Reductive amination of oxaloacetate\n\nThis biologically parallel route (OAA + NH\u2084\u207a + [H] \u2192 aspartate) has been tested with multiple reducing systems. Hafenbradl, Keller, W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user & Stetter (1995, *Tetrahedron Lett.* 36, 5179) used FeS + H\u2082S at 100\u00b0C under anaerobic conditions but obtained low yields. Critically, Barge, Flores et al. (2019, *PNAS* 116, 4828) tested reductive amination with mixed-valence Fe(II)/Fe(III) oxyhydroxides and found that **aspartic acid was NOT obtained from oxaloacetate** \u2014 the starting material converted entirely to pyruvate (via decarboxylation) and subsequently yielded alanine and lactate. Mayer & Moran (2022, *Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.* 61, e202212237) showed OAA has intermediate reactivity for reductive amination with NaBH\u2083CN, with a rate 1.7\u00d7 faster than glutamate formation from \u03b1-ketoglutarate \u2014 but OAA decarboxylation remains the dominant competing pathway.\n\n### Michael addition of ammonia to fumarate\n\nThe biological reaction (aspartase, EC 4.3.1.1) reversibly adds NH\u2083 to fumarate yielding L-aspartate (K_m \u2248 15\u201320 mM for NH\u2084\u207a). Non-enzymatically, this reaction is thermodynamically feasible under **alkaline conditions with high NH\u2083 concentrations** at elevated temperatures, but yields are very low without enzymatic catalysis. Fumarate itself can be produced prebiotically through several routes: photocatalytic reduction of oxaloacetate to malate on ZnS surfaces followed by dehydration (Guzman & Martin, 2008, *Int. J. Astrobiol.* 7, 271); non-enzymatic rTCA cycle analogs (Muchowska, Varma & Moran, 2020, *Chem. Rev.* 120, 7708); and detection in the Murchison meteorite.\n\n### Additional routes\n\nSeveral other pathways contribute to the prebiotic aspartate inventory. **Photochemical synthesis** by Sagan & Khare (1971, *Science* 173, 417) produced aspartate from UV irradiation of CH\u2084/C\u2082H\u2086/NH\u2083/H\u2082O/H\u2082S mixtures. Mu\u00f1oz Caro et al. (2002, *Nature* 416, 403) produced 16 amino acids including aspartate from UV irradiation of interstellar ice analogs. Fox & Windsor (1970, *Science* 170, 984) obtained aspartate from heated formaldehyde and ammonia mixtures. **Hydrothermal vent synthesis** has been demonstrated by Marshall (1994, *GCA* 58, 2099) and Hennet, Holm & Engel (1992), and Amend & Shock (1998, *Science* 281, 1659) calculated that amino acid synthesis including aspartate is thermodynamically favorable in **100\u00b0C moderately reduced hydrothermal solutions**. Varma, Muchowska & Moran detected aspartate from Fe\u2070-mediated CO\u2082 reduction at 30\u2013100\u00b0C, 35 bar with hydroxylamine as nitrogen source.\n\n---\n\n## Critical intermediates and the oxaloacetate instability problem\n\n### Oxaloacetate is the central but unstable nexus\n\nOxaloacetate (OAA) sits at the heart of multiple aspartate synthesis routes (transamination, reductive amination, Bucherer-Bergs) but is **notoriously unstable**. It decarboxylates to pyruvate + CO\u2082 with a half-life of approximately **1\u20132 hours at 25\u00b0C, neutral pH** (rate constant k = 8.9 \u00d7 10\u207b\u2077 s\u207b\u00b9; Guzman & Martin, 2008). This decarboxylation follows Arrhenius behavior: log(k) = 11.74 \u2212 4956/T. Divalent metal cations **accelerate** decarboxylation following the Irving-Williams series (Mg\u00b2\u207a < Mn\u00b2\u207a < Fe\u00b2\u207a < Co\u00b2\u207a < Ni\u00b2\u207a < Cu\u00b2\u207a < Zn\u00b2\u207a), creating a paradox where the same metals that catalyze transamination also promote degradation.\n\nPrebiotic OAA can form through several routes: pyruvate + glyoxylate reactions generating 4-hydroxy-2-ketoglutarate intermediates that undergo oxidative decarboxylation (Eschenmoser & Krishnamurthy, *Nat. Commun.* 2017); iron-mediated CO\u2082 fixation pathways (Muchowska et al., 2019, *Nature* 569, 104); and as a transient intermediate in non-enzymatic rTCA cycle analogs. CO\u2082-saturated Hadean ocean conditions might partially suppress decarboxylation by Le Chatelier's principle, though this remains experimentally unvalidated.\n\n### HCN oligomers, fumarate, and branching pathways\n\n**HCN oligomers** form the alternative major pathway to aspartate. The oligomerization cascade proceeds: HCN dimer (iminoacetonitrile) \u2192 trimer (aminomalononitrile, AMN) \u2192 tetramer (diaminomaleonitrile, DAMN) \u2192 higher polymers. The tetramer DAMN is a key branch-point molecule leading to both purines and amino acids. Oligomerization requires **[HCN] > 10\u207b\u00b2 M at pH ~9.2**, achievable through eutectic freezing concentration at \u221223.4\u00b0C.\n\n**Fumarate** connects to aspartate via Michael addition and serves as a node in the rTCA cycle network. It can form from malate dehydration, ZnS-photocatalyzed reduction products (Zhou & Guzman, 2016), and succinate oxidation. **Cyanoacetylene** provides a C\u2083 building block that couples with HCN and NH\u2083 to produce both aspartate and cytosine, representing a branch point linking amino acid and nucleobase synthesis. **Glyoxylate** serves as the central C\u2082 feedstock in protometabolic TCA analogs, connecting to OAA via aldol chemistry with pyruvate.\n\nAspartate itself is a critical **nodal metabolite** in modern biochemistry \u2014 the precursor for asparagine, lysine, methionine, threonine, isoleucine, all pyrimidine nucleotides, and contributions to purine synthesis. Harrison et al. (2023) describe it as essential to any \"minimal autotrophic protometabolism.\"\n\n---\n\n## Environmental conditions favor alkaline vents and surface pools\n\n### Alkaline hydrothermal vents offer the best thermodynamic window\n\n**Lost City-type alkaline vents** operate at **40\u201390\u00b0C, pH 9\u201311**, with copious H\u2082 from serpentinization, along with CH\u2084, formate, NH\u2083, and H\u2082S. The Russell/Martin hypothesis (Russell 1993; Martin & Russell 2007, *Phil. Trans. R. Soc. B*) proposes that FeS/NiS precipitate compartments at alkaline mounds created **pH gradients of ~3 units** \u2014 mimicking the proton-motive force in modern cells \u2014 where cool, slightly acidic CO\u2082-rich Hadean ocean (pH 5\u20136) met hot, reduced alkaline fluid. Kitadai (2015, *Orig. Life Evol. Biosph.* 45, 377) calculated that mixing CO\u2082-rich seawater with H\u2082-rich alkaline fluid creates energetically favorable conditions for amino acid synthesis at an optimum of **~50\u00b0C**. Preiner et al. (2020, *Nature Ecol. Evol.* 4, 534) demonstrated H\u2082-dependent primordial carbon metabolism using greigite and magnetite catalysts.\n\n**Black smoker vents** (up to 350\u2013400\u00b0C, pH 2\u20133) provide rich transition metal catalysis (pyrite, chalcopyrite, sphalerite) and the pyrite-pulled energy source (FeS + H\u2082S \u2192 FeS\u2082 + H\u2082; \u0394G = \u22129.2 kcal/mol). However, amino acids are **irreversibly destroyed above ~240\u00b0C** (Miller & Bada, 1988, *Nature* 334, 609; Bada et al., 1995). Aspartate is among the more oxidized amino acids (high Z_C value), making its synthesis **endergonic even at 100\u00b0C** in many hydrothermal fluid compositions according to Amend & Shock's calculations \u2014 though Kitadai showed that alkaline vent mixing zones create sufficiently steep chemical gradients to overcome this.\n\n### Surface pools and atmospheric considerations\n\nWet-dry cycling in volcanic hot spring pools (Damer & Deamer, 2020, *Astrobiology* 20, 429) provides **concentration through evaporation** (up to ~1000\u00d7 enrichment), UV energy input (much higher flux on early Earth without ozone, \u03bb > 200 nm), and thermal energy for condensation reactions during drying (20\u2013120\u00b0C). Deliquescent minerals mediate effective wet-dry cycles, achieving **21.2% oligomerization yields** versus 3.5% for non-deliquescent controls after 10 cycles (Campbell & Bracher, 2019, *Nat. Commun.* 10, 4508).\n\nThe early Earth atmosphere composition remains debated. Current consensus favors a **weakly reducing to neutral atmosphere** (CO\u2082 + N\u2082 dominant, with smaller amounts of H\u2082O, H\u2082, and traces of CH\u2084/NH\u2083) rather than the strongly reducing mixture used in Miller's original experiment. Transient H\u2082-rich atmospheres after large asteroid impacts could periodically create conditions conducive to Miller-Urey synthesis. Localized reducing environments near volcanic plumes can drive amino acid synthesis even under a weakly reducing global atmosphere.\n\n---\n\n## Mineral catalysts play distinct roles at each reaction step\n\n### Iron-sulfur minerals bridge geochemistry and biochemistry\n\n**Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)** has an inverse thiospinel structure with cubic Fe\u2084S\u2084 units that are structurally identical to [4Fe-4S] clusters in ferredoxins and CODH/ACS enzymes. It is thermodynamically stable (confirmed by Navrotsky group, *PNAS* 2020), catalyzes CO\u2082 reduction to small organics, and can promote the CO\u2082 fixation steps that generate oxaloacetate precursors. Santos-Carballal et al. (2018, *Phil. Trans. R. Soc. A*) modeled CO\u2082 reactivity on greigite surfaces by DFT.\n\n**Pyrite (FeS\u2082)** provides the thermodynamic driving force for W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user's surface metabolism (FeS + H\u2082S \u2192 FeS\u2082 + H\u2082; \u0394G = \u22129.2 kcal/mol). Hafenbradl et al. (1995) demonstrated amino acid synthesis by reductive amination of \u03b1-oxo acids coupled to pyrite formation. A remarkable recent finding: natural pyrite **photocatalytically drives reductive amination** of keto acids with **14.5\u201342.4% enantiomeric excess for D-amino acids** via wavy surface atom arrangements (*Nat. Commun.* 2024).\n\n**Mackinawite (FeS)** \u2014 a layered iron sulfide and precursor to greigite \u2014 reduces CO\u2082 to CO at >300\u00b0C and catalyzes H\u2082-driven CO\u2082 reduction to methanol at **80\u2013120\u00b0C** when doped with Mn (5\u00d7 enhancement) or illuminated with UV-visible light (*Nat. Commun.* 2024). Its semiconductor properties enable photo-assisted catalysis relevant to the earliest steps of carbon fixation.\n\n### Clay minerals concentrate and catalyze\n\n**Montmorillonite** catalyzes oligomerization of activated nucleotides to 40\u201355-mers (Ferris & Ertem, 1992, *Science* 257, 1387), amino acid polymerization under wet-dry cycling (Lahav et al., 1978, *Science* 201, 67), and specifically the formation of glycyl-aspartic acid dipeptides from glycine and aspartate at **85 \u00b1 5\u00b0C** (Kalra/Pant et al., *Int. J. Astrobiol.*). Notably, linear and cyclic aspartate-only peptides were NOT formed, indicating distinct reactivity for aspartate on clay surfaces. Montmorillonite interlayers create **nano-confined environments** distinct from bulk solution, providing locally anhydrous conditions that protect from hydrolysis.\n\n### Photocatalysts and transition metal ions\n\n**ZnS** (sphalerite, band gap ~3.6 eV) photocatalyzes **reversible amination of \u03b1-keto acids** under UV (~360 nm) irradiation, including oxaloacetate \u2192 aspartate (Wang et al., 2011\u20132013; Guzman & Martin, 2008). Chiral mesostructured ZnS can drive CO\u2082 + NH\u2083 \u2192 amino acids with **>96% enantiomeric excess** via spin-polarized electron transfer. **TiO\u2082** (rutile/anatase, band gap 3.0\u20133.2 eV) enhances amino acid polymerization (23% increase with anatase) and converts formamide to nucleoside bases under UV.\n\n**Cu\u00b2\u207a** is the most efficient non-enzymatic transamination catalyst (Harrison et al., 2023). **Fe\u2070** reduces CO\u2082 to pyruvate and acetate at 30\u2013100\u00b0C, 35 bar, generating aspartate when hydroxylamine is present as nitrogen source (Varma et al., 2018, *Nat. Ecol. Evol.*). **Ni\u2070** catalyzes a prebiotic Krebs cycle analog generating amino acids from H\u2082 + NH\u2083 (Kaur et al., 2024, *Chem* 10, 1528). FeS/NiS co-catalyzes thioester synthesis (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1997).\n\n---\n\n## Meteoritic and extraterrestrial evidence confirms abiotic aspartate formation\n\nAspartate is consistently detected in carbonaceous chondrites. In the **Murchison meteorite**, modern analyses by Glavin et al. report **L-aspartate at 1.7 \u00b1 0.1 nmol/g** and **D-aspartate at 0.95 \u00b1 0.04 nmol/g**. The **Tagish Lake meteorite** shows remarkably large L-enantiomeric excesses of **~60% for aspartate**, confirmed as extraterrestrial by \u03b4\u00b9\u00b3C enrichments (+24\u2030 D, +29\u2030 L). The Aguas Zarcas meteorite shows **~28% L-ee** for aspartate. Chimiak et al. (2022, *Geochim. Cosmochim. Acta* 321, 78) used position-specific carbon isotope analysis of Murchison aspartate and found signatures consistent with Strecker synthesis origins. Over **90 amino acids** have been identified in Murchison, with glycine most abundant and aspartate present at lower but significant concentrations. Mu\u00f1oz Caro et al. (2002, *Nature* 416, 403) produced 16 amino acids including aspartate from UV irradiation of interstellar ice analogs (H\u2082O/CO\u2082/CO/CH\u2083OH/NH\u2083), demonstrating that extraterrestrial aspartate formation is experimentally reproducible.\n\n---\n\n## Six major unresolved challenges constrain prebiotic aspartate synthesis\n\n### The oxaloacetate decarboxylation race\n\nThe single greatest bottleneck is that **OAA decarboxylates to pyruvate faster than it can be aminated to aspartate** under most tested conditions. Barge et al. (2019) showed this definitively: iron oxyhydroxide experiments yielded alanine (from pyruvate, the OAA decomposition product) rather than aspartate. The ~5% transamination yield achieved by Harrison et al. (2023) requires the reaction to outpace decarboxylation in the first hour, but sustained production demands continuous OAA regeneration \u2014 something not yet demonstrated in a cyclic, self-sustaining manner. The glyoxylate-mediated OAA generation pathway (Eschenmoser & Krishnamurthy, *Nat. Commun.* 2017) works but requires relatively high concentrations and H\u2082O\u2082 as oxidant.\n\n### Chirality remains without a definitive solution\n\nAll major prebiotic routes produce **racemic aspartate**. Known symmetry-breaking mechanisms include circularly polarized UV light (~1\u20132% ee in aminonitrile precursors), chiral mineral surfaces, and kinetic resolution via dipeptide-mediated transamination (Dherbassy/Moran group, *PNAS* 2024). The most aspartate-specific mechanism is **differential adsorption on calcite**: Hazen et al. (2001, *PNAS* 98, 5487) showed D-aspartate forms 3 strong bonds on calcite (214) surfaces (~8 kcal/mol lower energy than L-aspartate with 2 bonds), enabling chiral separation on mirror-related scalenohedral faces. Aspartate's ability to form **conglomerate enantiopure crystals** (unlike alanine's racemic crystals) provides a plausible amplification mechanism. Racemization half-lives are approximately **3,500\u201315,000 years at 25\u00b0C** (Bada & Schroeder), with aspartate racemizing faster than most amino acids via a succinimide intermediate.\n\n### The concentration problem\n\nEstimated steady-state amino acid concentrations in the prebiotic ocean are ~10\u207b\u2079 M \u2014 orders of magnitude below the mM concentrations used in most published experiments. Strecker synthesis requires [HCN] > 10\u207b\u00b2 M; peptide bond formation needs mM amino acid concentrations. Solutions include evaporative concentration in pools (up to 1000\u00d7), eutectic freezing (HCN concentrates to ~10 M at \u221223.4\u00b0C), mineral adsorption, aerosol enrichment, and submarine vent gradients. Whether protometabolic cycles can operate at ocean-relevant dilutions remains largely untested.\n\n### Thermal stability limits viable environments\n\nAspartate decomposes via deamination (\u2192 fumarate + NH\u2083) and decarboxylation (\u2192 \u03b2-alanine + CO\u2082). At **240\u2013250\u00b0C**, decomposition is rapid and irreversible (Miller & Bada, 1988). Activation energies range from **88.5\u2013137.4 kJ/mol** for amino acid decomposition at 160\u2013240\u00b0C (Hou et al., 2024, *Sci. Rep.*). At 100\u00b0C, half-lives are on the order of thousands of years, making alkaline vents (40\u201390\u00b0C) far more favorable than black smokers (>300\u00b0C). Solid-state decomposition occurs at ~270\u00b0C (\u0394H_f = \u2212973 kJ/mol). Protection by mineral adsorption, vesicle encapsulation, and peptide incorporation can extend stability.\n\n### Competing reactions and pathway selectivity\n\nHCN polymerization converts the vast majority of starting material to intractable \"tar\" rather than useful amino acids. Maillard-type reactions between amino acids and sugars produce complex brown polymers. Aspartate undergoes cyclization to succinimide intermediates, leading to \u03b2-aspartate isomers and accelerated racemization. In aqueous solution, hydrolysis of peptide bonds overwhelmingly outcompetes condensation at hydrothermal temperatures.\n\n### Key experimentally undemonstrated steps\n\nThe following remain as the weakest links in proposed pathways:\n\n- Sustained OAA production from CO\u2082 fixation under prebiotically plausible conditions without enzymes or ATP\n- A complete, self-sustaining non-enzymatic rTCA cycle with turnover (9 of 11 intermediates demonstrated individually by Muchowska et al. 2019, but not as a running cycle)\n- Prebiotic synthesis of pyridoxamine, required for the most efficient transamination route\n- Operation of any protometabolic aspartate synthesis at ocean-relevant dilute concentrations\n- Experimental validation that Hadean CO\u2082 saturation suppresses OAA decarboxylation\n\n---\n\n## Conclusion: converging pathways, persistent gaps\n\nThe prebiotic synthesis landscape for aspartic acid is richer than often appreciated, with HCN oligomer hydrolysis and the Bucherer-Bergs pathway from \u03b1-keto acids standing out as the most productive and most elegant routes, respectively. **HCN oligomerization uniquely yields aspartate as a major product** alongside glycine \u2014 not a trace component \u2014 making it the most efficient single route. The **Bucherer-Bergs pathway** (Pulletikurti et al., 2022) simultaneously generates aspartate and dihydroorotate, linking amino acid and pyrimidine nucleotide synthesis in a single reaction network. For network design in an agentic AI system, these two pathways should be prioritized as primary aspartate sources.\n\nThe protometabolic routes via oxaloacetate (transamination, reductive amination) face the fundamental kinetic barrier of OAA decarboxylation but achieve biological relevance through Cu\u00b2\u207a/pyridoxamine catalysis at ~5% yields in one hour. The most plausible integrated scenario combines **alkaline vent CO\u2082 fixation** (Fe/Ni catalysts, 40\u201390\u00b0C) to generate keto acid intermediates, **rapid transamination or Bucherer-Bergs conversion** before OAA degrades, and **transport to lower-temperature environments** (surface pools, clay surfaces) for concentration via wet-dry cycling and chiral selection on calcite. The three unresolved challenges that most constrain pathway viability are OAA stabilization, operation at realistic dilutions, and the origin of homochirality \u2014 each representing a frontier where new experimental work could transform our understanding of how this metabolically essential amino acid first emerged on the prebiotic Earth.\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Aspartic acid\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"The network prioritizes literature-supported prebiotic aspartate sources by combining (i) hydrothermal CO2 fixation to central keto-acid hubs, especially pyruvate and oxaloacetate, (ii) surface cyanosulfidic and HCN chemistry that generates HCN-derived branch intermediates and direct aspartate-producing oligomer routes, and (iii) biochemical/prebiotic conversion of oxaloacetate through Bucherer-Bergs and transamination. Ten distinct pathways to aspartic acid are represented by alternative sequences converging on four hub molecules: HCN, pyruvate, oxaloacetate, and fumarate. The design explicitly incorporates the major productive route (HCN oligomer hydrolysis), the recently demonstrated Bucherer-Bergs route from oxaloacetate, Cu2+/pyridoxamine transamination of oxaloacetate, cyanoacetylene chemistry, fumarate ammoniation, and direct hydrothermal Fe0-mediated synthesis. Environmental interconnection is shown by hydrothermal generation of pyruvate and oxaloacetate precursors, surface concentration/photochemistry of HCN and cyanoacetylene, and biochemical assembly steps that convert shared intermediates into the target.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"azane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"HCN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH2O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"methanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxyethanal\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glycolaldehyde\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyruvic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H2O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxoacetic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glyoxylic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H4O5\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxobutanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"oxaloacetic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H4O5/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h1H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H4O4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(E)-but-2-enedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"fumaric acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H4O4/c5-3(6)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H,(H,5,6)(H,7,8)/b2-1+\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H5N\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"pyridine-3-ylmethanamine derivative\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyridoxamine\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHNO\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"formamide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"formamide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3HN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"prop-2-ynenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"cyanoacetylene\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3HN/c1-2-3-4/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H8N2O4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-carbamoylaminobutanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"N-carbamoyl aspartate\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H5N3O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3,4-dihydroxopyrimidin-2(1H)-one precursor\",\n      \"common_name\": \"dihydroorotate\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H7NO4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminobutanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"aspartic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H7NO4/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h2H,1,5H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH2OH\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydroxylamine\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydroxylamine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3NO/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H4N4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2,3-diaminobut-2-enedinitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"DAMN\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formaldehyde/glycolaldehyde feedstock\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"350-450K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"magnetite and mackinawite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline vent mixing; H2-rich serpentinization conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Mineral-catalyzed CO2 hydrogenation and Fischer-Tropsch-type C-C coupling generate reduced C1 and C2 carbonyl compounds that feed surface and protometabolic chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrothermal Fe-bearing minerals and vent conditions generate reduced carbonyl feedstocks from CO2 and H2, providing plausible precursors to downstream pyruvate and HCN-linked chemistry in alkaline vent settings (Preiner et al., 2020; Kitadai, 2015; Santos-Carballal et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal Fe0-mediated pyruvate formation from CO2\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe0)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"303-373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"35 bar\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe0 with iron-sulfur surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic CO2-rich system; hydroxylamine-compatible network context\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reduced iron drives CO2 fixation to central carbonyl/carboxylate products including pyruvate under mild hydrothermal conditions.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Fe0-mediated CO2 reduction produces pyruvate under prebiotically plausible hydrothermal conditions, establishing pyruvate as a central hub for oxaloacetate and amino acid synthesis (Varma et al., 2018; Muchowska et al., 2019).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal generation of glyoxylate from reduced C2 carbonyl chemistry\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_006\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"313-373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"greigite and pyrite\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline hydrothermal/protometabolic carbon fixation network\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Iron-sulfur-mediated CO2 fixation and carbonyl rearrangement furnish glyoxylate as a key C2 protometabolic node.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Glyoxylate is a central feedstock in non-enzymatic protometabolic TCA-like chemistry and links hydrothermal carbon fixation to oxaloacetate formation; its role in pyruvate-glyoxylate chemistry is emphasized in protometabolic studies (Muchowska et al., 2019; Eschenmoser & Krishnamurthy, 2017).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Protometabolic aldol route to oxaloacetate from pyruvate and glyoxylate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"greigite (Fe3S4)\", \"elemental iron (Fe0)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298-373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"35 bar\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe0 and Fe-S surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"CO2-rich anoxic protometabolic network; oxaloacetate treated as transient due to rapid decarboxylation\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate and glyoxylate enter non-enzymatic protometabolic carbon-addition chemistry to access oxaloacetate or oxaloacetate-equivalent keto diacids.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Oxaloacetate is the key nexus for aspartate synthesis, and pyruvate-glyoxylate chemistry is among the principal literature-supported routes to OAA-related intermediates despite instability and rapid decarboxylation (Eschenmoser & Krishnamurthy, 2017; Muchowska et al., 2019; Guzman & Martin, 2008).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface HCN formation by UV/spark photochemistry\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 photocatalysis on mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"strong UV irradiation; evaporitic pools and volcanic plume chemistry\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical nitrile generation from reduced carbon and nitrogen feedstocks supplies concentrated HCN for oligomerization and cyanoacetylene chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"HCN is the dominant hub for productive abiotic aspartate synthesis via oligomerization and related chemistry; surface photochemical environments are necessary to concentrate and process cyanide precursors under early Earth UV flux (Matthews & Moser, 1966; Ferris et al., 1978; Sagan & Khare, 1971).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN oligomerization to DAMN and higher HCN polymers\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"195-300K to 350K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral-assisted concentration and UV processing\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"requires [HCN] > 10^-2 M; optimal around pH 9.2; eutectic freezing can concentrate HCN to ~10 M\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Concentrated cyanide oligomerizes through dimer/trimer/tetramer stages to DAMN and higher polymers that serve as direct amino-acid-yielding reservoirs upon hydrolysis.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"HCN oligomerization is the most productive known route to prebiotic aspartate, with DAMN as a key branch intermediate; oligomerization is favored at pH ~9.2 and by freezing concentration (Ferris, Donner & Lobo, 1974; Ferris et al., 1978; Miyakawa, Cleaves & Miller, 2002).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of HCN oligomers to aspartic acid\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"383K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"acid hydrolysis analogous to 6 N HCl, 110C, 24 h analytical release of amino acids from HCN oligomers\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acidic hydrolysis of HCN oligomer backbones releases amino acids, with aspartate among the major products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrolysis of HCN oligomers reproducibly yields aspartic acid as a major product rather than a trace component, making this the strongest single source route in the literature (Ferris, Donner & Lobo, 1974; Ferris et al., 1978; Matthews & Moser, 1966).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface cyanoacetylene formation from cyanide-rich photochemistry\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV-irradiated mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"false\",\n        \"other\": \"electric discharge/photochemical atmosphere-to-surface transfer; weakly reducing localized settings\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"High-energy photochemistry converts cyanide-rich feedstocks into cyanoacetylene, a reactive C3 nitrile branch point.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cyanoacetylene is a documented atmospheric discharge product and a key branch intermediate leading to both aspartate and cytosine in aqueous NH3/HCN chemistry (Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel, 1966; Miller, 1953; Shapiro, 1999).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanoacetylene + HCN + NH3 route to aspartic acid\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_013\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"295-300K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral concentration surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH ~9; room temperature aqueous solution\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"C3 cyanoacetylene couples with HCN and ammonia in aqueous alkaline solution to generate aspartate through nitrile addition and hydrolysis chemistry distinct from classical Strecker synthesis.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This direct cyanoacetylene pathway is specifically reported to generate aspartic acid, asparagine, and cytosine at about pH 9 and room temperature, providing a cyanide-rich surface route to the target (Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel, 1966).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Bucherer-Bergs conversion of oxaloacetate to N-carbamoyl aspartate and aspartate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_014\", \"mol_015\", \"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298-333K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"aqueous NaCN + NH4HCO3 equivalent conditions; neutral to slightly basic pH\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Oxaloacetate undergoes Bucherer-Bergs reactivity with cyanide and ammonium bicarbonate to form N-carbamoyl aspartate, which hydrolyzes to aspartate while also enabling dihydroorotate formation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The Bucherer-Bergs pathway from oxaloacetate is a recently demonstrated and highly relevant prebiotic route to aspartate, directly linking amino acid and pyrimidine precursor synthesis through N-carbamoyl aspartate and dihydroorotate (Pulletikurti, Yadav, Springsteen & Krishnamurthy, 2022).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"Cu2+-pyridoxamine transamination of oxaloacetate to aspartate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298-343K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"ambient to high pressure\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"1 mM Cu2+\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"5-10 mM reactants; 50 mM NH4HCO3 buffer; pH 6-10; ~1 h reaction window before substantial OAA loss\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Metal-assisted PLP-analog transamination transfers amino functionality from pyridoxamine to oxaloacetate faster than decarboxylation during the initial reaction window.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Cu2+-catalyzed transamination of oxaloacetate by pyridoxamine is the best-characterized biologically parallel prebiotic route, reaching ~5% aspartate in 1 h but limited by competing OAA decarboxylation (Harrison et al., 2023; Mayer et al., 2021; Dherbassy et al., 2023).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Oxaloacetate decarboxylation to pyruvate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298-343K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"half-life ~1-2 h at 25C near neutral pH; accelerated by divalent metals\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Spontaneous beta-keto acid decarboxylation converts oxaloacetate to pyruvate, competing with all OAA-to-aspartate routes.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Rapid oxaloacetate decarboxylation is the dominant bottleneck in prebiotic aspartate synthesis and must be explicitly represented because it diverts OAA toward pyruvate and alanine-forming chemistry (Guzman & Martin, 2008; Barge et al., 2019; Harrison et al., 2023).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Photochemical OAA-to-fumarate branch via malate/fumarate chemistry\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"montmorillonite (clay)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-330K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV-active mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"photocatalytic reduction/dehydration network inspired by ZnS malate/fumarate chemistry; represented here with allowed surface minerals as concentration/photochemical supports\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Oxaloacetate enters a photochemical redox/dehydration branch that accesses fumarate, a known rTCA-related node and precursor to aspartate by ammoniation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Fumarate is a documented prebiotic branch point connected to oxaloacetate/malate chemistry in non-enzymatic rTCA analogs and photocatalytic networks, and it is specifically identified in the literature as a node leading to aspartate via ammonia addition; this connection is somewhat schematic here because the cited studies emphasize ZnS rather than the allowed output mineral list (Guzman & Martin, 2008; Zhou & Guzman, 2016; Muchowska, Varma & Moran, 2020).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"Michael addition of ammonia to fumarate forming aspartic acid\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"320-370K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": null,\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline conditions with high NH3/NH4+ concentration; low non-enzymatic yield\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Non-enzymatic conjugate addition of ammonia to fumarate affords aspartate, analogous to the reverse biological aspartase reaction.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Although low yielding without enzymatic catalysis, ammonia addition to fumarate is thermodynamically feasible under alkaline, ammonia-rich conditions and is a literature-recognized distinct route to aspartate (Muchowska, Varma & Moran, 2020; Harrison et al., 2023).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_015\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal Fe0/hydroxylamine direct route to aspartate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\", \"mol_017\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe0)\", \"pyrite (FeS2)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"303-373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"35 bar\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe0 with iron mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic CO2 reduction network with hydroxylamine as nitrogen source\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Direct Fe0-driven CO2 reduction in the presence of a reactive nitrogen donor furnishes amino acid products including aspartate within a broader protometabolic network.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Aspartate has been detected in Fe0-mediated CO2 reduction experiments when hydroxylamine serves as nitrogen source, making this a direct hydrothermal source route distinct from OAA transamination or HCN oligomer hydrolysis (Varma et al., 2018).\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_016\",\n      \"name\": \"Surface UV conversion of HCN and water to formamide\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"300-340K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"TiO2 photocatalysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"strong UV irradiation in shallow pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical hydration/oxidation of cyanide-rich surface inventories generates formamide, a versatile prebiotic solvent/reactant linked to nitrile chemistry.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Formamide is a well-established product/intermediate in UV-driven cyanide chemistry and helps connect cyanide-rich surface environments to broader prebiotic synthesis space; included here as a network-supported branch from the HCN hub (Sagan & Khare, 1971; Mu\u00f1oz Caro et al., 2002).\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct HCN oligomer hydrolysis route\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN generated in surface environments oligomerizes to DAMN/higher polymers and hydrolyzes to release aspartate as a major product.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Frozen-concentrated HCN oligomer route\",\n      \"description\": \"The same HCN oligomer route operates under eutectic freezing concentration, improving cyanide concentration before hydrolysis to aspartate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanoacetylene coupling route\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface HCN is converted to cyanoacetylene, which reacts with HCN and NH3 in alkaline aqueous solution to form aspartate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal OAA to Bucherer-Bergs route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 fixation generates pyruvate and glyoxylate, which feed oxaloacetate formation; oxaloacetate is trapped by cyanide/ammonium chemistry to form aspartate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Transamination route from oxaloacetate\",\n      \"description\": \"Oxaloacetate formed through protometabolic hydrothermal chemistry is rapidly aminated by Cu2+/pyridoxamine before decarboxylation dominates.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Fumarate ammoniation route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal oxaloacetate precursors feed a surface photochemical branch to fumarate, followed by non-enzymatic ammonia addition to aspartate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct Fe0-hydroxylamine hydrothermal route\",\n      \"description\": \"Aspartate arises directly in an Fe0-mediated CO2 reduction network with hydroxylamine as nitrogen donor under mild hydrothermal conditions.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_015\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": []\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal-to-surface HCN then Bucherer-Bergs hybrid route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal oxaloacetate formation converges with surface-generated HCN; the two streams meet in Bucherer-Bergs conversion to aspartate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal carbonyl feedstock to HCN oligomer route\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal reduced carbonyl compounds seed surface HCN production, which then proceeds through oligomerization and hydrolysis to aspartate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Pyruvate-regeneration constrained OAA route\",\n      \"description\": \"Pyruvate formed hydrothermally regenerates transient oxaloacetate via glyoxylate chemistry; aspartate forms by transamination in competition with OAA decarboxylation.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_011\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_008\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_006\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_016\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_010\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_013\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_014\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Aspartic acid", "overall_strategy": "The network prioritizes literature-supported prebiotic aspartate sources by combining (i) hydrothermal CO2 fixation to central keto-acid hubs, especially pyruvate and oxaloacetate, (ii) surface cyanosulfidic and HCN chemistry that generates HCN-derived branch intermediates and direct aspartate-producing oligomer routes, and (iii) biochemical/prebiotic conversion of oxaloacetate through Bucherer-Bergs and transamination. Ten distinct pathways to aspartic acid are represented by alternative sequences converging on four hub molecules: HCN, pyruvate, oxaloacetate, and fumarate. The design explicitly incorporates the major productive route (HCN oligomer hydrolysis), the recently demonstrated Bucherer-Bergs route from oxaloacetate, Cu2+/pyridoxamine transamination of oxaloacetate, cyanoacetylene chemistry, fumarate ammoniation, and direct hydrothermal Fe0-mediated synthesis. Environmental interconnection is shown by hydrothermal generation of pyruvate and oxaloacetate precursors, surface concentration/photochemistry of HCN and cyanoacetylene, and biochemical assembly steps that convert shared intermediates into the target.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "HCN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "CH2O", "iupac_name": "methanal", "common_name": "formaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O/c1-2/h1H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "C2H4O2", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxyethanal", "common_name": "glycolaldehyde", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H4O2/c3-1-2-4/h1,3H,2H2", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C2H2O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxoacetic acid", "common_name": "glyoxylic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C4H4O5", "iupac_name": "2-oxobutanedioic acid", "common_name": "oxaloacetic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H4O5/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h1H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C4H4O4", "iupac_name": "(E)-but-2-enedioic acid", "common_name": "fumaric acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H4O4/c5-3(6)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H,(H,5,6)(H,7,8)/b2-1+", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "C5H5N", "iupac_name": "pyridine-3-ylmethanamine derivative", "common_name": "pyridoxamine", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "CHNO", "iupac_name": "formamide", "common_name": "formamide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH3NO/c2-1-3/h1H,(H2,2,3)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C3HN", "iupac_name": "prop-2-ynenitrile", "common_name": "cyanoacetylene", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3HN/c1-2-3-4/h1H", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C4H8N2O4", "iupac_name": "2-carbamoylaminobutanedioic acid", "common_name": "N-carbamoyl aspartate", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C4H5N3O2", "iupac_name": "3,4-dihydroxopyrimidin-2(1H)-one precursor", "common_name": "dihydroorotate", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C4H7NO4", "iupac_name": "2-aminobutanedioic acid", "common_name": "aspartic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H7NO4/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h2H,1,5H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "NH2OH", "iupac_name": "hydroxylamine", "common_name": "hydroxylamine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3NO/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "C4H4N4", "iupac_name": "2,3-diaminobut-2-enedinitrile", "common_name": "DAMN", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formaldehyde/glycolaldehyde feedstock", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_005", "mol_006"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "350-450K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "magnetite and mackinawite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline vent mixing; H2-rich serpentinization conditions"}, "mechanism": "Mineral-catalyzed CO2 hydrogenation and Fischer-Tropsch-type C-C coupling generate reduced C1 and C2 carbonyl compounds that feed surface and protometabolic chemistry.", "reasoning": "Hydrothermal Fe-bearing minerals and vent conditions generate reduced carbonyl feedstocks from CO2 and H2, providing plausible precursors to downstream pyruvate and HCN-linked chemistry in alkaline vent settings (Preiner et al., 2020; Kitadai, 2015; Santos-Carballal et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Hydrothermal Fe0-mediated pyruvate formation from CO2", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe0)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "303-373K", "pressure": "35 bar", "catalyst": "Fe0 with iron-sulfur surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic CO2-rich system; hydroxylamine-compatible network context"}, "mechanism": "Reduced iron drives CO2 fixation to central carbonyl/carboxylate products including pyruvate under mild hydrothermal conditions.", "reasoning": "Fe0-mediated CO2 reduction produces pyruvate under prebiotically plausible hydrothermal conditions, establishing pyruvate as a central hub for oxaloacetate and amino acid synthesis (Varma et al., 2018; Muchowska et al., 2019)."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Hydrothermal generation of glyoxylate from reduced C2 carbonyl chemistry", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_006"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "313-373K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "greigite and pyrite", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline hydrothermal/protometabolic carbon fixation network"}, "mechanism": "Iron-sulfur-mediated CO2 fixation and carbonyl rearrangement furnish glyoxylate as a key C2 protometabolic node.", "reasoning": "Glyoxylate is a central feedstock in non-enzymatic protometabolic TCA-like chemistry and links hydrothermal carbon fixation to oxaloacetate formation; its role in pyruvate-glyoxylate chemistry is emphasized in protometabolic studies (Muchowska et al., 2019; Eschenmoser & Krishnamurthy, 2017)."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Protometabolic aldol route to oxaloacetate from pyruvate and glyoxylate", "inputs": ["mol_007", "mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_009"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["greigite (Fe3S4)", "elemental iron (Fe0)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "298-373K", "pressure": "35 bar", "catalyst": "Fe0 and Fe-S surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "CO2-rich anoxic protometabolic network; oxaloacetate treated as transient due to rapid decarboxylation"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate and glyoxylate enter non-enzymatic protometabolic carbon-addition chemistry to access oxaloacetate or oxaloacetate-equivalent keto diacids.", "reasoning": "Oxaloacetate is the key nexus for aspartate synthesis, and pyruvate-glyoxylate chemistry is among the principal literature-supported routes to OAA-related intermediates despite instability and rapid decarboxylation (Eschenmoser & Krishnamurthy, 2017; Muchowska et al., 2019; Guzman & Martin, 2008)."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Surface HCN formation by UV/spark photochemistry", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_004"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 photocatalysis on mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "strong UV irradiation; evaporitic pools and volcanic plume chemistry"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical nitrile generation from reduced carbon and nitrogen feedstocks supplies concentrated HCN for oligomerization and cyanoacetylene chemistry.", "reasoning": "HCN is the dominant hub for productive abiotic aspartate synthesis via oligomerization and related chemistry; surface photochemical environments are necessary to concentrate and process cyanide precursors under early Earth UV flux (Matthews & Moser, 1966; Ferris et al., 1978; Sagan & Khare, 1971)."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "HCN oligomerization to DAMN and higher HCN polymers", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "195-300K to 350K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral-assisted concentration and UV processing", "aqueous": "true", "other": "requires [HCN] > 10^-2 M; optimal around pH 9.2; eutectic freezing can concentrate HCN to ~10 M"}, "mechanism": "Concentrated cyanide oligomerizes through dimer/trimer/tetramer stages to DAMN and higher polymers that serve as direct amino-acid-yielding reservoirs upon hydrolysis.", "reasoning": "HCN oligomerization is the most productive known route to prebiotic aspartate, with DAMN as a key branch intermediate; oligomerization is favored at pH ~9.2 and by freezing concentration (Ferris, Donner & Lobo, 1974; Ferris et al., 1978; Miyakawa, Cleaves & Miller, 2002)."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "Hydrolysis of HCN oligomers to aspartic acid", "inputs": ["mol_018"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "383K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "acid hydrolysis analogous to 6 N HCl, 110C, 24 h analytical release of amino acids from HCN oligomers"}, "mechanism": "Acidic hydrolysis of HCN oligomer backbones releases amino acids, with aspartate among the major products.", "reasoning": "Hydrolysis of HCN oligomers reproducibly yields aspartic acid as a major product rather than a trace component, making this the strongest single source route in the literature (Ferris, Donner & Lobo, 1974; Ferris et al., 1978; Matthews & Moser, 1966)."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Surface cyanoacetylene formation from cyanide-rich photochemistry", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV-irradiated mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "false", "other": "electric discharge/photochemical atmosphere-to-surface transfer; weakly reducing localized settings"}, "mechanism": "High-energy photochemistry converts cyanide-rich feedstocks into cyanoacetylene, a reactive C3 nitrile branch point.", "reasoning": "Cyanoacetylene is a documented atmospheric discharge product and a key branch intermediate leading to both aspartate and cytosine in aqueous NH3/HCN chemistry (Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel, 1966; Miller, 1953; Shapiro, 1999)."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Cyanoacetylene + HCN + NH3 route to aspartic acid", "inputs": ["mol_013", "mol_004", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "295-300K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral concentration surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH ~9; room temperature aqueous solution"}, "mechanism": "C3 cyanoacetylene couples with HCN and ammonia in aqueous alkaline solution to generate aspartate through nitrile addition and hydrolysis chemistry distinct from classical Strecker synthesis.", "reasoning": "This direct cyanoacetylene pathway is specifically reported to generate aspartic acid, asparagine, and cytosine at about pH 9 and room temperature, providing a cyanide-rich surface route to the target (Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel, 1966)."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Bucherer-Bergs conversion of oxaloacetate to N-carbamoyl aspartate and aspartate", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_004", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_014", "mol_015", "mol_016"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "298-333K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "aqueous NaCN + NH4HCO3 equivalent conditions; neutral to slightly basic pH"}, "mechanism": "Oxaloacetate undergoes Bucherer-Bergs reactivity with cyanide and ammonium bicarbonate to form N-carbamoyl aspartate, which hydrolyzes to aspartate while also enabling dihydroorotate formation.", "reasoning": "The Bucherer-Bergs pathway from oxaloacetate is a recently demonstrated and highly relevant prebiotic route to aspartate, directly linking amino acid and pyrimidine precursor synthesis through N-carbamoyl aspartate and dihydroorotate (Pulletikurti, Yadav, Springsteen & Krishnamurthy, 2022)."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "Cu2+-pyridoxamine transamination of oxaloacetate to aspartate", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "298-343K", "pressure": "ambient to high pressure", "catalyst": "1 mM Cu2+", "aqueous": "true", "other": "5-10 mM reactants; 50 mM NH4HCO3 buffer; pH 6-10; ~1 h reaction window before substantial OAA loss"}, "mechanism": "Metal-assisted PLP-analog transamination transfers amino functionality from pyridoxamine to oxaloacetate faster than decarboxylation during the initial reaction window.", "reasoning": "Cu2+-catalyzed transamination of oxaloacetate by pyridoxamine is the best-characterized biologically parallel prebiotic route, reaching ~5% aspartate in 1 h but limited by competing OAA decarboxylation (Harrison et al., 2023; Mayer et al., 2021; Dherbassy et al., 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Oxaloacetate decarboxylation to pyruvate", "inputs": ["mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_007", "mol_001"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "298-343K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "half-life ~1-2 h at 25C near neutral pH; accelerated by divalent metals"}, "mechanism": "Spontaneous beta-keto acid decarboxylation converts oxaloacetate to pyruvate, competing with all OAA-to-aspartate routes.", "reasoning": "Rapid oxaloacetate decarboxylation is the dominant bottleneck in prebiotic aspartate synthesis and must be explicitly represented because it diverts OAA toward pyruvate and alanine-forming chemistry (Guzman & Martin, 2008; Barge et al., 2019; Harrison et al., 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Photochemical OAA-to-fumarate branch via malate/fumarate chemistry", "inputs": ["mol_009"], "outputs": ["mol_010"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "montmorillonite (clay)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-330K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV-active mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "photocatalytic reduction/dehydration network inspired by ZnS malate/fumarate chemistry; represented here with allowed surface minerals as concentration/photochemical supports"}, "mechanism": "Oxaloacetate enters a photochemical redox/dehydration branch that accesses fumarate, a known rTCA-related node and precursor to aspartate by ammoniation.", "reasoning": "Fumarate is a documented prebiotic branch point connected to oxaloacetate/malate chemistry in non-enzymatic rTCA analogs and photocatalytic networks, and it is specifically identified in the literature as a node leading to aspartate via ammonia addition; this connection is somewhat schematic here because the cited studies emphasize ZnS rather than the allowed output mineral list (Guzman & Martin, 2008; Zhou & Guzman, 2016; Muchowska, Varma & Moran, 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "Michael addition of ammonia to fumarate forming aspartic acid", "inputs": ["mol_010", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "320-370K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline conditions with high NH3/NH4+ concentration; low non-enzymatic yield"}, "mechanism": "Non-enzymatic conjugate addition of ammonia to fumarate affords aspartate, analogous to the reverse biological aspartase reaction.", "reasoning": "Although low yielding without enzymatic catalysis, ammonia addition to fumarate is thermodynamically feasible under alkaline, ammonia-rich conditions and is a literature-recognized distinct route to aspartate (Muchowska, Varma & Moran, 2020; Harrison et al., 2023)."}, {"id": "rxn_015", "name": "Hydrothermal Fe0/hydroxylamine direct route to aspartate", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002", "mol_017"], "outputs": ["mol_016"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe0)", "pyrite (FeS2)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "303-373K", "pressure": "35 bar", "catalyst": "Fe0 with iron mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic CO2 reduction network with hydroxylamine as nitrogen source"}, "mechanism": "Direct Fe0-driven CO2 reduction in the presence of a reactive nitrogen donor furnishes amino acid products including aspartate within a broader protometabolic network.", "reasoning": "Aspartate has been detected in Fe0-mediated CO2 reduction experiments when hydroxylamine serves as nitrogen source, making this a direct hydrothermal source route distinct from OAA transamination or HCN oligomer hydrolysis (Varma et al., 2018)."}, {"id": "rxn_016", "name": "Surface UV conversion of HCN and water to formamide", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["TiO2 (anatase/rutile)", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-340K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "TiO2 photocatalysis", "aqueous": "true", "other": "strong UV irradiation in shallow pools"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical hydration/oxidation of cyanide-rich surface inventories generates formamide, a versatile prebiotic solvent/reactant linked to nitrile chemistry.", "reasoning": "Formamide is a well-established product/intermediate in UV-driven cyanide chemistry and helps connect cyanide-rich surface environments to broader prebiotic synthesis space; included here as a network-supported branch from the HCN hub (Sagan & Khare, 1971; Mu\u00f1oz Caro et al., 2002)."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Direct HCN oligomer hydrolysis route", "description": "HCN generated in surface environments oligomerizes to DAMN/higher polymers and hydrolyzes to release aspartate as a major product.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_018"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Frozen-concentrated HCN oligomer route", "description": "The same HCN oligomer route operates under eutectic freezing concentration, improving cyanide concentration before hydrolysis to aspartate.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_018"]}, {"pathway_id": "P3", "name": "Cyanoacetylene coupling route", "description": "Surface HCN is converted to cyanoacetylene, which reacts with HCN and NH3 in alkaline aqueous solution to form aspartate.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_005", "rxn_008", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_013"]}, {"pathway_id": "P4", "name": "Hydrothermal OAA to Bucherer-Bergs route", "description": "Hydrothermal CO2 fixation generates pyruvate and glyoxylate, which feed oxaloacetate formation; oxaloacetate is trapped by cyanide/ammonium chemistry to form aspartate.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_009", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P5", "name": "Transamination route from oxaloacetate", "description": "Oxaloacetate formed through protometabolic hydrothermal chemistry is rapidly aminated by Cu2+/pyridoxamine before decarboxylation dominates.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_009"]}, {"pathway_id": "P6", "name": "Fumarate ammoniation route", "description": "Hydrothermal oxaloacetate precursors feed a surface photochemical branch to fumarate, followed by non-enzymatic ammonia addition to aspartate.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_013", "rxn_014"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_010"]}, {"pathway_id": "P7", "name": "Direct Fe0-hydroxylamine hydrothermal route", "description": "Aspartate arises directly in an Fe0-mediated CO2 reduction network with hydroxylamine as nitrogen donor under mild hydrothermal conditions.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_015"], "key_intermediates": []}, {"pathway_id": "P8", "name": "Hydrothermal-to-surface HCN then Bucherer-Bergs hybrid route", "description": "Hydrothermal oxaloacetate formation converges with surface-generated HCN; the two streams meet in Bucherer-Bergs conversion to aspartate.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_005", "rxn_010"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_009", "mol_004", "mol_014"]}, {"pathway_id": "P9", "name": "Hydrothermal carbonyl feedstock to HCN oligomer route", "description": "Hydrothermal reduced carbonyl compounds seed surface HCN production, which then proceeds through oligomerization and hydrolysis to aspartate.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_001", "rxn_005", "rxn_006", "rxn_007"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_005", "mol_004", "mol_018"]}, {"pathway_id": "P10", "name": "Pyruvate-regeneration constrained OAA route", "description": "Pyruvate formed hydrothermally regenerates transient oxaloacetate via glyoxylate chemistry; aspartate forms by transamination in competition with OAA decarboxylation.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_002", "rxn_003", "rxn_004", "rxn_012", "rxn_004", "rxn_011"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_007", "mol_008", "mol_009"]}], "hub_molecules": ["mol_004", "mol_007", "mol_009", "mol_010", "mol_008"], "convergence_points": [{"molecule_id": "mol_004", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_005"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_006", "rxn_008", "rxn_009", "rxn_010", "rxn_016"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_007", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_002", "rxn_012"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_004"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_009", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_004"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_010", "rxn_011", "rxn_012", "rxn_013"]}, {"molecule_id": "mol_010", "incoming_reactions": ["rxn_013"], "outgoing_reactions": ["rxn_014"]}]}, "reasoning": "", "duration_ms": 112020.52521705627, "success": true, "error_message": null}
{"timestamp": "2026-04-19T13:26:49.828709", "agent_name": "CriticAgent", "method_name": "evaluate_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "You are evaluating a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK, not individual reactions.\n\n## Evaluation Criteria\n\n### 1. Network Topology (0.0-1.0)\n- Are there sufficient molecule and reaction nodes?\n- Are hub molecules properly connected (degree \u2265 3)?\n- Are there convergent pathways?\n- Is the network connected (no isolated subgraphs)?\n\n### 2. Chemical Feasibility (0.0-1.0)\n- Is each reaction chemically sound?\n- Are the conditions appropriate for each environment?\n- Are the mechanisms plausible?\n\n### 3. Environmental Interconnection (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network show Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical flow?\n- Are environmental transitions justified (e.g., hydrothermal products feeding surface reactions)?\n- Are conditions realistic for each stage?\n- Do Hydrothermal and Surface reactions specify mineral agents?\n\n### 4. Pathway Coherence (0.0-1.0)\n- Do pathways form valid routes to the target?\n- Are key intermediates properly identified?\n- Is the overall strategy sound?\n\n### 5. Target Achievement (0.0-1.0)\n- Does the network actually produce the target molecule?\n- Are the final steps chemically valid?\n\n### 6. Literature Alignment (0.0-1.0) - When research findings are provided\n- Does the network align with known prebiotic synthesis routes from literature?\n- Are reactions supported by experimental evidence from cited studies?\n- Are literature citations present in reaction reasoning?\n- Does the network address known challenges identified in the research?\n\n## Scoring Guidelines\n- 0.9-1.0: Excellent network, well-connected, chemically sound\n- 0.8-0.9: Good network with minor issues\n- 0.7-0.8: Acceptable but with notable concerns\n- 0.5-0.7: Significant problems with topology or chemistry\n- 0.0-0.5: Major issues, network is not viable\n\nA network is APPROVED if overall_confidence >= 0.9\n\nOutput your evaluation as JSON matching the NetworkEvaluation schema.\n", "user_message": "Evaluate this synthesis network:\n\nTARGET MOLECULE: Aspartic acid\nOVERALL STRATEGY: The network prioritizes literature-supported prebiotic aspartate sources by combining (i) hydrothermal CO2 fixation to central keto-acid hubs, especially pyruvate and oxaloacetate, (ii) surface cyanosulfidic and HCN chemistry that generates HCN-derived branch intermediates and direct aspartate-producing oligomer routes, and (iii) biochemical/prebiotic conversion of oxaloacetate through Bucherer-Bergs and transamination. Ten distinct pathways to aspartic acid are represented by alternative sequences converging on four hub molecules: HCN, pyruvate, oxaloacetate, and fumarate. The design explicitly incorporates the major productive route (HCN oligomer hydrolysis), the recently demonstrated Bucherer-Bergs route from oxaloacetate, Cu2+/pyridoxamine transamination of oxaloacetate, cyanoacetylene chemistry, fumarate ammoniation, and direct hydrothermal Fe0-mediated synthesis. Environmental interconnection is shown by hydrothermal generation of pyruvate and oxaloacetate precursors, surface concentration/photochemistry of HCN and cyanoacetylene, and biochemical assembly steps that convert shared intermediates into the target.\n\nMOLECULES (18 nodes):\n  - mol_001: CO2 (carbon dioxide) [starting]\n  - mol_002: H2 (hydrogen) [starting]\n  - mol_003: NH3 (ammonia) [starting]\n  - mol_004: HCN (hydrogen cyanide) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_005: CH2O (formaldehyde) [intermediate]\n  - mol_006: C2H4O2 (glycolaldehyde) [intermediate]\n  - mol_007: C3H4O3 (pyruvic acid) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_008: C2H2O3 (glyoxylic acid) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_009: C4H4O5 (oxaloacetic acid) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_010: C4H4O4 (fumaric acid) [hub_intermediate]\n  - mol_011: C5H5N (pyridoxamine) [intermediate]\n  - mol_012: CHNO (formamide) [intermediate]\n  - mol_013: C3HN (cyanoacetylene) [intermediate]\n  - mol_014: C4H8N2O4 (N-carbamoyl aspartate) [intermediate]\n  - mol_015: C4H5N3O2 (dihydroorotate) [intermediate]\n  - mol_016: C4H7NO4 (aspartic acid) [target]\n  - mol_017: NH2OH (hydroxylamine) [starting]\n  - mol_018: C4H4N4 (DAMN) [intermediate]\n\nREACTIONS (16 nodes):\n  - rxn_001: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_005, mol_006 (Hydrothermal CO2 reduction to formaldehyde/glycolaldehyde feedstock) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_002: mol_001, mol_002 -> mol_007 (Hydrothermal Fe0-mediated pyruvate formation from CO2) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_003: mol_001, mol_002, mol_006 -> mol_008 (Hydrothermal generation of glyoxylate from reduced C2 carbonyl chemistry) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_004: mol_007, mol_008 -> mol_009 (Protometabolic aldol route to oxaloacetate from pyruvate and glyoxylate) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_005: mol_005, mol_003 -> mol_004 (Surface HCN formation by UV/spark photochemistry) [Surface]\n  - rxn_006: mol_004 -> mol_018 (HCN oligomerization to DAMN and higher HCN polymers) [Surface]\n  - rxn_007: mol_018 -> mol_016 (Hydrolysis of HCN oligomers to aspartic acid) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_008: mol_004 -> mol_013 (Surface cyanoacetylene formation from cyanide-rich photochemistry) [Surface]\n  - rxn_009: mol_013, mol_004, mol_003 -> mol_016 (Cyanoacetylene + HCN + NH3 route to aspartic acid) [Surface]\n  - rxn_010: mol_009, mol_004, mol_003 -> mol_014, mol_015, mol_016 (Bucherer-Bergs conversion of oxaloacetate to N-carbamoyl aspartate and aspartate) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_011: mol_009, mol_011 -> mol_016 (Cu2+-pyridoxamine transamination of oxaloacetate to aspartate) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_012: mol_009 -> mol_007, mol_001 (Oxaloacetate decarboxylation to pyruvate) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_013: mol_009 -> mol_010 (Photochemical OAA-to-fumarate branch via malate/fumarate chemistry) [Surface]\n  - rxn_014: mol_010, mol_003 -> mol_016 (Michael addition of ammonia to fumarate forming aspartic acid) [Biochemical]\n  - rxn_015: mol_001, mol_002, mol_017 -> mol_016 (Hydrothermal Fe0/hydroxylamine direct route to aspartate) [Hydrothermal]\n  - rxn_016: mol_004 -> mol_012 (Surface UV conversion of HCN and water to formamide) [Surface]\n\nPATHWAYS (10):\n  - P1: Direct HCN oligomer hydrolysis route (3 steps)\n  - P2: Frozen-concentrated HCN oligomer route (3 steps)\n  - P3: Cyanoacetylene coupling route (3 steps)\n  - P4: Hydrothermal OAA to Bucherer-Bergs route (4 steps)\n  - P5: Transamination route from oxaloacetate (4 steps)\n  - P6: Fumarate ammoniation route (5 steps)\n  - P7: Direct Fe0-hydroxylamine hydrothermal route (1 steps)\n  - P8: Hydrothermal-to-surface HCN then Bucherer-Bergs hybrid route (5 steps)\n  - P9: Hydrothermal carbonyl feedstock to HCN oligomer route (4 steps)\n  - P10: Pyruvate-regeneration constrained OAA route (6 steps)\n\nHUB MOLECULES: mol_004, mol_007, mol_009, mol_010, mol_008\nCONVERGENCE POINTS: 4\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH ON TARGET MOLECULE ===\nThe following research was conducted on the target molecule before network generation. Use it to assess whether the network aligns with known prebiotic chemistry literature.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n# Prebiotic synthesis of aspartic acid: routes, evidence, and open challenges\n\n**Aspartic acid ranks among the most metabolically central yet prebiotically elusive amino acids.** At least 10 distinct prebiotic routes have been proposed or demonstrated, ranging from HCN oligomer hydrolysis \u2014 where aspartate emerges as a major product \u2014 to metal-catalyzed transamination of oxaloacetate, which mimics the biological pathway but battles the rapid decarboxylation of its precursor. The core tension in prebiotic aspartate chemistry is that the most biologically relevant pathways (via oxaloacetate) face severe kinetic competition from degradation, while the most productive abiotic routes (HCN oligomerization, spark discharge) operate through entirely different mechanisms. This report synthesizes the full landscape of published research on prebiotic aspartate formation, organized to guide synthesis network design and pathway evaluation in an agentic AI system for prebiotic chemistry.\n\n---\n\n## Known prebiotic routes span at least 10 distinct pathways\n\n### Strecker synthesis\n\nThe classical Strecker route proceeds through aldehyde + NH\u2083 \u2192 imine (Schiff base), then imine + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-aminonitrile, and finally hydrolysis of the aminonitrile to the amino acid. For aspartate, this requires a **C3 aldehyde bearing a carboxyl group** (such as 3-oxopropanoic acid or a related functionalized aldehyde), making the Strecker route to aspartate less straightforward than for glycine or alanine. Miller (1957, *Biochim. Biophys. Acta* 23, 480) established that spark discharge amino acid synthesis proceeds via this Strecker mechanism in the aqueous phase. Conditions are aqueous solution, **pH 7\u20139, room temperature to moderate heat**, with reaction times of hours to days. The prebiotic availability of the specific C4 aldehyde precursor for aspartate remains poorly constrained, representing a significant gap in this pathway.\n\n### Miller-Urey spark discharge\n\nMiller's original 1953 experiment (*Science* 117, 528) used CH\u2084 (200 torr), NH\u2083 (200 torr), H\u2082 (100 torr), and H\u2082O with Tesla coil spark discharge for one week. Aspartic acid was tentatively identified as spot #1 on the 2D paper chromatogram, though Miller's more rigorous 1955 analysis (*JACS* 77, 2351) reclassified this spot as likely **iminodiacetic acid**. The yield of aspartate, when confirmed, was approximately **0.024% relative to carbon input** \u2014 far below glycine at ~2.1%.\n\nModern reanalysis of Miller's archived samples transformed our understanding. Johnson et al. (2008, *Science* 322, 404) reanalyzed volcanic apparatus vials using HPLC-ToF-MS, detecting **22 amino acids and 5 amines** including confirmed D,L-aspartate. Parker et al. (2011, *PNAS* 108, 5526) reanalyzed Miller's unpublished 1958 H\u2082S experiment (CH\u2084/NH\u2083/H\u2082S/CO\u2082 atmosphere), finding **23 amino acids and 4 amines** including 7 organosulfur compounds. Aspartate was present at relatively low abundances, and the H\u2082S experiment produced yields an **order of magnitude higher** than the classic apparatus for many amino acids. Cleaves et al. (2008, *Orig. Life Evol. Biosph.* 38, 105) showed that adding oxidation inhibitors (pyrite, ascorbic acid, FeSO\u2084) to neutral atmosphere (CO\u2082/N\u2082) spark discharge experiments boosted amino acid yields by factors of **2\u2013100\u00d7**.\n\n### HCN oligomerization \u2014 the most productive route for aspartate\n\nHCN oligomerization followed by hydrolysis is the single most productive prebiotic route specifically for aspartate. Ferris, Donner & Lobo (1974, *J. Mol. Evol.* 3, 225) demonstrated that the **major amino acids** released on hydrolysis of HCN oligomers were **glycine, aspartate, and diaminosuccinic acid** \u2014 making aspartate a dominant product rather than a trace component. Ferris et al. (1978, *J. Mol. Evol.* 11, 293) confirmed this using 0.1 M HCN solutions at pH 9.2, where oligomers form over days to weeks and yield amino acids upon acid hydrolysis (6N HCl, 110\u00b0C, 24h). Matthews & Moser (1966, *PNAS* 56, 1087) independently detected glycine, alanine, and aspartic acid from HCN polymerization in aqueous ammonia. Frozen HCN solutions (\u221220 to \u221278\u00b0C) concentrated at the eutectic point (~10 M HCN at \u221223.4\u00b0C) also produce aspartate upon oligomer hydrolysis (Miyakawa, Cleaves & Miller, 2002, *Orig. Life Evol. Biosph.* 32, 195). The mechanism likely involves **5-carboxymethylidenehydantoin**, a cyclic intermediate specifically related to aspartate identified in HCN oligomer mixtures.\n\n### Cyanoacetylene route\n\nSanchez, Ferris & Orgel (1966, *Science* 154, 784) showed that cyanoacetylene (HC\u2261C-C\u2261N) \u2014 a major nitrogen-containing product of electric discharge in CH\u2084/N\u2082 mixtures (up to 8.4% of HCN yield) \u2014 reacts with HCN and NH\u2083 in aqueous solution at **pH ~9, room temperature** to produce **aspartic acid, asparagine, and cytosine**. This C\u2083 + C\u2081 coupling pathway is distinct from Strecker chemistry. However, cyanoacetylene production is suppressed when NH\u2083 or H\u2082S are present in the discharge, and Shapiro (1999, *PNAS*) questioned its abundance under more realistic CO\u2082/N\u2082 atmospheres.\n\n### Bucherer-Bergs pathway via \u03b1-keto acids \u2014 a key recent discovery\n\nPulletikurti, Yadav, Springsteen & Krishnamurthy (2022, *Nature Chemistry* 14, 1142) demonstrated that \u03b1-keto acids react with cyanide and ammonia sources via the **Bucherer-Bergs pathway** (not classical Strecker) to form amino acids. Specifically, **oxaloacetate + NaCN + NH\u2084HCO\u2083** produces aspartate via an **N-carbamoyl aspartate** intermediate. This route simultaneously generates **dihydroorotate**, directly paralleling biochemical pyrimidine nucleobase synthesis and elegantly linking amino acid and nucleotide pathways. Conditions are aqueous solution at room temperature to mild heating, neutral to slightly basic pH. This discovery bridges the gap between prebiotic Strecker chemistry (aldehyde-based) and biological metabolism (\u03b1-keto-acid-based).\n\n### Transamination of oxaloacetate\n\nHarrison, Webb, Rammu & Lane (2023, *Life* 13, 1177) published the most focused study on prebiotic aspartate synthesis via transamination. Cu\u00b2\u207a-catalyzed transamination of oxaloacetate by pyridoxamine achieved **~5% yield of aspartate within 1 hour** (160\u2013258 \u00b5M), operating across pH 6\u201310, 25\u201370\u00b0C, and ambient to high pressure. Metal ions tested included Cu\u00b2\u207a (best), Fe\u00b3\u207a, Mn\u00b2\u207a, and Co\u00b2\u207a, at **5\u201310 mM reactants, 50 mM NH\u2084HCO\u2083 buffer, 1 mM catalyst**. Mayer, Kaur, Rauscher & Moran (2021, *JACS* 143, 19099) and Dherbassy, Mayer, Muchowska & Moran (2023, *JACS* 145, 13357) provided kinetic and mechanistic details for non-enzymatic metal-pyridoxal transamination. The critical finding: Cu\u00b2\u207a-catalyzed transamination can initially **outcompete** OAA decarboxylation, but sustained aspartate production requires continuous OAA regeneration.\n\n### Reductive amination of oxaloacetate\n\nThis biologically parallel route (OAA + NH\u2084\u207a + [H] \u2192 aspartate) has been tested with multiple reducing systems. Hafenbradl, Keller, W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user & Stetter (1995, *Tetrahedron Lett.* 36, 5179) used FeS + H\u2082S at 100\u00b0C under anaerobic conditions but obtained low yields. Critically, Barge, Flores et al. (2019, *PNAS* 116, 4828) tested reductive amination with mixed-valence Fe(II)/Fe(III) oxyhydroxides and found that **aspartic acid was NOT obtained from oxaloacetate** \u2014 the starting material converted entirely to pyruvate (via decarboxylation) and subsequently yielded alanine and lactate. Mayer & Moran (2022, *Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.* 61, e202212237) showed OAA has intermediate reactivity for reductive amination with NaBH\u2083CN, with a rate 1.7\u00d7 faster than glutamate formation from \u03b1-ketoglutarate \u2014 but OAA decarboxylation remains the dominant competing pathway.\n\n### Michael addition of ammonia to fumarate\n\nThe biological reaction (aspartase, EC 4.3.1.1) reversibly adds NH\u2083 to fumarate yielding L-aspartate (K_m \u2248 15\u201320 mM for NH\u2084\u207a). Non-enzymatically, this reaction is thermodynamically feasible under **alkaline conditions with high NH\u2083 concentrations** at elevated temperatures, but yields are very low without enzymatic catalysis. Fumarate itself can be produced prebiotically through several routes: photocatalytic reduction of oxaloacetate to malate on ZnS surfaces followed by dehydration (Guzman & Martin, 2008, *Int. J. Astrobiol.* 7, 271); non-enzymatic rTCA cycle analogs (Muchowska, Varma & Moran, 2020, *Chem. Rev.* 120, 7708); and detection in the Murchison meteorite.\n\n### Additional routes\n\nSeveral other pathways contribute to the prebiotic aspartate inventory. **Photochemical synthesis** by Sagan & Khare (1971, *Science* 173, 417) produced aspartate from UV irradiation of CH\u2084/C\u2082H\u2086/NH\u2083/H\u2082O/H\u2082S mixtures. Mu\u00f1oz Caro et al. (2002, *Nature* 416, 403) produced 16 amino acids including aspartate from UV irradiation of interstellar ice analogs. Fox & Windsor (1970, *Science* 170, 984) obtained aspartate from heated formaldehyde and ammonia mixtures. **Hydrothermal vent synthesis** has been demonstrated by Marshall (1994, *GCA* 58, 2099) and Hennet, Holm & Engel (1992), and Amend & Shock (1998, *Science* 281, 1659) calculated that amino acid synthesis including aspartate is thermodynamically favorable in **100\u00b0C moderately reduced hydrothermal solutions**. Varma, Muchowska & Moran detected aspartate from Fe\u2070-mediated CO\u2082 reduction at 30\u2013100\u00b0C, 35 bar with hydroxylamine as nitrogen source.\n\n---\n\n## Critical intermediates and the oxaloacetate instability problem\n\n### Oxaloacetate is the central but unstable nexus\n\nOxaloacetate (OAA) sits at the heart of multiple aspartate synthesis routes (transamination, reductive amination, Bucherer-Bergs) but is **notoriously unstable**. It decarboxylates to pyruvate + CO\u2082 with a half-life of approximately **1\u20132 hours at 25\u00b0C, neutral pH** (rate constant k = 8.9 \u00d7 10\u207b\u2077 s\u207b\u00b9; Guzman & Martin, 2008). This decarboxylation follows Arrhenius behavior: log(k) = 11.74 \u2212 4956/T. Divalent metal cations **accelerate** decarboxylation following the Irving-Williams series (Mg\u00b2\u207a < Mn\u00b2\u207a < Fe\u00b2\u207a < Co\u00b2\u207a < Ni\u00b2\u207a < Cu\u00b2\u207a < Zn\u00b2\u207a), creating a paradox where the same metals that catalyze transamination also promote degradation.\n\nPrebiotic OAA can form through several routes: pyruvate + glyoxylate reactions generating 4-hydroxy-2-ketoglutarate intermediates that undergo oxidative decarboxylation (Eschenmoser & Krishnamurthy, *Nat. Commun.* 2017); iron-mediated CO\u2082 fixation pathways (Muchowska et al., 2019, *Nature* 569, 104); and as a transient intermediate in non-enzymatic rTCA cycle analogs. CO\u2082-saturated Hadean ocean conditions might partially suppress decarboxylation by Le Chatelier's principle, though this remains experimentally unvalidated.\n\n### HCN oligomers, fumarate, and branching pathways\n\n**HCN oligomers** form the alternative major pathway to aspartate. The oligomerization cascade proceeds: HCN dimer (iminoacetonitrile) \u2192 trimer (aminomalononitrile, AMN) \u2192 tetramer (diaminomaleonitrile, DAMN) \u2192 higher polymers. The tetramer DAMN is a key branch-point molecule leading to both purines and amino acids. Oligomerization requires **[HCN] > 10\u207b\u00b2 M at pH ~9.2**, achievable through eutectic freezing concentration at \u221223.4\u00b0C.\n\n**Fumarate** connects to aspartate via Michael addition and serves as a node in the rTCA cycle network. It can form from malate dehydration, ZnS-photocatalyzed reduction products (Zhou & Guzman, 2016), and succinate oxidation. **Cyanoacetylene** provides a C\u2083 building block that couples with HCN and NH\u2083 to produce both aspartate and cytosine, representing a branch point linking amino acid and nucleobase synthesis. **Glyoxylate** serves as the central C\u2082 feedstock in protometabolic TCA analogs, connecting to OAA via aldol chemistry with pyruvate.\n\nAspartate itself is a critical **nodal metabolite** in modern biochemistry \u2014 the precursor for asparagine, lysine, methionine, threonine, isoleucine, all pyrimidine nucleotides, and contributions to purine synthesis. Harrison et al. (2023) describe it as essential to any \"minimal autotrophic protometabolism.\"\n\n---\n\n## Environmental conditions favor alkaline vents and surface pools\n\n### Alkaline hydrothermal vents offer the best thermodynamic window\n\n**Lost City-type alkaline vents** operate at **40\u201390\u00b0C, pH 9\u201311**, with copious H\u2082 from serpentinization, along with CH\u2084, formate, NH\u2083, and H\u2082S. The Russell/Martin hypothesis (Russell 1993; Martin & Russell 2007, *Phil. Trans. R. Soc. B*) proposes that FeS/NiS precipitate compartments at alkaline mounds created **pH gradients of ~3 units** \u2014 mimicking the proton-motive force in modern cells \u2014 where cool, slightly acidic CO\u2082-rich Hadean ocean (pH 5\u20136) met hot, reduced alkaline fluid. Kitadai (2015, *Orig. Life Evol. Biosph.* 45, 377) calculated that mixing CO\u2082-rich seawater with H\u2082-rich alkaline fluid creates energetically favorable conditions for amino acid synthesis at an optimum of **~50\u00b0C**. Preiner et al. (2020, *Nature Ecol. Evol.* 4, 534) demonstrated H\u2082-dependent primordial carbon metabolism using greigite and magnetite catalysts.\n\n**Black smoker vents** (up to 350\u2013400\u00b0C, pH 2\u20133) provide rich transition metal catalysis (pyrite, chalcopyrite, sphalerite) and the pyrite-pulled energy source (FeS + H\u2082S \u2192 FeS\u2082 + H\u2082; \u0394G = \u22129.2 kcal/mol). However, amino acids are **irreversibly destroyed above ~240\u00b0C** (Miller & Bada, 1988, *Nature* 334, 609; Bada et al., 1995). Aspartate is among the more oxidized amino acids (high Z_C value), making its synthesis **endergonic even at 100\u00b0C** in many hydrothermal fluid compositions according to Amend & Shock's calculations \u2014 though Kitadai showed that alkaline vent mixing zones create sufficiently steep chemical gradients to overcome this.\n\n### Surface pools and atmospheric considerations\n\nWet-dry cycling in volcanic hot spring pools (Damer & Deamer, 2020, *Astrobiology* 20, 429) provides **concentration through evaporation** (up to ~1000\u00d7 enrichment), UV energy input (much higher flux on early Earth without ozone, \u03bb > 200 nm), and thermal energy for condensation reactions during drying (20\u2013120\u00b0C). Deliquescent minerals mediate effective wet-dry cycles, achieving **21.2% oligomerization yields** versus 3.5% for non-deliquescent controls after 10 cycles (Campbell & Bracher, 2019, *Nat. Commun.* 10, 4508).\n\nThe early Earth atmosphere composition remains debated. Current consensus favors a **weakly reducing to neutral atmosphere** (CO\u2082 + N\u2082 dominant, with smaller amounts of H\u2082O, H\u2082, and traces of CH\u2084/NH\u2083) rather than the strongly reducing mixture used in Miller's original experiment. Transient H\u2082-rich atmospheres after large asteroid impacts could periodically create conditions conducive to Miller-Urey synthesis. Localized reducing environments near volcanic plumes can drive amino acid synthesis even under a weakly reducing global atmosphere.\n\n---\n\n## Mineral catalysts play distinct roles at each reaction step\n\n### Iron-sulfur minerals bridge geochemistry and biochemistry\n\n**Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)** has an inverse thiospinel structure with cubic Fe\u2084S\u2084 units that are structurally identical to [4Fe-4S] clusters in ferredoxins and CODH/ACS enzymes. It is thermodynamically stable (confirmed by Navrotsky group, *PNAS* 2020), catalyzes CO\u2082 reduction to small organics, and can promote the CO\u2082 fixation steps that generate oxaloacetate precursors. Santos-Carballal et al. (2018, *Phil. Trans. R. Soc. A*) modeled CO\u2082 reactivity on greigite surfaces by DFT.\n\n**Pyrite (FeS\u2082)** provides the thermodynamic driving force for W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user's surface metabolism (FeS + H\u2082S \u2192 FeS\u2082 + H\u2082; \u0394G = \u22129.2 kcal/mol). Hafenbradl et al. (1995) demonstrated amino acid synthesis by reductive amination of \u03b1-oxo acids coupled to pyrite formation. A remarkable recent finding: natural pyrite **photocatalytically drives reductive amination** of keto acids with **14.5\u201342.4% enantiomeric excess for D-amino acids** via wavy surface atom arrangements (*Nat. Commun.* 2024).\n\n**Mackinawite (FeS)** \u2014 a layered iron sulfide and precursor to greigite \u2014 reduces CO\u2082 to CO at >300\u00b0C and catalyzes H\u2082-driven CO\u2082 reduction to methanol at **80\u2013120\u00b0C** when doped with Mn (5\u00d7 enhancement) or illuminated with UV-visible light (*Nat. Commun.* 2024). Its semiconductor properties enable photo-assisted catalysis relevant to the earliest steps of carbon fixation.\n\n### Clay minerals concentrate and catalyze\n\n**Montmorillonite** catalyzes oligomerization of activated nucleotides to 40\u201355-mers (Ferris & Ertem, 1992, *Science* 257, 1387), amino acid polymerization under wet-dry cycling (Lahav et al., 1978, *Science* 201, 67), and specifically the formation of glycyl-aspartic acid dipeptides from glycine and aspartate at **85 \u00b1 5\u00b0C** (Kalra/Pant et al., *Int. J. Astrobiol.*). Notably, linear and cyclic aspartate-only peptides were NOT formed, indicating distinct reactivity for aspartate on clay surfaces. Montmorillonite interlayers create **nano-confined environments** distinct from bulk solution, providing locally anhydrous conditions that protect from hydrolysis.\n\n### Photocatalysts and transition metal ions\n\n**ZnS** (sphalerite, band gap ~3.6 eV) photocatalyzes **reversible amination of \u03b1-keto acids** under UV (~360 nm) irradiation, including oxaloacetate \u2192 aspartate (Wang et al., 2011\u20132013; Guzman & Martin, 2008). Chiral mesostructured ZnS can drive CO\u2082 + NH\u2083 \u2192 amino acids with **>96% enantiomeric excess** via spin-polarized electron transfer. **TiO\u2082** (rutile/anatase, band gap 3.0\u20133.2 eV) enhances amino acid polymerization (23% increase with anatase) and converts formamide to nucleoside bases under UV.\n\n**Cu\u00b2\u207a** is the most efficient non-enzymatic transamination catalyst (Harrison et al., 2023). **Fe\u2070** reduces CO\u2082 to pyruvate and acetate at 30\u2013100\u00b0C, 35 bar, generating aspartate when hydroxylamine is present as nitrogen source (Varma et al., 2018, *Nat. Ecol. Evol.*). **Ni\u2070** catalyzes a prebiotic Krebs cycle analog generating amino acids from H\u2082 + NH\u2083 (Kaur et al., 2024, *Chem* 10, 1528). FeS/NiS co-catalyzes thioester synthesis (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1997).\n\n---\n\n## Meteoritic and extraterrestrial evidence confirms abiotic aspartate formation\n\nAspartate is consistently detected in carbonaceous chondrites. In the **Murchison meteorite**, modern analyses by Glavin et al. report **L-aspartate at 1.7 \u00b1 0.1 nmol/g** and **D-aspartate at 0.95 \u00b1 0.04 nmol/g**. The **Tagish Lake meteorite** shows remarkably large L-enantiomeric excesses of **~60% for aspartate**, confirmed as extraterrestrial by \u03b4\u00b9\u00b3C enrichments (+24\u2030 D, +29\u2030 L). The Aguas Zarcas meteorite shows **~28% L-ee** for aspartate. Chimiak et al. (2022, *Geochim. Cosmochim. Acta* 321, 78) used position-specific carbon isotope analysis of Murchison aspartate and found signatures consistent with Strecker synthesis origins. Over **90 amino acids** have been identified in Murchison, with glycine most abundant and aspartate present at lower but significant concentrations. Mu\u00f1oz Caro et al. (2002, *Nature* 416, 403) produced 16 amino acids including aspartate from UV irradiation of interstellar ice analogs (H\u2082O/CO\u2082/CO/CH\u2083OH/NH\u2083), demonstrating that extraterrestrial aspartate formation is experimentally reproducible.\n\n---\n\n## Six major unresolved challenges constrain prebiotic aspartate synthesis\n\n### The oxaloacetate decarboxylation race\n\nThe single greatest bottleneck is that **OAA decarboxylates to pyruvate faster than it can be aminated to aspartate** under most tested conditions. Barge et al. (2019) showed this definitively: iron oxyhydroxide experiments yielded alanine (from pyruvate, the OAA decomposition product) rather than aspartate. The ~5% transamination yield achieved by Harrison et al. (2023) requires the reaction to outpace decarboxylation in the first hour, but sustained production demands continuous OAA regeneration \u2014 something not yet demonstrated in a cyclic, self-sustaining manner. The glyoxylate-mediated OAA generation pathway (Eschenmoser & Krishnamurthy, *Nat. Commun.* 2017) works but requires relatively high concentrations and H\u2082O\u2082 as oxidant.\n\n### Chirality remains without a definitive solution\n\nAll major prebiotic routes produce **racemic aspartate**. Known symmetry-breaking mechanisms include circularly polarized UV light (~1\u20132% ee in aminonitrile precursors), chiral mineral surfaces, and kinetic resolution via dipeptide-mediated transamination (Dherbassy/Moran group, *PNAS* 2024). The most aspartate-specific mechanism is **differential adsorption on calcite**: Hazen et al. (2001, *PNAS* 98, 5487) showed D-aspartate forms 3 strong bonds on calcite (214) surfaces (~8 kcal/mol lower energy than L-aspartate with 2 bonds), enabling chiral separation on mirror-related scalenohedral faces. Aspartate's ability to form **conglomerate enantiopure crystals** (unlike alanine's racemic crystals) provides a plausible amplification mechanism. Racemization half-lives are approximately **3,500\u201315,000 years at 25\u00b0C** (Bada & Schroeder), with aspartate racemizing faster than most amino acids via a succinimide intermediate.\n\n### The concentration problem\n\nEstimated steady-state amino acid concentrations in the prebiotic ocean are ~10\u207b\u2079 M \u2014 orders of magnitude below the mM concentrations used in most published experiments. Strecker synthesis requires [HCN] > 10\u207b\u00b2 M; peptide bond formation needs mM amino acid concentrations. Solutions include evaporative concentration in pools (up to 1000\u00d7), eutectic freezing (HCN concentrates to ~10 M at \u221223.4\u00b0C), mineral adsorption, aerosol enrichment, and submarine vent gradients. Whether protometabolic cycles can operate at ocean-relevant dilutions remains largely untested.\n\n### Thermal stability limits viable environments\n\nAspartate decomposes via deamination (\u2192 fumarate + NH\u2083) and decarboxylation (\u2192 \u03b2-alanine + CO\u2082). At **240\u2013250\u00b0C**, decomposition is rapid and irreversible (Miller & Bada, 1988). Activation energies range from **88.5\u2013137.4 kJ/mol** for amino acid decomposition at 160\u2013240\u00b0C (Hou et al., 2024, *Sci. Rep.*). At 100\u00b0C, half-lives are on the order of thousands of years, making alkaline vents (40\u201390\u00b0C) far more favorable than black smokers (>300\u00b0C). Solid-state decomposition occurs at ~270\u00b0C (\u0394H_f = \u2212973 kJ/mol). Protection by mineral adsorption, vesicle encapsulation, and peptide incorporation can extend stability.\n\n### Competing reactions and pathway selectivity\n\nHCN polymerization converts the vast majority of starting material to intractable \"tar\" rather than useful amino acids. Maillard-type reactions between amino acids and sugars produce complex brown polymers. Aspartate undergoes cyclization to succinimide intermediates, leading to \u03b2-aspartate isomers and accelerated racemization. In aqueous solution, hydrolysis of peptide bonds overwhelmingly outcompetes condensation at hydrothermal temperatures.\n\n### Key experimentally undemonstrated steps\n\nThe following remain as the weakest links in proposed pathways:\n\n- Sustained OAA production from CO\u2082 fixation under prebiotically plausible conditions without enzymes or ATP\n- A complete, self-sustaining non-enzymatic rTCA cycle with turnover (9 of 11 intermediates demonstrated individually by Muchowska et al. 2019, but not as a running cycle)\n- Prebiotic synthesis of pyridoxamine, required for the most efficient transamination route\n- Operation of any protometabolic aspartate synthesis at ocean-relevant dilute concentrations\n- Experimental validation that Hadean CO\u2082 saturation suppresses OAA decarboxylation\n\n---\n\n## Conclusion: converging pathways, persistent gaps\n\nThe prebiotic synthesis landscape for aspartic acid is richer than often appreciated, with HCN oligomer hydrolysis and the Bucherer-Bergs pathway from \u03b1-keto acids standing out as the most productive and most elegant routes, respectively. **HCN oligomerization uniquely yields aspartate as a major product** alongside glycine \u2014 not a trace component \u2014 making it the most efficient single route. The **Bucherer-Bergs pathway** (Pulletikurti et al., 2022) simultaneously generates aspartate and dihydroorotate, linking amino acid and pyrimidine nucleotide synthesis in a single reaction network. For network design in an agentic AI system, these two pathways should be prioritized as primary aspartate sources.\n\nThe protometabolic routes via oxaloacetate (transamination, reductive amination) face the fundamental kinetic barrier of OAA decarboxylation but achieve biological relevance through Cu\u00b2\u207a/pyridoxamine catalysis at ~5% yields in one hour. The most plausible integrated scenario combines **alkaline vent CO\u2082 fixation** (Fe/Ni catalysts, 40\u201390\u00b0C) to generate keto acid intermediates, **rapid transamination or Bucherer-Bergs conversion** before OAA degrades, and **transport to lower-temperature environments** (surface pools, clay surfaces) for concentration via wet-dry cycling and chiral selection on calcite. The three unresolved challenges that most constrain pathway viability are OAA stabilization, operation at realistic dilutions, and the origin of homochirality \u2014 each representing a frontier where new experimental work could transform our understanding of how this metabolically essential amino acid first emerged on the prebiotic Earth.\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH ===\n\nConsider how well the network aligns with this literature in your evaluation.\n\n\nPlease evaluate the network and respond with JSON:\n{\n    \"p