yde in one step is not a well-defined hydrothermal transformation. The rest of the pathway benefits from the strong Bucherer-Bergs end step, but upstream feedstock generation is too compressed.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_001\",\n        \"rxn_005\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Split rxn_001 into more defensible carbon fixation steps such as formate/formaldehyde formation followed by C-C coupling\",\n        \"Better justify how HCN derived at the surface contributes to the Bucherer-Bergs chemistry on returning to pool conditions\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_001\": 0.45,\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.6,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.9,\n        \"rxn_007\": 0.88\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.72,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.81,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.88,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.9,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.79,\n      \"feedback\": \"This pathway effectively links hydrothermal carbonyl generation to surface HCN chemistry and then to hydrolysis, but it relies on two oversimplified feedstock steps. The downstream HCN oligomer section is strong; the upstream hydrothermal-to-HCN conversion logic is much less literature-grounded. As a result, it is an attractive systems narrative but not among the most chemically secure pathways.\",\n      \"approved\": false,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [\n        \"rxn_001\",\n        \"rxn_005\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Use atmospheric or photochemical HCN generation independently of formaldehyde feedstock unless a specific mechanistic link is justified\",\n        \"Retain the oligomer-hydrolysis core as the primary validated component\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_002\": 0.8,\n        \"rxn_003\": 0.55,\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.72,\n        \"rxn_012\": 0