thermal reactions are too lumped or insufficiently supported in the exact forms written, especially direct CO2-to-formaldehyde/glycolaldehyde feedstock production and the one-step glyoxylate/OAA generation sequence. The OAA instability problem, which is the major literature bottleneck, is recognized implicitly by inclusion of decarboxylation but not fully handled mechanistically. The fumarate branch is especially weak. There is also a significant literature-gap issue around pyridoxamine availability, which the network uses as an input without justification.\\n\\nEnvironmental interconnection is good overall, but the evaluation is limited by missing mineral-agent detail in the summarized network presentation. Because the system instructions require mineral agents for all hydrothermal and surface reactions, this omission would be a formal compliance problem unless the original full JSON included them. Literature alignment is good but not perfect: the network captures the right major routes, yet some reactions would need tighter condition fidelity and explicit citations to fully satisfy the specification.\\n\\nOverall, this is a good but not approval-grade network. It is coherent, connected, and largely literature-informed, but it falls short of >=0.9 confidence because several critical steps are oversimplified and some pathway claims exceed current experimental support.\",\n  \"hub_quality\": 0.9,\n  \"convergence_quality\": 0.88\n}", "parsed_response": {"pathway_evaluations": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "reaction_scores": {"rxn_005": 0.6, "rxn_006": 0.9, "rxn_007": 0.88}, "chemical_feasibility": 0.82, "pathway_coherence": 0.9, "environmental_progression": 0.84, "target_achievement": 0.9, "overall_confidence": 0.86, "feedback": "This is one of the strongest pathways in the network and aligns well with literature prioritizing HCN oligomer hydrolysis as a major aspartate source. HCN oligomerization to DAMN/higher polymers is well supported, and hydrolysis of oligomers yieldin