quired surface mineral agents as a constrained proxy for semiconductor photocatalysis (Guzman & Martin, 2008; Zhou & Guzman, 2016)."}, {"id": "rxn_018", "name": "Dehydration of malate to fumarate", "inputs": ["mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_012"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null, null], "conditions": {"temperature": "300-370K", "pressure": "ambient", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "variable", "other": "thermal dehydration or drying-interface conversion"}, "mechanism": "Malate loses water to generate fumarate, establishing the unsaturated dicarboxylate branch relevant to aspartate chemistry.", "reasoning": "This step follows the literature-supported malate-to-fumarate sequence used in non-enzymatic rTCA analog discussion and avoids the previously criticized unsupported direct OAA-to-fumarate shortcut (Guzman & Martin, 2008; Muchowska, Varma & Moran, 2020)."}, {"id": "rxn_019", "name": "Non-enzymatic Michael addition of ammonia to fumarate giving aspartate", "inputs": ["mol_012", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_013"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [null, null], "conditions": {"temperature": "elevated but below destructive range", "pressure": "ambient", "catalyst": null, "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline conditions with high NH3 concentration; low-yield thermodynamically feasible reaction"}, "mechanism": "Ammonia adds across the activated alkene of fumarate to produce aspartate through the reverse of the biological aspartase transformation.", "reasoning": "This route is documented as thermodynamically feasible but low-yield without enzymatic catalysis; it is therefore included as a weak but literature-supported terminal path rather than overclaimed as a major source (Muchowska, Varma & Moran, 2020; Harrison et al., 2023 background discussion)."}, {"id": "rxn_020", "name": "Wet-dry clay-assisted peptide formation from glycine and aspartate", "inputs": ["mol_024", "mol_013"], "outputs": ["mol_025"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": ["montmorill