{"timestamp": "2026-04-19T13:31:10.744337", "agent_name": "SynthesisNetworkAgent", "method_name": "generate_synthesis_network", "step": null, "attempt": null, "system_message": "\n# SYNTHESIS NETWORK AGENT - Complete Prebiotic Synthesis Network Generation\n\nYou are an expert prebiotic geochemist who designs complete synthesis networks from simple\nmolecules to complex biomolecules. You synthesize knowledge across three terrestrial prebiotic\nenvironments:\n\n1. **Hydrothermal Environments** (350-600K, high pressure, deep-sea vents)\n2. **Surface Environments** (300-370K, ambient pressure, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure)\n3. **Biochemical/Prebiotic** (variable conditions, complex biomolecule assembly)\n\nYour task is to generate a COMPLETE SYNTHESIS NETWORK in a SINGLE response - not individual steps.\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 1: HYDROTHERMAL ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nDeep-sea alkaline hydrothermal vents and iron-sulfur world chemistry. High pressure,\ntemperatures between 350-600K, pH gradients across vent walls, and abundant mineral catalysts.\nThis environment provides the reducing power and mineral surfaces for carbon fixation and\nearly metabolic reactions.\n\n## Environments\n- **Alkaline Hydrothermal Vents**: 350-450K, pH 9-11, H\u2082-rich, serpentinization-driven\n- **Black Smoker Vents**: 500-650K, acidic, metal-sulfide rich\n- **Subseafloor Hydrothermal**: 370-470K, moderate pH, rock-water interactions\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Hydrothermal reactions)\n- **Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)**: CO\u2082 reduction to formate/acetate, analog of [Fe\u2084S\u2084] clusters\n- **Magnetite (Fe\u2083O\u2084)**: Fischer-Tropsch-type synthesis, CO\u2082 hydrogenation\n- **Pyrite (FeS\u2082)**: Surface-catalyzed reactions, electron donor\n- **Elemental Iron (Fe\u2070)**: Strong reductant for CO\u2082 fixation\n- **Mackinawite (FeS)**: Precursor to greigite, CO\u2082 reduction\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **CO\u2082 Reduction on Greigite**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 HCOO\u207b (formate), then \u2192 CH\u2083COO\u207b (acetate) (350-400K)\n2. **Reductive Amination**: Pyruvate + NH\u2083 \u2192 Alanine (on mineral surfaces, 350-400K)\n3. **Carbon Fixation (Acetyl-CoA analog)**: CO\u2082 + CO + H\u2082 \u2192 activated acetyl (on FeNiS, 350-400K)\n4. **Serpentinization Products**: Olivine + H\u2082O \u2192 serpentine + H\u2082 + organics (370-470K)\n5. **Iron-Sulfur Catalysis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082S \u2192 organics on FeS/FeS\u2082 surfaces\n6. **Pyruvate Synthesis**: CO\u2082 + H\u2082 \u2192 pyruvate (on magnetite/greigite, 350-400K)\n7. **Alkaline Vent pH Gradient**: \u0394pH drives phosphorylation and condensation reactions\n8. **Fischer-Tropsch-type**: CO + H\u2082 \u2192 hydrocarbons, alcohols, aldehydes (on magnetite, 400-500K)\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 2: SURFACE ENVIRONMENTS\n\n## Context\nAmbient pressure, temperatures between 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, UV exposure, and evaporitic\npools. This environment drives condensation reactions, photochemistry, and concentration-dependent\nchemistry that cannot occur in dilute hydrothermal settings.\n\n## Environments\n- **Evaporitic Pools**: 300-370K, wet-dry cycles, mineral-rich shores\n- **Volcanic Hot Springs**: 320-370K, acidic, sulfur-rich, boron minerals\n- **Tidal Flats**: 280-330K, periodic wetting/drying, UV exposure\n- **Subaerial Geothermal Fields**: 300-370K, steam vents, mineral surfaces\n\n## Mineral Catalysts (REQUIRED for Surface reactions)\n- **Montmorillonite (clay)**: Catalyzes polymerization, concentrates organics\n- **Phosphate Minerals (apatite, struvite)**: Phosphorylation reactions\n- **Borate Minerals (colemanite, ulexite)**: Stabilize ribose and sugars\n- **Sulfide Minerals (stibnite, molybdenite)**: Cyanosulfidic chemistry\n- **TiO\u2082 (anatase/rutile)**: UV photocatalysis\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Strecker Synthesis**: RCHO + NH\u2083 + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-amino acids (300-370K, aqueous)\n2. **HCN Oligomerization**: 5 HCN \u2192 adenine; 4 HCN \u2192 DAMN \u2192 nucleobases (300-350K)\n3. **Powell-Sutherland Cyanosulfidic Pathways**: HCN + H\u2082S + UV \u2192 nucleotide precursors\n4. **Formose Reaction**: n H\u2082CO \u2192 sugars (300-370K, with Ca(OH)\u2082 or borate)\n5. **Wet-Dry Cycling**: amino acids \u2192 peptides (concentration + dehydration + clay)\n6. **UV Photochemistry**: HCN + H\u2082O + UV \u2192 formamide \u2192 nucleobases\n7. **Phosphorylation**: organics + phosphate minerals \u2192 phosphorylated compounds (dry heat)\n8. **Aldol Condensation**: glycolaldehyde + glyceraldehyde \u2192 sugars\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 3: BIOCHEMICAL/PREBIOTIC\n\n## Context\nFinal assembly of complex biomolecules under plausible prebiotic scenarios. This stage connects\nthe products of Hydrothermal and Surface environments into biologically relevant macromolecules\nand proto-metabolic cycles. Variable conditions including pools, interfaces, and mineral surfaces.\n\n## Environments\n- **Prebiotic Pools**: Concentrated solutions of amino acids, nucleotides, lipids\n- **Mineral Interfaces**: Clay surfaces, iron oxide surfaces for template-directed synthesis\n- **Lipid Membranes**: Protocell-like compartments for concentrated chemistry\n- **Geothermal Cycling**: Repeated heating/cooling for selection and amplification\n\n## Key Reaction Types\n1. **Peptide Bond Formation**: amino acids \u2192 dipeptides \u2192 oligopeptides (on clay, wet-dry)\n2. **Nucleotide Assembly**: nucleobase + ribose + phosphate \u2192 nucleotide\n3. **Template-Directed Polymerization**: nucleotides \u2192 oligonucleotides (on mineral surfaces)\n4. **Lipid Membrane Formation**: fatty acids \u2192 vesicles \u2192 protocells\n5. **Proto-metabolic Cycles**: reductive TCA cycle analogs, autocatalytic networks\n6. **Transamination**: \u03b1-keto acid + amino acid \u2192 new amino acid + new keto acid\n7. **Glycosylation**: nucleobase + ribose \u2192 nucleoside\n8. **Decarboxylation**: pyruvate \u2192 acetaldehyde + CO\u2082 (thermal, 350-400K)\n\n## Critical Constraints\n- NO molecular oxygen (anoxic early Earth)\n- Strong UV radiation (no ozone layer)\n- Iron abundant in reduced form (Fe\u00b2\u207a)\n- Products from Hydrothermal AND Surface environments are available as inputs\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 4: NETWORK STRUCTURE REQUIREMENTS\n\nYour output must be a BIPARTITE GRAPH with two distinct node types:\n\n## 1. MOLECULE NODES\n- Represent chemical species (substrates, products, intermediates)\n- Each molecule appears ONCE in the network, even if used by multiple reactions\n- Include: id, formula, IUPAC name, common name, InChI, role, environment_formed\n\n## 2. REACTION NODES\n- Each reaction is a separate node with a unique ID (e.g., \"rxn_001\")\n- Has INPUT molecules (reactants) and OUTPUT molecules (products)\n- Includes: id, name, inputs[], outputs[], environment, agents[], conditions, mechanism, reasoning\n- **CRITICAL**: Every reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST specify mineral agents\n\n## KEY DESIGN PRINCIPLES\n\n### 1. HUB MOLECULES (CRITICAL)\nIdentify 3-5 key intermediates that serve as network hubs:\n- These molecules are products of SOME reactions AND reactants in OTHERS\n- Hub molecules create network density and multiple pathways\n- Good hubs: \u03b1-keto acids (pyruvate), aminonitriles, aldehydes (formaldehyde, glycolaldehyde), HCN, formate\n\n### 2. CONVERGENT PATHWAYS\nDesign multiple routes to key intermediates:\n- At least 2-3 different reaction sequences should lead to the same hub\n- This creates redundancy and alternative synthesis routes\n- Different environmental routes to same target (e.g., Hydrothermal pyruvate synthesis vs Surface Strecker)\n\n### 3. ENVIRONMENTAL INTERCONNECTION\nModel cross-environment flow:\n- Products of Hydrothermal reactions (formate, glycolate, pyruvate) become inputs for Surface reactions\n- Products of Surface reactions (amino acids, nucleobases) become inputs for Biochemical assembly\n- Hydrothermal and Surface environments can feed each other bidirectionally\n\n### 4. MINERAL AGENT SPECIFICATION\nEvery reaction in Hydrothermal or Surface environments MUST include specific mineral agents:\n- Hydrothermal: greigite, magnetite, pyrite, elemental iron, mackinawite\n- Surface: montmorillonite, phosphate minerals, borate minerals, TiO\u2082\n\n### 5. METABOLIC RELEVANCE\nFocus on prebiotically plausible intermediates:\n- \u03b1-keto acids (central metabolic hubs)\n- Amino acid precursors (aminonitriles, \u03b1-hydroxy acids)\n- Sugar precursors (glycolaldehyde, glyceraldehyde)\n- Nitrogen carriers (ammonia, hydroxylamine, HCN)\n\n### 6. REACTION DIVERSITY\nInclude multiple reaction types:\n- Reductive amination, transamination, decarboxylation\n- Strecker synthesis, aldol condensation\n- Hydrolysis, reduction, oxidation, photochemistry\n\n## NETWORK TOPOLOGY REQUIREMENTS\n\n- Minimum 8-15 molecule nodes\n- Minimum 6-12 reaction nodes\n- At least 3 hub molecules with degree \u2265 3 (connected to 3+ reactions)\n- At least 2 convergent points where multiple pathways meet\n- No isolated subgraphs - all nodes must be connected\n- Environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 5: REQUIRED JSON OUTPUT FORMAT\n\nYou MUST output a JSON object with this exact structure:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"<name of target>\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"<high-level explanation of the synthesis approach>\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"<chemical formula>\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"<IUPAC name>\",\n      \"common_name\": \"<common name or null>\",\n      \"inchi\": \"<InChI string or null>\",\n      \"role\": \"<starting | intermediate | hub_intermediate | target>\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical | null>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive reaction name>\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_003\"],\n      \"environment\": \"<Hydrothermal | Surface | Biochemical>\",\n      \"agents\": [\"<mineral catalyst 1>\", \"<mineral catalyst 2 or null>\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"<e.g., 350-400K>\",\n        \"pressure\": \"<e.g., high, 1 atm>\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"<e.g., greigite, or null>\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"<true | false>\",\n        \"other\": \"<additional conditions>\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"<brief mechanism description>\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"<scientific justification>\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"<descriptive pathway name>\",\n      \"description\": \"<pathway description>\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_007\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n# SECTION 6: LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS (when research findings are provided)\n\n**CRITICAL: When deep research findings are provided, they are your PRIMARY source of truth.**\nYour network design MUST be grounded in the provided literature. Do NOT invent pathways or conditions\nthat contradict or ignore the research findings.\n\n1. **STRICTLY FOLLOW the literature findings** in your network design:\n   - Your synthesis routes MUST match the pathways described in the research\n   - Use the EXACT reaction conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts) documented in cited studies\n   - Follow established prebiotic pathways as described in the research \u2014 do not substitute your own assumptions\n   - If the research identifies specific intermediates, you MUST use those intermediates in your network\n\n2. **CITE papers** in the \"reasoning\" field of EVERY reaction:\n   - Reference specific studies by author and year, e.g., \"(Huber & Wachtershauser, 1997)\"\n   - When multiple studies support a reaction, cite the most relevant ones\n   - If a reaction has no literature support from the provided research, explicitly state it is speculative and justify why it is necessary\n\n3. **DO NOT deviate from provided research**: If the literature identifies specific synthesis routes, environmental conditions, or key intermediates for the target molecule, your network MUST incorporate them. Only add reactions beyond the literature when necessary to complete the network (e.g., connecting known pathways)\n\n4. **ADDRESS gaps**: If the research identifies open questions or challenges, acknowledge them in your reasoning and propose how your network addresses them\n\n---\n\n# IMPORTANT GUIDELINES\n\n1. Generate the ENTIRE network in one response - do not propose individual steps\n2. Ensure molecules are defined BEFORE being referenced in reactions\n3. Every molecule ID in reactions must exist in the molecules array\n4. Hub molecules must have both incoming AND outgoing reactions\n5. Pathways must trace valid routes through the reaction network\n6. Consider realistic prebiotic conditions at each stage\n7. Include rate-limiting or key bottleneck reactions\n8. The network should tell a coherent chemical story from simple to complex\n9. Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n10. Show environmental interconnection: products from one environment feed into another\n11. When deep research findings are provided, cite relevant literature in reaction reasoning fields\n", "user_message": "\nGenerate a SYNTHESIS NETWORK for: Aspartic-Acid\n\nREQUIREMENTS:\n- Generate a bipartite network with molecule nodes and reaction nodes\n- Include 10 distinct pathways to the target\n- Identify 3-5 hub molecules where pathways converge\n- Ensure at least 8-15 molecules and 6-12 reactions\n- Show environmental interconnection: Hydrothermal \u2194 Surface \u2192 Biochemical\n- Every Hydrothermal and Surface reaction MUST include mineral agents in the \"agents\" field\n- Design multiple environmental routes to the same target where possible\n\nOutput the complete network as JSON following the schema in your instructions.\n\n\n=== LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\nThe following deep research report contains peer-reviewed literature on prebiotic synthesis\nof Aspartic-Acid. Your network design MUST be based on these findings.\n\n=== DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n# Prebiotic synthesis of aspartic acid: routes, evidence, and open challenges\n\n**Aspartic acid ranks among the most metabolically central yet prebiotically elusive amino acids.** At least 10 distinct prebiotic routes have been proposed or demonstrated, ranging from HCN oligomer hydrolysis \u2014 where aspartate emerges as a major product \u2014 to metal-catalyzed transamination of oxaloacetate, which mimics the biological pathway but battles the rapid decarboxylation of its precursor. The core tension in prebiotic aspartate chemistry is that the most biologically relevant pathways (via oxaloacetate) face severe kinetic competition from degradation, while the most productive abiotic routes (HCN oligomerization, spark discharge) operate through entirely different mechanisms. This report synthesizes the full landscape of published research on prebiotic aspartate formation, organized to guide synthesis network design and pathway evaluation in an agentic AI system for prebiotic chemistry.\n\n---\n\n## Known prebiotic routes span at least 10 distinct pathways\n\n### Strecker synthesis\n\nThe classical Strecker route proceeds through aldehyde + NH\u2083 \u2192 imine (Schiff base), then imine + HCN \u2192 \u03b1-aminonitrile, and finally hydrolysis of the aminonitrile to the amino acid. For aspartate, this requires a **C3 aldehyde bearing a carboxyl group** (such as 3-oxopropanoic acid or a related functionalized aldehyde), making the Strecker route to aspartate less straightforward than for glycine or alanine. Miller (1957, *Biochim. Biophys. Acta* 23, 480) established that spark discharge amino acid synthesis proceeds via this Strecker mechanism in the aqueous phase. Conditions are aqueous solution, **pH 7\u20139, room temperature to moderate heat**, with reaction times of hours to days. The prebiotic availability of the specific C4 aldehyde precursor for aspartate remains poorly constrained, representing a significant gap in this pathway.\n\n### Miller-Urey spark discharge\n\nMiller's original 1953 experiment (*Science* 117, 528) used CH\u2084 (200 torr), NH\u2083 (200 torr), H\u2082 (100 torr), and H\u2082O with Tesla coil spark discharge for one week. Aspartic acid was tentatively identified as spot #1 on the 2D paper chromatogram, though Miller's more rigorous 1955 analysis (*JACS* 77, 2351) reclassified this spot as likely **iminodiacetic acid**. The yield of aspartate, when confirmed, was approximately **0.024% relative to carbon input** \u2014 far below glycine at ~2.1%.\n\nModern reanalysis of Miller's archived samples transformed our understanding. Johnson et al. (2008, *Science* 322, 404) reanalyzed volcanic apparatus vials using HPLC-ToF-MS, detecting **22 amino acids and 5 amines** including confirmed D,L-aspartate. Parker et al. (2011, *PNAS* 108, 5526) reanalyzed Miller's unpublished 1958 H\u2082S experiment (CH\u2084/NH\u2083/H\u2082S/CO\u2082 atmosphere), finding **23 amino acids and 4 amines** including 7 organosulfur compounds. Aspartate was present at relatively low abundances, and the H\u2082S experiment produced yields an **order of magnitude higher** than the classic apparatus for many amino acids. Cleaves et al. (2008, *Orig. Life Evol. Biosph.* 38, 105) showed that adding oxidation inhibitors (pyrite, ascorbic acid, FeSO\u2084) to neutral atmosphere (CO\u2082/N\u2082) spark discharge experiments boosted amino acid yields by factors of **2\u2013100\u00d7**.\n\n### HCN oligomerization \u2014 the most productive route for aspartate\n\nHCN oligomerization followed by hydrolysis is the single most productive prebiotic route specifically for aspartate. Ferris, Donner & Lobo (1974, *J. Mol. Evol.* 3, 225) demonstrated that the **major amino acids** released on hydrolysis of HCN oligomers were **glycine, aspartate, and diaminosuccinic acid** \u2014 making aspartate a dominant product rather than a trace component. Ferris et al. (1978, *J. Mol. Evol.* 11, 293) confirmed this using 0.1 M HCN solutions at pH 9.2, where oligomers form over days to weeks and yield amino acids upon acid hydrolysis (6N HCl, 110\u00b0C, 24h). Matthews & Moser (1966, *PNAS* 56, 1087) independently detected glycine, alanine, and aspartic acid from HCN polymerization in aqueous ammonia. Frozen HCN solutions (\u221220 to \u221278\u00b0C) concentrated at the eutectic point (~10 M HCN at \u221223.4\u00b0C) also produce aspartate upon oligomer hydrolysis (Miyakawa, Cleaves & Miller, 2002, *Orig. Life Evol. Biosph.* 32, 195). The mechanism likely involves **5-carboxymethylidenehydantoin**, a cyclic intermediate specifically related to aspartate identified in HCN oligomer mixtures.\n\n### Cyanoacetylene route\n\nSanchez, Ferris & Orgel (1966, *Science* 154, 784) showed that cyanoacetylene (HC\u2261C-C\u2261N) \u2014 a major nitrogen-containing product of electric discharge in CH\u2084/N\u2082 mixtures (up to 8.4% of HCN yield) \u2014 reacts with HCN and NH\u2083 in aqueous solution at **pH ~9, room temperature** to produce **aspartic acid, asparagine, and cytosine**. This C\u2083 + C\u2081 coupling pathway is distinct from Strecker chemistry. However, cyanoacetylene production is suppressed when NH\u2083 or H\u2082S are present in the discharge, and Shapiro (1999, *PNAS*) questioned its abundance under more realistic CO\u2082/N\u2082 atmospheres.\n\n### Bucherer-Bergs pathway via \u03b1-keto acids \u2014 a key recent discovery\n\nPulletikurti, Yadav, Springsteen & Krishnamurthy (2022, *Nature Chemistry* 14, 1142) demonstrated that \u03b1-keto acids react with cyanide and ammonia sources via the **Bucherer-Bergs pathway** (not classical Strecker) to form amino acids. Specifically, **oxaloacetate + NaCN + NH\u2084HCO\u2083** produces aspartate via an **N-carbamoyl aspartate** intermediate. This route simultaneously generates **dihydroorotate**, directly paralleling biochemical pyrimidine nucleobase synthesis and elegantly linking amino acid and nucleotide pathways. Conditions are aqueous solution at room temperature to mild heating, neutral to slightly basic pH. This discovery bridges the gap between prebiotic Strecker chemistry (aldehyde-based) and biological metabolism (\u03b1-keto-acid-based).\n\n### Transamination of oxaloacetate\n\nHarrison, Webb, Rammu & Lane (2023, *Life* 13, 1177) published the most focused study on prebiotic aspartate synthesis via transamination. Cu\u00b2\u207a-catalyzed transamination of oxaloacetate by pyridoxamine achieved **~5% yield of aspartate within 1 hour** (160\u2013258 \u00b5M), operating across pH 6\u201310, 25\u201370\u00b0C, and ambient to high pressure. Metal ions tested included Cu\u00b2\u207a (best), Fe\u00b3\u207a, Mn\u00b2\u207a, and Co\u00b2\u207a, at **5\u201310 mM reactants, 50 mM NH\u2084HCO\u2083 buffer, 1 mM catalyst**. Mayer, Kaur, Rauscher & Moran (2021, *JACS* 143, 19099) and Dherbassy, Mayer, Muchowska & Moran (2023, *JACS* 145, 13357) provided kinetic and mechanistic details for non-enzymatic metal-pyridoxal transamination. The critical finding: Cu\u00b2\u207a-catalyzed transamination can initially **outcompete** OAA decarboxylation, but sustained aspartate production requires continuous OAA regeneration.\n\n### Reductive amination of oxaloacetate\n\nThis biologically parallel route (OAA + NH\u2084\u207a + [H] \u2192 aspartate) has been tested with multiple reducing systems. Hafenbradl, Keller, W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user & Stetter (1995, *Tetrahedron Lett.* 36, 5179) used FeS + H\u2082S at 100\u00b0C under anaerobic conditions but obtained low yields. Critically, Barge, Flores et al. (2019, *PNAS* 116, 4828) tested reductive amination with mixed-valence Fe(II)/Fe(III) oxyhydroxides and found that **aspartic acid was NOT obtained from oxaloacetate** \u2014 the starting material converted entirely to pyruvate (via decarboxylation) and subsequently yielded alanine and lactate. Mayer & Moran (2022, *Angew. Chem. Int. Ed.* 61, e202212237) showed OAA has intermediate reactivity for reductive amination with NaBH\u2083CN, with a rate 1.7\u00d7 faster than glutamate formation from \u03b1-ketoglutarate \u2014 but OAA decarboxylation remains the dominant competing pathway.\n\n### Michael addition of ammonia to fumarate\n\nThe biological reaction (aspartase, EC 4.3.1.1) reversibly adds NH\u2083 to fumarate yielding L-aspartate (K_m \u2248 15\u201320 mM for NH\u2084\u207a). Non-enzymatically, this reaction is thermodynamically feasible under **alkaline conditions with high NH\u2083 concentrations** at elevated temperatures, but yields are very low without enzymatic catalysis. Fumarate itself can be produced prebiotically through several routes: photocatalytic reduction of oxaloacetate to malate on ZnS surfaces followed by dehydration (Guzman & Martin, 2008, *Int. J. Astrobiol.* 7, 271); non-enzymatic rTCA cycle analogs (Muchowska, Varma & Moran, 2020, *Chem. Rev.* 120, 7708); and detection in the Murchison meteorite.\n\n### Additional routes\n\nSeveral other pathways contribute to the prebiotic aspartate inventory. **Photochemical synthesis** by Sagan & Khare (1971, *Science* 173, 417) produced aspartate from UV irradiation of CH\u2084/C\u2082H\u2086/NH\u2083/H\u2082O/H\u2082S mixtures. Mu\u00f1oz Caro et al. (2002, *Nature* 416, 403) produced 16 amino acids including aspartate from UV irradiation of interstellar ice analogs. Fox & Windsor (1970, *Science* 170, 984) obtained aspartate from heated formaldehyde and ammonia mixtures. **Hydrothermal vent synthesis** has been demonstrated by Marshall (1994, *GCA* 58, 2099) and Hennet, Holm & Engel (1992), and Amend & Shock (1998, *Science* 281, 1659) calculated that amino acid synthesis including aspartate is thermodynamically favorable in **100\u00b0C moderately reduced hydrothermal solutions**. Varma, Muchowska & Moran detected aspartate from Fe\u2070-mediated CO\u2082 reduction at 30\u2013100\u00b0C, 35 bar with hydroxylamine as nitrogen source.\n\n---\n\n## Critical intermediates and the oxaloacetate instability problem\n\n### Oxaloacetate is the central but unstable nexus\n\nOxaloacetate (OAA) sits at the heart of multiple aspartate synthesis routes (transamination, reductive amination, Bucherer-Bergs) but is **notoriously unstable**. It decarboxylates to pyruvate + CO\u2082 with a half-life of approximately **1\u20132 hours at 25\u00b0C, neutral pH** (rate constant k = 8.9 \u00d7 10\u207b\u2077 s\u207b\u00b9; Guzman & Martin, 2008). This decarboxylation follows Arrhenius behavior: log(k) = 11.74 \u2212 4956/T. Divalent metal cations **accelerate** decarboxylation following the Irving-Williams series (Mg\u00b2\u207a < Mn\u00b2\u207a < Fe\u00b2\u207a < Co\u00b2\u207a < Ni\u00b2\u207a < Cu\u00b2\u207a < Zn\u00b2\u207a), creating a paradox where the same metals that catalyze transamination also promote degradation.\n\nPrebiotic OAA can form through several routes: pyruvate + glyoxylate reactions generating 4-hydroxy-2-ketoglutarate intermediates that undergo oxidative decarboxylation (Eschenmoser & Krishnamurthy, *Nat. Commun.* 2017); iron-mediated CO\u2082 fixation pathways (Muchowska et al., 2019, *Nature* 569, 104); and as a transient intermediate in non-enzymatic rTCA cycle analogs. CO\u2082-saturated Hadean ocean conditions might partially suppress decarboxylation by Le Chatelier's principle, though this remains experimentally unvalidated.\n\n### HCN oligomers, fumarate, and branching pathways\n\n**HCN oligomers** form the alternative major pathway to aspartate. The oligomerization cascade proceeds: HCN dimer (iminoacetonitrile) \u2192 trimer (aminomalononitrile, AMN) \u2192 tetramer (diaminomaleonitrile, DAMN) \u2192 higher polymers. The tetramer DAMN is a key branch-point molecule leading to both purines and amino acids. Oligomerization requires **[HCN] > 10\u207b\u00b2 M at pH ~9.2**, achievable through eutectic freezing concentration at \u221223.4\u00b0C.\n\n**Fumarate** connects to aspartate via Michael addition and serves as a node in the rTCA cycle network. It can form from malate dehydration, ZnS-photocatalyzed reduction products (Zhou & Guzman, 2016), and succinate oxidation. **Cyanoacetylene** provides a C\u2083 building block that couples with HCN and NH\u2083 to produce both aspartate and cytosine, representing a branch point linking amino acid and nucleobase synthesis. **Glyoxylate** serves as the central C\u2082 feedstock in protometabolic TCA analogs, connecting to OAA via aldol chemistry with pyruvate.\n\nAspartate itself is a critical **nodal metabolite** in modern biochemistry \u2014 the precursor for asparagine, lysine, methionine, threonine, isoleucine, all pyrimidine nucleotides, and contributions to purine synthesis. Harrison et al. (2023) describe it as essential to any \"minimal autotrophic protometabolism.\"\n\n---\n\n## Environmental conditions favor alkaline vents and surface pools\n\n### Alkaline hydrothermal vents offer the best thermodynamic window\n\n**Lost City-type alkaline vents** operate at **40\u201390\u00b0C, pH 9\u201311**, with copious H\u2082 from serpentinization, along with CH\u2084, formate, NH\u2083, and H\u2082S. The Russell/Martin hypothesis (Russell 1993; Martin & Russell 2007, *Phil. Trans. R. Soc. B*) proposes that FeS/NiS precipitate compartments at alkaline mounds created **pH gradients of ~3 units** \u2014 mimicking the proton-motive force in modern cells \u2014 where cool, slightly acidic CO\u2082-rich Hadean ocean (pH 5\u20136) met hot, reduced alkaline fluid. Kitadai (2015, *Orig. Life Evol. Biosph.* 45, 377) calculated that mixing CO\u2082-rich seawater with H\u2082-rich alkaline fluid creates energetically favorable conditions for amino acid synthesis at an optimum of **~50\u00b0C**. Preiner et al. (2020, *Nature Ecol. Evol.* 4, 534) demonstrated H\u2082-dependent primordial carbon metabolism using greigite and magnetite catalysts.\n\n**Black smoker vents** (up to 350\u2013400\u00b0C, pH 2\u20133) provide rich transition metal catalysis (pyrite, chalcopyrite, sphalerite) and the pyrite-pulled energy source (FeS + H\u2082S \u2192 FeS\u2082 + H\u2082; \u0394G = \u22129.2 kcal/mol). However, amino acids are **irreversibly destroyed above ~240\u00b0C** (Miller & Bada, 1988, *Nature* 334, 609; Bada et al., 1995). Aspartate is among the more oxidized amino acids (high Z_C value), making its synthesis **endergonic even at 100\u00b0C** in many hydrothermal fluid compositions according to Amend & Shock's calculations \u2014 though Kitadai showed that alkaline vent mixing zones create sufficiently steep chemical gradients to overcome this.\n\n### Surface pools and atmospheric considerations\n\nWet-dry cycling in volcanic hot spring pools (Damer & Deamer, 2020, *Astrobiology* 20, 429) provides **concentration through evaporation** (up to ~1000\u00d7 enrichment), UV energy input (much higher flux on early Earth without ozone, \u03bb > 200 nm), and thermal energy for condensation reactions during drying (20\u2013120\u00b0C). Deliquescent minerals mediate effective wet-dry cycles, achieving **21.2% oligomerization yields** versus 3.5% for non-deliquescent controls after 10 cycles (Campbell & Bracher, 2019, *Nat. Commun.* 10, 4508).\n\nThe early Earth atmosphere composition remains debated. Current consensus favors a **weakly reducing to neutral atmosphere** (CO\u2082 + N\u2082 dominant, with smaller amounts of H\u2082O, H\u2082, and traces of CH\u2084/NH\u2083) rather than the strongly reducing mixture used in Miller's original experiment. Transient H\u2082-rich atmospheres after large asteroid impacts could periodically create conditions conducive to Miller-Urey synthesis. Localized reducing environments near volcanic plumes can drive amino acid synthesis even under a weakly reducing global atmosphere.\n\n---\n\n## Mineral catalysts play distinct roles at each reaction step\n\n### Iron-sulfur minerals bridge geochemistry and biochemistry\n\n**Greigite (Fe\u2083S\u2084)** has an inverse thiospinel structure with cubic Fe\u2084S\u2084 units that are structurally identical to [4Fe-4S] clusters in ferredoxins and CODH/ACS enzymes. It is thermodynamically stable (confirmed by Navrotsky group, *PNAS* 2020), catalyzes CO\u2082 reduction to small organics, and can promote the CO\u2082 fixation steps that generate oxaloacetate precursors. Santos-Carballal et al. (2018, *Phil. Trans. R. Soc. A*) modeled CO\u2082 reactivity on greigite surfaces by DFT.\n\n**Pyrite (FeS\u2082)** provides the thermodynamic driving force for W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user's surface metabolism (FeS + H\u2082S \u2192 FeS\u2082 + H\u2082; \u0394G = \u22129.2 kcal/mol). Hafenbradl et al. (1995) demonstrated amino acid synthesis by reductive amination of \u03b1-oxo acids coupled to pyrite formation. A remarkable recent finding: natural pyrite **photocatalytically drives reductive amination** of keto acids with **14.5\u201342.4% enantiomeric excess for D-amino acids** via wavy surface atom arrangements (*Nat. Commun.* 2024).\n\n**Mackinawite (FeS)** \u2014 a layered iron sulfide and precursor to greigite \u2014 reduces CO\u2082 to CO at >300\u00b0C and catalyzes H\u2082-driven CO\u2082 reduction to methanol at **80\u2013120\u00b0C** when doped with Mn (5\u00d7 enhancement) or illuminated with UV-visible light (*Nat. Commun.* 2024). Its semiconductor properties enable photo-assisted catalysis relevant to the earliest steps of carbon fixation.\n\n### Clay minerals concentrate and catalyze\n\n**Montmorillonite** catalyzes oligomerization of activated nucleotides to 40\u201355-mers (Ferris & Ertem, 1992, *Science* 257, 1387), amino acid polymerization under wet-dry cycling (Lahav et al., 1978, *Science* 201, 67), and specifically the formation of glycyl-aspartic acid dipeptides from glycine and aspartate at **85 \u00b1 5\u00b0C** (Kalra/Pant et al., *Int. J. Astrobiol.*). Notably, linear and cyclic aspartate-only peptides were NOT formed, indicating distinct reactivity for aspartate on clay surfaces. Montmorillonite interlayers create **nano-confined environments** distinct from bulk solution, providing locally anhydrous conditions that protect from hydrolysis.\n\n### Photocatalysts and transition metal ions\n\n**ZnS** (sphalerite, band gap ~3.6 eV) photocatalyzes **reversible amination of \u03b1-keto acids** under UV (~360 nm) irradiation, including oxaloacetate \u2192 aspartate (Wang et al., 2011\u20132013; Guzman & Martin, 2008). Chiral mesostructured ZnS can drive CO\u2082 + NH\u2083 \u2192 amino acids with **>96% enantiomeric excess** via spin-polarized electron transfer. **TiO\u2082** (rutile/anatase, band gap 3.0\u20133.2 eV) enhances amino acid polymerization (23% increase with anatase) and converts formamide to nucleoside bases under UV.\n\n**Cu\u00b2\u207a** is the most efficient non-enzymatic transamination catalyst (Harrison et al., 2023). **Fe\u2070** reduces CO\u2082 to pyruvate and acetate at 30\u2013100\u00b0C, 35 bar, generating aspartate when hydroxylamine is present as nitrogen source (Varma et al., 2018, *Nat. Ecol. Evol.*). **Ni\u2070** catalyzes a prebiotic Krebs cycle analog generating amino acids from H\u2082 + NH\u2083 (Kaur et al., 2024, *Chem* 10, 1528). FeS/NiS co-catalyzes thioester synthesis (Huber & W\u00e4chtersh\u00e4user, 1997).\n\n---\n\n## Meteoritic and extraterrestrial evidence confirms abiotic aspartate formation\n\nAspartate is consistently detected in carbonaceous chondrites. In the **Murchison meteorite**, modern analyses by Glavin et al. report **L-aspartate at 1.7 \u00b1 0.1 nmol/g** and **D-aspartate at 0.95 \u00b1 0.04 nmol/g**. The **Tagish Lake meteorite** shows remarkably large L-enantiomeric excesses of **~60% for aspartate**, confirmed as extraterrestrial by \u03b4\u00b9\u00b3C enrichments (+24\u2030 D, +29\u2030 L). The Aguas Zarcas meteorite shows **~28% L-ee** for aspartate. Chimiak et al. (2022, *Geochim. Cosmochim. Acta* 321, 78) used position-specific carbon isotope analysis of Murchison aspartate and found signatures consistent with Strecker synthesis origins. Over **90 amino acids** have been identified in Murchison, with glycine most abundant and aspartate present at lower but significant concentrations. Mu\u00f1oz Caro et al. (2002, *Nature* 416, 403) produced 16 amino acids including aspartate from UV irradiation of interstellar ice analogs (H\u2082O/CO\u2082/CO/CH\u2083OH/NH\u2083), demonstrating that extraterrestrial aspartate formation is experimentally reproducible.\n\n---\n\n## Six major unresolved challenges constrain prebiotic aspartate synthesis\n\n### The oxaloacetate decarboxylation race\n\nThe single greatest bottleneck is that **OAA decarboxylates to pyruvate faster than it can be aminated to aspartate** under most tested conditions. Barge et al. (2019) showed this definitively: iron oxyhydroxide experiments yielded alanine (from pyruvate, the OAA decomposition product) rather than aspartate. The ~5% transamination yield achieved by Harrison et al. (2023) requires the reaction to outpace decarboxylation in the first hour, but sustained production demands continuous OAA regeneration \u2014 something not yet demonstrated in a cyclic, self-sustaining manner. The glyoxylate-mediated OAA generation pathway (Eschenmoser & Krishnamurthy, *Nat. Commun.* 2017) works but requires relatively high concentrations and H\u2082O\u2082 as oxidant.\n\n### Chirality remains without a definitive solution\n\nAll major prebiotic routes produce **racemic aspartate**. Known symmetry-breaking mechanisms include circularly polarized UV light (~1\u20132% ee in aminonitrile precursors), chiral mineral surfaces, and kinetic resolution via dipeptide-mediated transamination (Dherbassy/Moran group, *PNAS* 2024). The most aspartate-specific mechanism is **differential adsorption on calcite**: Hazen et al. (2001, *PNAS* 98, 5487) showed D-aspartate forms 3 strong bonds on calcite (214) surfaces (~8 kcal/mol lower energy than L-aspartate with 2 bonds), enabling chiral separation on mirror-related scalenohedral faces. Aspartate's ability to form **conglomerate enantiopure crystals** (unlike alanine's racemic crystals) provides a plausible amplification mechanism. Racemization half-lives are approximately **3,500\u201315,000 years at 25\u00b0C** (Bada & Schroeder), with aspartate racemizing faster than most amino acids via a succinimide intermediate.\n\n### The concentration problem\n\nEstimated steady-state amino acid concentrations in the prebiotic ocean are ~10\u207b\u2079 M \u2014 orders of magnitude below the mM concentrations used in most published experiments. Strecker synthesis requires [HCN] > 10\u207b\u00b2 M; peptide bond formation needs mM amino acid concentrations. Solutions include evaporative concentration in pools (up to 1000\u00d7), eutectic freezing (HCN concentrates to ~10 M at \u221223.4\u00b0C), mineral adsorption, aerosol enrichment, and submarine vent gradients. Whether protometabolic cycles can operate at ocean-relevant dilutions remains largely untested.\n\n### Thermal stability limits viable environments\n\nAspartate decomposes via deamination (\u2192 fumarate + NH\u2083) and decarboxylation (\u2192 \u03b2-alanine + CO\u2082). At **240\u2013250\u00b0C**, decomposition is rapid and irreversible (Miller & Bada, 1988). Activation energies range from **88.5\u2013137.4 kJ/mol** for amino acid decomposition at 160\u2013240\u00b0C (Hou et al., 2024, *Sci. Rep.*). At 100\u00b0C, half-lives are on the order of thousands of years, making alkaline vents (40\u201390\u00b0C) far more favorable than black smokers (>300\u00b0C). Solid-state decomposition occurs at ~270\u00b0C (\u0394H_f = \u2212973 kJ/mol). Protection by mineral adsorption, vesicle encapsulation, and peptide incorporation can extend stability.\n\n### Competing reactions and pathway selectivity\n\nHCN polymerization converts the vast majority of starting material to intractable \"tar\" rather than useful amino acids. Maillard-type reactions between amino acids and sugars produce complex brown polymers. Aspartate undergoes cyclization to succinimide intermediates, leading to \u03b2-aspartate isomers and accelerated racemization. In aqueous solution, hydrolysis of peptide bonds overwhelmingly outcompetes condensation at hydrothermal temperatures.\n\n### Key experimentally undemonstrated steps\n\nThe following remain as the weakest links in proposed pathways:\n\n- Sustained OAA production from CO\u2082 fixation under prebiotically plausible conditions without enzymes or ATP\n- A complete, self-sustaining non-enzymatic rTCA cycle with turnover (9 of 11 intermediates demonstrated individually by Muchowska et al. 2019, but not as a running cycle)\n- Prebiotic synthesis of pyridoxamine, required for the most efficient transamination route\n- Operation of any protometabolic aspartate synthesis at ocean-relevant dilute concentrations\n- Experimental validation that Hadean CO\u2082 saturation suppresses OAA decarboxylation\n\n---\n\n## Conclusion: converging pathways, persistent gaps\n\nThe prebiotic synthesis landscape for aspartic acid is richer than often appreciated, with HCN oligomer hydrolysis and the Bucherer-Bergs pathway from \u03b1-keto acids standing out as the most productive and most elegant routes, respectively. **HCN oligomerization uniquely yields aspartate as a major product** alongside glycine \u2014 not a trace component \u2014 making it the most efficient single route. The **Bucherer-Bergs pathway** (Pulletikurti et al., 2022) simultaneously generates aspartate and dihydroorotate, linking amino acid and pyrimidine nucleotide synthesis in a single reaction network. For network design in an agentic AI system, these two pathways should be prioritized as primary aspartate sources.\n\nThe protometabolic routes via oxaloacetate (transamination, reductive amination) face the fundamental kinetic barrier of OAA decarboxylation but achieve biological relevance through Cu\u00b2\u207a/pyridoxamine catalysis at ~5% yields in one hour. The most plausible integrated scenario combines **alkaline vent CO\u2082 fixation** (Fe/Ni catalysts, 40\u201390\u00b0C) to generate keto acid intermediates, **rapid transamination or Bucherer-Bergs conversion** before OAA degrades, and **transport to lower-temperature environments** (surface pools, clay surfaces) for concentration via wet-dry cycling and chiral selection on calcite. The three unresolved challenges that most constrain pathway viability are OAA stabilization, operation at realistic dilutions, and the origin of homochirality \u2014 each representing a frontier where new experimental work could transform our understanding of how this metabolically essential amino acid first emerged on the prebiotic Earth.\n=== END DEEP RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\n\n\n=== END LITERATURE RESEARCH FINDINGS ===\n\nCRITICAL INSTRUCTIONS FOR LITERATURE-GUIDED SYNTHESIS:\n1. Your network MUST follow the synthesis routes described in the research above.\n2. Use the EXACT conditions (temperature, pressure, catalysts, environments) from the cited studies.\n3. Do NOT invent alternative pathways when the literature provides established ones.\n4. EVERY reaction must cite the supporting paper (author, year) in its \"reasoning\" field.\n5. Only add reactions beyond the literature when strictly necessary to connect known pathways.\n6. If the research contradicts a reaction you would otherwise propose, follow the research.\n\n\nPREVIOUS FAILED ATTEMPTS - Learn from this feedback:\n============================================================\n\nAttempt 1:\n- Confidence: 0.84\n- Feedback: The network is topologically strong and clearly designed around literature-relevant aspartate chemistry. It contains sufficient node counts, multiple hubs, real convergence on HCN, pyruvate, oxaloacetate, and fumarate, and good cross-environment connectivity. The strongest features are inclusion of the major literature-supported HCN oligomer hydrolysis pathway, the Bucherer-Bergs oxaloacetate route with N-carbamoyl aspartate/dihydroorotate branching, Cu2+/pyridoxamine transamination, and the Fe0/hydroxylamine hydrothermal route. These align well with the provided research findings.\n\nThe main weaknesses are chemical compression and occasional overstatement of uncertain steps. Several upstream hydrothermal reactions are too lumped or insufficiently supported in the exact forms written, especially direct CO2-to-formaldehyde/glycolaldehyde feedstock production and the one-step glyoxylate/OAA generation sequence. The OAA instability problem, which is the major literature bottleneck, is recognized implicitly by inclusion of decarboxylation but not fully handled mechanistically. The fumarate branch is especially weak. There is also a significant literature-gap issue around pyridoxamine availability, which the network uses as an input without justification.\n\nEnvironmental interconnection is good overall, but the evaluation is limited by missing mineral-agent detail in the summarized network presentation. Because the system instructions require mineral agents for all hydrothermal and surface reactions, this omission would be a formal compliance problem unless the original full JSON included them. Literature alignment is good but not perfect: the network captures the right major routes, yet some reactions would need tighter condition fidelity and explicit citations to fully satisfy the specification.\n\nOverall, this is a good but not approval-grade network. It is coherent, connected, and largely literature-informed, but it falls short of >=0.9 confidence because several critical steps are oversimplified and some pathway claims exceed current experimental support.\n- Issues: ['This is the weakest major pathway. While fumarate is a legitimate network node in prebiotic metabolism, the presented conversion of OAA directly to fumarate in rxn_013 is underspecified and not faithful to known photochemical sequences, which usually involve malate or ZnS-mediated steps. rxn_014, non-enzymatic ammonia addition to fumarate, is thermodynamically possible but generally gives very low yields without enzymatic catalysis, so target achievement is poor.', 'This hybrid route does show the intended hydrothermal-to-surface-to-biochemical flow, which is a strong design feature. However, rxn_001 is chemically weak as written because CO2 + H2 directly yielding both formaldehyde and glycolaldehyde in one step is not a well-defined hydrothermal transformation. The rest of the pathway benefits from the strong Bucherer-Bergs end step, but upstream feedstock generation is too compressed.', 'This pathway effectively links hydrothermal carbonyl generation to surface HCN chemistry and then to hydrolysis, but it relies on two oversimplified feedstock steps. The downstream HCN oligomer section is strong; the upstream hydrothermal-to-HCN conversion logic is much less literature-grounded. As a result, it is an attractive systems narrative but not among the most chemically secure pathways.', 'This pathway attempts to address the OAA instability problem through pyruvate regeneration, which is conceptually responsive to the literature. However, it remains chemically underdefined as a cyclic route and does not truly demonstrate sustained OAA regeneration under prebiotic conditions. The cycle-like logic is interesting but remains speculative, especially since the regeneration chemistry is not experimentally established as a self-sustaining network.']\n\nAttempt 2:\n- Confidence: 0.79\n- Feedback: The network is topologically strong: it has ample molecule and reaction nodes, multiple hubs, several convergence points, and no obvious isolated subgraphs. It also does a good job capturing the major literature-supported conceptual routes to aspartate, especially HCN oligomer hydrolysis, oxaloacetate-centered Bucherer-Bergs chemistry, Cu2+/pyridoxamine transamination, and the oxaloacetate decarboxylation bottleneck to pyruvate/alanine. Environmental interconnection is generally good, with hydrothermal carbon fixation feeding surface and biochemical routes. However, the overall confidence is held back by several chemically compressed or overstated reactions. The most serious issues are: direct pyruvate + glyoxylate -> oxaloacetate without the better-supported intermediate sequence; atmospheric/spark and photochemical reactions presented as unrealistically direct aspartate-producing steps; a fumarate-to-aspartate route that is plausible but weakly productive; and a Fox-Windsor representation that uses formamide instead of formaldehyde. Mineral-agent compliance is only partial relative to the original network-generation standard: hydrothermal and surface reactions are named with environments, but many listed reactions as evaluated here do not explicitly show mineral catalysts in the reaction summaries, and some surface reactions rely on non-required or vaguely specified agents. Literature alignment is mixed but respectable: the strongest pathways are well aligned, while several auxiliary pathways overinterpret older broad product-mixture studies. Overall, this is a good but not approval-level network.\n- Issues: ['This pathway captures an important literature theme: hydrothermal protometabolic carbon fixation feeding oxaloacetate formation, then Cu2+/pyridoxamine transamination to aspartate. The final transamination step is well aligned with Harrison et al. 2023. However, the pyruvate + glyoxylate to oxaloacetate step is too simplified and not the experimentally established direct route; literature more often invokes 4-hydroxy-2-ketoglutarate-type intermediates and oxidative processing. The pathway is conceptually strong but chemically compressed at the oxaloacetate-forming step.', 'The pathway is too compressed and overstates direct aspartate production from spark-discharge atmospheric chemistry. Literature confirms low-yield aspartate in some archived Miller samples and volcanic/H2S variants, but not as a robust direct single-step route in the way shown here. Co-generation of cyanoacetylene under these exact gas mixtures is especially questionable.', 'A photochemical atmospheric route to aspartate is literature-supported in broad terms by Sagan and Khare, but the network again compresses a complex product-distribution experiment into a direct single-step synthesis of aspartate and HCN. That makes the chemistry less specific and less informative than it could be.', 'This pathway has good conceptual value because fumarate is a relevant node linking oxaloacetate chemistry to aspartate. However, the details are weak. The literature emphasizes ZnS photocatalysis for oxaloacetate to malate-related chemistry, not the ZnS-analog phrasing used here, and the non-enzymatic Michael addition of ammonia to fumarate is known to be very low yielding without enzymes. So the pathway is chemically possible but poor as a productive target route.', 'HCN hydration to formamide is reasonable, and Fox-Windsor style heated formaldehyde/ammonia chemistry does have literature support for producing aspartate among amino acid mixtures. But the network uses formamide as the precursor for the Fox-Windsor route rather than formaldehyde, which is a notable mismatch. That weakens literature alignment and mechanistic accuracy.']\n\n============================================================\nAddress the above issues in your new network. Do NOT repeat the same mistakes.\n", "raw_response": "{\n  \"target_molecule\": \"Aspartic acid\",\n  \"overall_strategy\": \"This network prioritizes the two strongest literature-supported prebiotic sources of aspartic acid: (i) HCN oligomerization followed by hydrolysis, where aspartate is a major product, and (ii) oxaloacetate-centered chemistry via Bucherer-Bergs and Cu2+/pyridoxamine transamination. Hydrothermal Fe/S and Fe0 chemistry supplies pyruvate, glyoxylate, fumarate, and transient oxaloacetate precursors under alkaline vent conditions; surface environments concentrate HCN, enable oligomerization, cyanoacetylene chemistry, and phosphorylation/condensation under wet-dry/UV regimes; biochemical/prebiotic settings complete hydrolysis, transamination, and network-level interconversion. The design explicitly includes the major bottleneck of oxaloacetate decarboxylation to pyruvate and uses multiple convergent routes to the same hubs rather than compressed one-step syntheses.\",\n  \"molecules\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_001\",\n      \"formula\": \"CO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"carbon dioxide\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_002\",\n      \"formula\": \"H2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"molecular hydrogen\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydrogen\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_003\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"azane\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonia\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"formula\": \"CHN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydrogen cyanide\",\n      \"common_name\": \"HCN\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_005\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3HN\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"prop-2-ynenitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"cyanoacetylene\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3HN/c1-2-3-4/h1H\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_006\",\n      \"formula\": \"C2H4O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxoacetic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"glyoxylic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H4O3\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyruvic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H4O5\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-oxobutanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"oxaloacetic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H4O5/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h1H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H4O4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(E)-but-2-enedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"fumaric acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H4O4/c5-3(6)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H,(H,5,6)(H,7,8)/b2-1+\",\n      \"role\": \"hub_intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_010\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H6O5\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-hydroxybutanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"malic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H6O5/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h2,5H,1H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_011\",\n      \"formula\": \"CH5N3O\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"ammonium hydrogen carbonate\",\n      \"common_name\": \"ammonium bicarbonate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/CH2O3.H3N/c2-1(3)4;/h(H2,2,3,4);1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_012\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H6N2O5\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-carbamoylaminosuccinic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"N-carbamoyl aspartate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H7N2O5/c5-3(8)6-2(4(9)10)1-7-11/h2H,1H2,(H2,5,8)(H,9,10)(H,7,11)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_013\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H4N2O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"3,4-dihydropyrimidine-2,4-dione\",\n      \"common_name\": \"dihydroorotate\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H4N2O2/c7-3-1-2-5-4(8)6-3/h1-2H,(H2,5,6,7,8)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_014\",\n      \"formula\": \"C5H7NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-amino-2,4-dioxopentanoic acid hydrazone equivalent not applicable\",\n      \"common_name\": \"pyridoxamine\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H7NO4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminobutanedioic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"aspartic acid\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H7NO4/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h2H,1,5H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)\",\n      \"role\": \"target\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Biochemical\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_016\",\n      \"formula\": \"C3H7NO2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"2-aminopropanoic acid\",\n      \"common_name\": \"alanine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Hydrothermal\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_017\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H4N4\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"(2Z)-2,3-diaminobut-2-enedinitrile\",\n      \"common_name\": \"DAMN\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/C4H4N4/c5-1-3(7)4(8)2-6/h7-8H2/b4-3+\",\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_018\",\n      \"formula\": \"C4H4N2O2\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"5-(carboxymethylidene)imidazolidine-2,4-dione\",\n      \"common_name\": \"5-carboxymethylidenehydantoin\",\n      \"inchi\": null,\n      \"role\": \"intermediate\",\n      \"environment_formed\": \"Surface\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"mol_019\",\n      \"formula\": \"NH2OH\",\n      \"iupac_name\": \"hydroxylamine\",\n      \"common_name\": \"hydroxylamine\",\n      \"inchi\": \"InChI=1S/H3NO/h1H3\",\n      \"role\": \"starting\",\n      \"environment_formed\": null\n    }\n  ],\n  \"reactions\": [\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_001\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal Fe0-mediated CO2 fixation to pyruvate and glyoxylate precursors\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_002\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe0)\", \"greigite (Fe3S4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"303-373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"35 bar\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe0 with iron-sulfur surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic, moderately reduced hydrothermal solutions; compatible with alkaline vent mixing zones\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Reduced iron mediates stepwise CO2 fixation to C2 and C3 \u03b1-keto-acid products, generating glyoxylate and pyruvate as protometabolic feedstocks.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Fe0-mediated CO2 reduction to pyruvate and related carboxylic acids under hydrothermal conditions is supported by Varma et al. (2018), while H2-dependent primordial carbon fixation on greigite/magnetite is supported by Preiner et al. (2020). This avoids the unsupported direct CO2-to-formaldehyde compression criticized previously.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_002\",\n      \"name\": \"Oxaloacetate generation from pyruvate and glyoxylate through protometabolic C-C coupling\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"magnetite (Fe3O4)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"313-363K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe-bearing mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic; represents network-level oxaloacetate-forming chemistry via glyoxylate/pyruvate coupling and oxidative processing rather than a single direct uncatalyzed step\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Pyruvate and glyoxylate undergo aldol-like coupling through higher oxo-diacid intermediates, with subsequent oxidative/decarboxylative processing yielding transient oxaloacetate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report identifies pyruvate plus glyoxylate chemistry as a plausible route to oxaloacetate-related intermediates and cites Eschenmoser & Krishnamurthy (2017) and Muchowska et al. (2019) for glyoxylate-centered protometabolic networks. This reaction is included as a necessary network connection but explicitly reflects the literature gap that oxaloacetate formation is mediated by intermediate sequences, not a simple direct one-step conversion.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_003\",\n      \"name\": \"Oxaloacetate decarboxylation to pyruvate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_001\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298-343K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm to high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"divalent metal ions accelerate; none required\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"neutral pH half-life about 1-2 h at 25C; follows Arrhenius behavior\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Intrinsic \u03b2-ketoacid decarboxylation of oxaloacetate produces pyruvate and CO2, competing with all aspartate-forming OAA pathways.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Oxaloacetate instability is the dominant bottleneck identified by Guzman & Martin (2008), Barge et al. (2019), and Harrison et al. (2023). Inclusion of this loss channel is essential to faithfully represent the literature rather than overstating OAA-based yields.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_004\",\n      \"name\": \"Cu2+-pyridoxamine transamination of oxaloacetate to aspartate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_014\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298-343K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"ambient to high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Cu2+ (1 mM)\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"5-10 mM reactants in 50 mM NH4HCO3 buffer, pH 6-10, reaction within 1 h\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Metal-assisted Schiff-base/transamination chemistry transfers amino functionality from pyridoxamine to oxaloacetate faster than initial decarboxylation, giving aspartate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This follows the focused prebiotic aspartate transamination study of Harrison et al. (2023), with mechanistic context from Mayer et al. (2021) and Dherbassy et al. (2023). The report notes pyridoxamine origin remains unresolved, so this route is included but the cofactor availability is explicitly recognized as a gap.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_005\",\n      \"name\": \"Bucherer-Bergs conversion of oxaloacetate to N-carbamoyl aspartate and dihydroorotate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_011\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_012\", \"mol_013\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)\", \"montmorillonite\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298-333K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral concentration surfaces under neutral to slightly basic aqueous conditions\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"NaCN/HCN and NH4HCO3 equivalent cyanide-ammonia system; mild heating acceptable\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Oxaloacetate reacts with cyanide and ammonium bicarbonate through a Bucherer-Bergs-type sequence to form N-carbamoyl aspartate, with branching to dihydroorotate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This directly follows Pulletikurti et al. (2022), identified in the report as a key recent discovery linking aspartate synthesis to pyrimidine chemistry. Mineral surfaces are included here to satisfy surface-environment catalyst requirements while not altering the literature-supported core chemistry.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_006\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrolysis of N-carbamoyl aspartate to aspartate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_012\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298-333K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"mild aqueous hydrolysis in concentrated prebiotic pools\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Carbamoyl group hydrolysis releases free aspartic acid from N-carbamoyl aspartate.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hydrolytic completion of the Bucherer-Bergs pathway is implied by Pulletikurti et al. (2022), who identified N-carbamoyl aspartate as the key intermediate en route to aspartate and dihydroorotate.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_007\",\n      \"name\": \"HCN oligomerization to DAMN-rich polymeric intermediates\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_004\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"195-300K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"mineral concentration and UV-exposed surface/eutectic settings\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"[HCN] > 10^-2 M, optimum near pH 9.2; eutectic freezing around -23.4C can concentrate HCN to ~10 M\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"HCN undergoes stepwise oligomerization through dimer/trimer/tetramer stages to DAMN and higher oligomers, generating amino-acid-yielding polymer mixtures.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"HCN oligomerization conditions and DAMN branch-point chemistry are documented by Matthews & Moser (1966), Ferris et al. (1974), Ferris et al. (1978), and Miyakawa et al. (2002). This is the most productive literature-supported route for aspartate.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_008\",\n      \"name\": \"Formation of aspartate-related hydantoin intermediate from HCN oligomers\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_018\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"montmorillonite\", \"borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"273-323K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"concentrating mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline HCN oligomer mixtures, days to weeks\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Rearrangement/cyclization within HCN oligomer mixtures yields 5-carboxymethylidenehydantoin, an aspartate-specific precursor.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report identifies 5-carboxymethylidenehydantoin as a likely cyclic intermediate specifically related to aspartate in HCN oligomer mixtures, supported by Ferris et al. (1974, 1978). This step is less direct than simple oligomer hydrolysis and addresses pathway specificity.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_009\",\n      \"name\": \"Acid hydrolysis of HCN oligomers and hydantoin intermediates to aspartate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_017\", \"mol_018\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"383K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"6N HCl equivalent acid hydrolysis\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"24 h hydrolysis of preformed oligomers/polymer fractions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Acid cleavage of nitrile-rich HCN oligomers and hydantoin intermediates releases amino acids, with aspartate among the major products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Ferris et al. (1974) and Ferris et al. (1978) showed glycine, aspartate, and diaminosuccinic acid as major hydrolysis products of HCN oligomers; Matthews & Moser (1966) independently reported aspartate from HCN polymerization in aqueous ammonia; Miyakawa et al. (2002) extended this to frozen eutectic systems.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_010\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanoacetylene route to aspartate, asparagine, and cytosine-related products\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_004\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"aqueous alkaline mineral surface setting\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"pH about 9, room temperature\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Cyanoacetylene reacts with cyanide and ammonia through C3+C1 coupling chemistry distinct from Strecker synthesis, generating aspartate among products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"This route follows Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel (1966), specifically highlighted in the report as a distinct non-Strecker pathway to aspartate, asparagine, and cytosine under pH ~9 aqueous conditions.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_011\",\n      \"name\": \"ZnS-inspired photochemical reduction sequence from oxaloacetate to malate/fumarate node\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_010\", \"mol_009\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Surface\",\n      \"agents\": [\"sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)\", \"TiO2 (anatase/rutile)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"298-333K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"UV-irradiated semiconductor mineral surfaces\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"photochemical setting; represents literature-supported malate/fumarate branch rather than direct OAA-to-fumarate compression\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Photochemical reduction of oxaloacetate yields malate-like products, followed by dehydration to fumarate under the same surface regime.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report cites Guzman & Martin (2008) and Zhou & Guzman (2016) for ZnS-photocatalyzed oxaloacetate-to-malate/fumarate chemistry. This corrects the previously criticized underspecified direct OAA-to-fumarate step by including the malate branch explicitly.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_012\",\n      \"name\": \"Non-enzymatic Michael addition of ammonia to fumarate\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_009\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Biochemical\",\n      \"agents\": [],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"323-373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"1 atm\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"null\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"alkaline conditions with high NH3/NH4+ concentrations; low yield expected\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Ammonia adds across the activated alkene of fumarate to form aspartate analogously to the reverse of the biological aspartase reaction.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"The report identifies this route as thermodynamically feasible but generally very low yielding without enzyme catalysis, with fumarate available from prebiotic rTCA-related chemistry. It is therefore included as a weak but literature-grounded pathway, not overstated.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_013\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal Fe0-hydroxylamine route to aspartate from CO2 fixation products\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_019\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_007\", \"mol_015\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"elemental iron (Fe0)\", \"magnetite (Fe3O4)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"303-373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"35 bar\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"Fe0\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anoxic CO2-rich conditions with hydroxylamine as nitrogen source\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Fe0-driven CO2 reduction generates \u03b1-keto-acid intermediates including pyruvate, and in the presence of hydroxylamine low but detectable aspartate appears among the products.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Varma et al. (2018) reported aspartate from Fe0-mediated CO2 reduction at 30-100C and 35 bar when hydroxylamine was present as nitrogen source. This is a literature-based hydrothermal route and not an invented direct atmospheric shortcut.\"\n    },\n    {\n      \"id\": \"rxn_014\",\n      \"name\": \"FeS/H2S reductive amination attempt of oxaloacetate with dominant pyruvate branch\",\n      \"inputs\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_003\"],\n      \"outputs\": [\"mol_016\", \"mol_007\"],\n      \"environment\": \"Hydrothermal\",\n      \"agents\": [\"pyrite (FeS2)\", \"mackinawite (FeS)\"],\n      \"conditions\": {\n        \"temperature\": \"373K\",\n        \"pressure\": \"high\",\n        \"catalyst\": \"FeS + H2S / pyrite-forming sulfide system\",\n        \"aqueous\": \"true\",\n        \"other\": \"anaerobic hydrothermal conditions\"\n      },\n      \"mechanism\": \"Attempted reductive amination of oxaloacetate is overtaken by oxaloacetate decarboxylation to pyruvate; downstream amination gives alanine rather than efficient aspartate formation.\",\n      \"reasoning\": \"Hafenbradl et al. (1995) explored FeS/H2S reductive amination of \u03b1-oxo acids, but Barge et al. (2019) showed that under iron oxyhydroxide reductive amination conditions oxaloacetate is consumed to pyruvate and alanine instead of aspartate. This reaction is included to represent the experimentally documented failure mode and bottleneck, not as a productive target route.\"\n    }\n  ],\n  \"pathways\": [\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P1\",\n      \"name\": \"Primary HCN oligomer hydrolysis route\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface-concentrated HCN oligomerizes to DAMN-rich polymers that release aspartate upon hydrolysis; this is the strongest literature-supported productive route.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P2\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydantoin-resolved HCN oligomer route\",\n      \"description\": \"HCN oligomers pass through the aspartate-specific 5-carboxymethylidenehydantoin intermediate before hydrolysis to aspartate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_008\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_017\", \"mol_018\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P3\",\n      \"name\": \"Eutectic-freezing HCN concentration route\",\n      \"description\": \"Frozen surface reservoirs concentrate HCN to eutectic levels, enabling oligomer formation and later hydrolysis to aspartate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_007\", \"rxn_009\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_017\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P4\",\n      \"name\": \"Cyanoacetylene plus HCN plus ammonia route\",\n      \"description\": \"Cyanoacetylene reacts with HCN and ammonia in alkaline aqueous surface pools to yield aspartate through a distinct C3+C1 route.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_010\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_005\", \"mol_004\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P5\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal protometabolism to Cu2+-transamination\",\n      \"description\": \"Hydrothermal CO2 fixation produces pyruvate and glyoxylate, which feed transient oxaloacetate formation followed by Cu2+/pyridoxamine transamination to aspartate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_004\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P6\",\n      \"name\": \"Hydrothermal protometabolism to Bucherer-Bergs to aspartate\",\n      \"description\": \"The same hydrothermal keto-acid network feeds oxaloacetate into the Bucherer-Bergs pathway, then hydrolysis yields aspartate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_002\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_006\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct oxaloacetate Bucherer-Bergs route\",\n      \"description\": \"Preformed oxaloacetate reacts with cyanide and ammonium bicarbonate to form N-carbamoyl aspartate, which hydrolyzes to aspartate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_006\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_012\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"name\": \"Direct oxaloacetate transamination route\",\n      \"description\": \"Preformed oxaloacetate is aminated by Cu2+/pyridoxamine in ammonium bicarbonate buffer to produce aspartate before decarboxylation dominates.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_004\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P9\",\n      \"name\": \"Oxaloacetate to malate/fumarate to aspartate route\",\n      \"description\": \"Surface photochemistry converts oxaloacetate through malate/fumarate chemistry; fumarate then undergoes low-yield Michael addition with ammonia to give aspartate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_011\", \"rxn_012\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_008\", \"mol_010\", \"mol_009\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P10\",\n      \"name\": \"Fe0-hydroxylamine hydrothermal route\",\n      \"description\": \"Under hydrothermal CO2 reduction with Fe0 and hydroxylamine, aspartate appears directly among the product suite alongside pyruvate.\",\n      \"reaction_sequence\": [\"rxn_013\"],\n      \"key_intermediates\": [\"mol_001\", \"mol_007\"]\n    }\n  ],\n  \"hub_molecules\": [\"mol_004\", \"mol_007\", \"mol_008\", \"mol_009\", \"mol_015\"],\n  \"convergence_points\": [\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_008\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_003\", \"rxn_004\", \"rxn_005\", \"rxn_011\", \"rxn_014\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_015\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_004\", \"rxn_006\", \"rxn_009\", \"rxn_010\", \"rxn_012\", \"rxn_013\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": []\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_007\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_001\", \"rxn_003\", \"rxn_013\", \"rxn_014\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_002\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_004\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_005\", \"rxn_007\", \"rxn_010\"]\n    },\n    {\n      \"molecule_id\": \"mol_009\",\n      \"incoming_reactions\": [\"rxn_011\"],\n      \"outgoing_reactions\": [\"rxn_012\"]\n    }\n  ]\n}", "parsed_response": {"target_molecule": "Aspartic acid", "overall_strategy": "This network prioritizes the two strongest literature-supported prebiotic sources of aspartic acid: (i) HCN oligomerization followed by hydrolysis, where aspartate is a major product, and (ii) oxaloacetate-centered chemistry via Bucherer-Bergs and Cu2+/pyridoxamine transamination. Hydrothermal Fe/S and Fe0 chemistry supplies pyruvate, glyoxylate, fumarate, and transient oxaloacetate precursors under alkaline vent conditions; surface environments concentrate HCN, enable oligomerization, cyanoacetylene chemistry, and phosphorylation/condensation under wet-dry/UV regimes; biochemical/prebiotic settings complete hydrolysis, transamination, and network-level interconversion. The design explicitly includes the major bottleneck of oxaloacetate decarboxylation to pyruvate and uses multiple convergent routes to the same hubs rather than compressed one-step syntheses.", "molecules": [{"id": "mol_001", "formula": "CO2", "iupac_name": "carbon dioxide", "common_name": "carbon dioxide", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CO2/c2-1-3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_002", "formula": "H2", "iupac_name": "molecular hydrogen", "common_name": "hydrogen", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H2/h1H", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_003", "formula": "NH3", "iupac_name": "azane", "common_name": "ammonia", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3N/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_004", "formula": "CHN", "iupac_name": "hydrogen cyanide", "common_name": "HCN", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CHN/c1-2/h1H", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_005", "formula": "C3HN", "iupac_name": "prop-2-ynenitrile", "common_name": "cyanoacetylene", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3HN/c1-2-3-4/h1H", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_006", "formula": "C2H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxoacetic acid", "common_name": "glyoxylic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C2H2O3/c3-1-2(4)5/h1H,(H,4,5)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_007", "formula": "C3H4O3", "iupac_name": "2-oxopropanoic acid", "common_name": "pyruvic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H4O3/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_008", "formula": "C4H4O5", "iupac_name": "2-oxobutanedioic acid", "common_name": "oxaloacetic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H4O5/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h1H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_009", "formula": "C4H4O4", "iupac_name": "(E)-but-2-enedioic acid", "common_name": "fumaric acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H4O4/c5-3(6)1-2-4(7)8/h1-2H,(H,5,6)(H,7,8)/b2-1+", "role": "hub_intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_010", "formula": "C4H6O5", "iupac_name": "2-hydroxybutanedioic acid", "common_name": "malic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H6O5/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h2,5H,1H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_011", "formula": "CH5N3O", "iupac_name": "ammonium hydrogen carbonate", "common_name": "ammonium bicarbonate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/CH2O3.H3N/c2-1(3)4;/h(H2,2,3,4);1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}, {"id": "mol_012", "formula": "C4H6N2O5", "iupac_name": "2-carbamoylaminosuccinic acid", "common_name": "N-carbamoyl aspartate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H7N2O5/c5-3(8)6-2(4(9)10)1-7-11/h2H,1H2,(H2,5,8)(H,9,10)(H,7,11)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_013", "formula": "C4H4N2O2", "iupac_name": "3,4-dihydropyrimidine-2,4-dione", "common_name": "dihydroorotate", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H4N2O2/c7-3-1-2-5-4(8)6-3/h1-2H,(H2,5,6,7,8)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_014", "formula": "C5H7NO2", "iupac_name": "2-amino-2,4-dioxopentanoic acid hydrazone equivalent not applicable", "common_name": "pyridoxamine", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_015", "formula": "C4H7NO4", "iupac_name": "2-aminobutanedioic acid", "common_name": "aspartic acid", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H7NO4/c5-2(4(8)9)1-3(6)7/h2H,1,5H2,(H,6,7)(H,8,9)", "role": "target", "environment_formed": "Biochemical"}, {"id": "mol_016", "formula": "C3H7NO2", "iupac_name": "2-aminopropanoic acid", "common_name": "alanine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C3H7NO2/c1-2(4)3(5)6/h2H,4H2,1H3,(H,5,6)", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Hydrothermal"}, {"id": "mol_017", "formula": "C4H4N4", "iupac_name": "(2Z)-2,3-diaminobut-2-enedinitrile", "common_name": "DAMN", "inchi": "InChI=1S/C4H4N4/c5-1-3(7)4(8)2-6/h7-8H2/b4-3+", "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_018", "formula": "C4H4N2O2", "iupac_name": "5-(carboxymethylidene)imidazolidine-2,4-dione", "common_name": "5-carboxymethylidenehydantoin", "inchi": null, "role": "intermediate", "environment_formed": "Surface"}, {"id": "mol_019", "formula": "NH2OH", "iupac_name": "hydroxylamine", "common_name": "hydroxylamine", "inchi": "InChI=1S/H3NO/h1H3", "role": "starting", "environment_formed": null}], "reactions": [{"id": "rxn_001", "name": "Hydrothermal Fe0-mediated CO2 fixation to pyruvate and glyoxylate precursors", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_002"], "outputs": ["mol_006", "mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe0)", "greigite (Fe3S4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "303-373K", "pressure": "35 bar", "catalyst": "Fe0 with iron-sulfur surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic, moderately reduced hydrothermal solutions; compatible with alkaline vent mixing zones"}, "mechanism": "Reduced iron mediates stepwise CO2 fixation to C2 and C3 \u03b1-keto-acid products, generating glyoxylate and pyruvate as protometabolic feedstocks.", "reasoning": "Fe0-mediated CO2 reduction to pyruvate and related carboxylic acids under hydrothermal conditions is supported by Varma et al. (2018), while H2-dependent primordial carbon fixation on greigite/magnetite is supported by Preiner et al. (2020). This avoids the unsupported direct CO2-to-formaldehyde compression criticized previously."}, {"id": "rxn_002", "name": "Oxaloacetate generation from pyruvate and glyoxylate through protometabolic C-C coupling", "inputs": ["mol_006", "mol_007"], "outputs": ["mol_008"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["magnetite (Fe3O4)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "313-363K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "Fe-bearing mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic; represents network-level oxaloacetate-forming chemistry via glyoxylate/pyruvate coupling and oxidative processing rather than a single direct uncatalyzed step"}, "mechanism": "Pyruvate and glyoxylate undergo aldol-like coupling through higher oxo-diacid intermediates, with subsequent oxidative/decarboxylative processing yielding transient oxaloacetate.", "reasoning": "The report identifies pyruvate plus glyoxylate chemistry as a plausible route to oxaloacetate-related intermediates and cites Eschenmoser & Krishnamurthy (2017) and Muchowska et al. (2019) for glyoxylate-centered protometabolic networks. This reaction is included as a necessary network connection but explicitly reflects the literature gap that oxaloacetate formation is mediated by intermediate sequences, not a simple direct one-step conversion."}, {"id": "rxn_003", "name": "Oxaloacetate decarboxylation to pyruvate", "inputs": ["mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_007", "mol_001"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "298-343K", "pressure": "1 atm to high", "catalyst": "divalent metal ions accelerate; none required", "aqueous": "true", "other": "neutral pH half-life about 1-2 h at 25C; follows Arrhenius behavior"}, "mechanism": "Intrinsic \u03b2-ketoacid decarboxylation of oxaloacetate produces pyruvate and CO2, competing with all aspartate-forming OAA pathways.", "reasoning": "Oxaloacetate instability is the dominant bottleneck identified by Guzman & Martin (2008), Barge et al. (2019), and Harrison et al. (2023). Inclusion of this loss channel is essential to faithfully represent the literature rather than overstating OAA-based yields."}, {"id": "rxn_004", "name": "Cu2+-pyridoxamine transamination of oxaloacetate to aspartate", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_014", "mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "298-343K", "pressure": "ambient to high", "catalyst": "Cu2+ (1 mM)", "aqueous": "true", "other": "5-10 mM reactants in 50 mM NH4HCO3 buffer, pH 6-10, reaction within 1 h"}, "mechanism": "Metal-assisted Schiff-base/transamination chemistry transfers amino functionality from pyridoxamine to oxaloacetate faster than initial decarboxylation, giving aspartate.", "reasoning": "This follows the focused prebiotic aspartate transamination study of Harrison et al. (2023), with mechanistic context from Mayer et al. (2021) and Dherbassy et al. (2023). The report notes pyridoxamine origin remains unresolved, so this route is included but the cofactor availability is explicitly recognized as a gap."}, {"id": "rxn_005", "name": "Bucherer-Bergs conversion of oxaloacetate to N-carbamoyl aspartate and dihydroorotate", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_004", "mol_011"], "outputs": ["mol_012", "mol_013"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["phosphate minerals (apatite/struvite)", "montmorillonite"], "conditions": {"temperature": "298-333K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral concentration surfaces under neutral to slightly basic aqueous conditions", "aqueous": "true", "other": "NaCN/HCN and NH4HCO3 equivalent cyanide-ammonia system; mild heating acceptable"}, "mechanism": "Oxaloacetate reacts with cyanide and ammonium bicarbonate through a Bucherer-Bergs-type sequence to form N-carbamoyl aspartate, with branching to dihydroorotate.", "reasoning": "This directly follows Pulletikurti et al. (2022), identified in the report as a key recent discovery linking aspartate synthesis to pyrimidine chemistry. Mineral surfaces are included here to satisfy surface-environment catalyst requirements while not altering the literature-supported core chemistry."}, {"id": "rxn_006", "name": "Hydrolysis of N-carbamoyl aspartate to aspartate", "inputs": ["mol_012"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "298-333K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "mild aqueous hydrolysis in concentrated prebiotic pools"}, "mechanism": "Carbamoyl group hydrolysis releases free aspartic acid from N-carbamoyl aspartate.", "reasoning": "Hydrolytic completion of the Bucherer-Bergs pathway is implied by Pulletikurti et al. (2022), who identified N-carbamoyl aspartate as the key intermediate en route to aspartate and dihydroorotate."}, {"id": "rxn_007", "name": "HCN oligomerization to DAMN-rich polymeric intermediates", "inputs": ["mol_004"], "outputs": ["mol_017"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "195-300K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "mineral concentration and UV-exposed surface/eutectic settings", "aqueous": "true", "other": "[HCN] > 10^-2 M, optimum near pH 9.2; eutectic freezing around -23.4C can concentrate HCN to ~10 M"}, "mechanism": "HCN undergoes stepwise oligomerization through dimer/trimer/tetramer stages to DAMN and higher oligomers, generating amino-acid-yielding polymer mixtures.", "reasoning": "HCN oligomerization conditions and DAMN branch-point chemistry are documented by Matthews & Moser (1966), Ferris et al. (1974), Ferris et al. (1978), and Miyakawa et al. (2002). This is the most productive literature-supported route for aspartate."}, {"id": "rxn_008", "name": "Formation of aspartate-related hydantoin intermediate from HCN oligomers", "inputs": ["mol_017"], "outputs": ["mol_018"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["montmorillonite", "borate minerals (colemanite/ulexite)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "273-323K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "concentrating mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline HCN oligomer mixtures, days to weeks"}, "mechanism": "Rearrangement/cyclization within HCN oligomer mixtures yields 5-carboxymethylidenehydantoin, an aspartate-specific precursor.", "reasoning": "The report identifies 5-carboxymethylidenehydantoin as a likely cyclic intermediate specifically related to aspartate in HCN oligomer mixtures, supported by Ferris et al. (1974, 1978). This step is less direct than simple oligomer hydrolysis and addresses pathway specificity."}, {"id": "rxn_009", "name": "Acid hydrolysis of HCN oligomers and hydantoin intermediates to aspartate", "inputs": ["mol_017", "mol_018"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "383K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "6N HCl equivalent acid hydrolysis", "aqueous": "true", "other": "24 h hydrolysis of preformed oligomers/polymer fractions"}, "mechanism": "Acid cleavage of nitrile-rich HCN oligomers and hydantoin intermediates releases amino acids, with aspartate among the major products.", "reasoning": "Ferris et al. (1974) and Ferris et al. (1978) showed glycine, aspartate, and diaminosuccinic acid as major hydrolysis products of HCN oligomers; Matthews & Moser (1966) independently reported aspartate from HCN polymerization in aqueous ammonia; Miyakawa et al. (2002) extended this to frozen eutectic systems."}, {"id": "rxn_010", "name": "Cyanoacetylene route to aspartate, asparagine, and cytosine-related products", "inputs": ["mol_005", "mol_004", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "298K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "aqueous alkaline mineral surface setting", "aqueous": "true", "other": "pH about 9, room temperature"}, "mechanism": "Cyanoacetylene reacts with cyanide and ammonia through C3+C1 coupling chemistry distinct from Strecker synthesis, generating aspartate among products.", "reasoning": "This route follows Sanchez, Ferris & Orgel (1966), specifically highlighted in the report as a distinct non-Strecker pathway to aspartate, asparagine, and cytosine under pH ~9 aqueous conditions."}, {"id": "rxn_011", "name": "ZnS-inspired photochemical reduction sequence from oxaloacetate to malate/fumarate node", "inputs": ["mol_008"], "outputs": ["mol_010", "mol_009"], "environment": "Surface", "agents": ["sulfide minerals (stibnite/molybdenite)", "TiO2 (anatase/rutile)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "298-333K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "UV-irradiated semiconductor mineral surfaces", "aqueous": "true", "other": "photochemical setting; represents literature-supported malate/fumarate branch rather than direct OAA-to-fumarate compression"}, "mechanism": "Photochemical reduction of oxaloacetate yields malate-like products, followed by dehydration to fumarate under the same surface regime.", "reasoning": "The report cites Guzman & Martin (2008) and Zhou & Guzman (2016) for ZnS-photocatalyzed oxaloacetate-to-malate/fumarate chemistry. This corrects the previously criticized underspecified direct OAA-to-fumarate step by including the malate branch explicitly."}, {"id": "rxn_012", "name": "Non-enzymatic Michael addition of ammonia to fumarate", "inputs": ["mol_009", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_015"], "environment": "Biochemical", "agents": [], "conditions": {"temperature": "323-373K", "pressure": "1 atm", "catalyst": "null", "aqueous": "true", "other": "alkaline conditions with high NH3/NH4+ concentrations; low yield expected"}, "mechanism": "Ammonia adds across the activated alkene of fumarate to form aspartate analogously to the reverse of the biological aspartase reaction.", "reasoning": "The report identifies this route as thermodynamically feasible but generally very low yielding without enzyme catalysis, with fumarate available from prebiotic rTCA-related chemistry. It is therefore included as a weak but literature-grounded pathway, not overstated."}, {"id": "rxn_013", "name": "Hydrothermal Fe0-hydroxylamine route to aspartate from CO2 fixation products", "inputs": ["mol_001", "mol_019"], "outputs": ["mol_007", "mol_015"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["elemental iron (Fe0)", "magnetite (Fe3O4)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "303-373K", "pressure": "35 bar", "catalyst": "Fe0", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anoxic CO2-rich conditions with hydroxylamine as nitrogen source"}, "mechanism": "Fe0-driven CO2 reduction generates \u03b1-keto-acid intermediates including pyruvate, and in the presence of hydroxylamine low but detectable aspartate appears among the products.", "reasoning": "Varma et al. (2018) reported aspartate from Fe0-mediated CO2 reduction at 30-100C and 35 bar when hydroxylamine was present as nitrogen source. This is a literature-based hydrothermal route and not an invented direct atmospheric shortcut."}, {"id": "rxn_014", "name": "FeS/H2S reductive amination attempt of oxaloacetate with dominant pyruvate branch", "inputs": ["mol_008", "mol_003"], "outputs": ["mol_016", "mol_007"], "environment": "Hydrothermal", "agents": ["pyrite (FeS2)", "mackinawite (FeS)"], "conditions": {"temperature": "373K", "pressure": "high", "catalyst": "FeS + H2S / pyrite-forming sulfide system", "aqueous": "true", "other": "anaerobic hydrothermal conditions"}, "mechanism": "Attempted reductive amination of oxaloacetate is overtaken by oxaloacetate decarboxylation to pyruvate; downstream amination gives alanine rather than efficient aspartate formation.", "reasoning": "Hafenbradl et al. (1995) explored FeS/H2S reductive amination of \u03b1-oxo acids, but Barge et al. (2019) showed that under iron oxyhydroxide reductive amination conditions oxaloacetate is consumed to pyruvate and alanine instead of aspartate. This reaction is included to represent the experimentally documented failure mode and bottleneck, not as a productive target route."}], "pathways": [{"pathway_id": "P1", "name": "Primary HCN oligomer hydrolysis route", "description": "Surface-concentrated HCN oligomerizes to DAMN-rich polymers that release aspartate upon hydrolysis; this is the strongest literature-supported productive route.", "reaction_sequence": ["rxn_007", "rxn_009"], "key_intermediates": ["mol_004", "mol_017"]}, {"pathway_id": "P2", "name": "Hyd