  \"rxn_002\"\n      ],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Retain the Bucherer-Bergs to N-carbamoyl aspartate to aspartate core, but improve oxaloacetate generation realism\",\n        \"Specify cyanide source and pH range for Bucherer-Bergs chemistry more explicitly\",\n        \"Avoid implying facile direct hydrothermal OAA accumulation without addressing decarboxylation losses\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P7\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_005\": 0.92,\n        \"rxn_006\": 0.9\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.91,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.94,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.88,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.93,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.92,\n      \"feedback\": \"This is an excellent pathway once oxaloacetate is available. It closely matches the recent literature on the Bucherer-Bergs pathway from oxaloacetate, including N-carbamoyl aspartate and dihydroorotate as coupled products. It is both chemically elegant and highly relevant to prebiotic nucleotide-amino acid network integration. The chief caveat is that OAA supply remains external to this short route.\",\n      \"approved\": true,\n      \"problematic_reactions\": [],\n      \"suggestions\": [\n        \"Keep this as a core high-confidence subnetwork\",\n        \"Clarify ammonium bicarbonate and cyanide stoichiometry in the Bucherer-Bergs step\",\n        \"Add explicit note that OAA instability requires rapid downstream capture\"\n      ]\n    },\n    {\n      \"pathway_id\": \"P8\",\n      \"reaction_scores\": {\n        \"rxn_004\": 0.74\n      },\n      \"chemical_feasibility\": 0.74,\n      \"pathway_coherence\": 0.86,\n      \"environmental_progression\": 0.7,\n      \"target_achievement\": 0.8,\n      \"overall_confidence\": 0.77,\n      \"feedback\": \"This route is literature supported in principle, and Cu2+-pyridoxamine transamination of oxaloacetate to aspartate is one of the most biologically relevant known prebiotic 